<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KlanName     05-07 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Klan Name,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Regent, Students Urges Renaming of Building Named For Klansman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A regent at the University of Oklahoma has
joined a group of students who are pleading with school officials
to change the name of a building named after a former leader of the
Ku Klux Klan.
   ``The time is right for a change,'' the regent, Sylvia Lewis,
said Friday. ``We shouldn't be perpetuating discrimination at one
of our flagship universities.''
   Faculty and student organizations at the university have asked
the regents to change the name of the chemistry building, which was
dedicated in 1917 as Debarr Hall after Edwin DeBarr, one of the
first four professors at Oklahoma.
   DeBarr established the school of pharmacy in 1894 and later the
first school of petroleum engineering. He was a vice president of
the university from 1909 to 1923.
   DeBarr was an Oklahoma grand dragon of the KKK, and in 1924 he
was a national chaplain of the Klan.
   In 1922, the university's regents censured DeBarr for his
involvement with the Klan and he was dismissed from the university
in 1923.
   ``The name is inappropriate,'' said Roland Lehr, acting chairman
of the chemistry department. In recent weeks, students have staged
a protest in front of the building.
   Oklahoma President Frank Horton declined comment on the issue on
Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
