<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     05-07 0810</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Watt says his first foray into
politics since returning to his native Wyoming has been quite
different from his troubled tenure as U.S. secretary of the
interior.
   ``It's been a lot of fun,'' Watt said Friday at the Wyoming
Republican Convention, where he is serving as a delegate.
   The former secretary said attitude is one key distinction
between politics in Wyoming and in Washington.
   ``There is a lot better perspective,'' he said. ``Because the
concern here is for people. There is compassion and understanding
for the concerns of one another. In Washington, it is a power
struggle, group against group, interest against interest.''
   Watt, President Reagan's first interior secretary, quit in 1983
after making remarks considered offensive by many blacks, Jews,
women and the handicapped. He also angered environmentalists, who
considered him pro-development.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Wallace, a mainstay of the long-running CBS
show ``60 Minutes,'' turns 70 Monday as his new five-year contract
goes into effect.
   ``His role will be the same as it has been in the past. He will
principally be a `60 Minutes' correspondent,'' CBS spokesman Roy
Brunett said Friday. No other details of the contract were made
available.
   Wallace, who has won numerous Emmy, duPont and Peabody awards,
will be feted by his colleagues on his birthday.
   He began his broadcast career in the 1940s and has spent about
25 years at CBS. Wallace is the only correspondent to have been
with the top-ranked show since its debut on Sept. 24, 1968.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Math instructor Jaime Escalante has been
getting a lot of attention since his exceptional teaching was
profiled in the film ``Stand and Deliver,'' and he says it hasn't
been good for his students.
   Vice President George Bush, stumping Thursday for the GOP
presidential nomination, was the latest to drop by Garfield High
School.
   Escalante, played in the film by Edward James Olmos, says the
droves of reporters and visiting dignitaries have upset his
teaching routine.
   ``It's distracting, and the kids are paying for it,'' Escalante
said.
   The surprise showing Escalante's students made on an advanced
placement calculus exam in 1982 gave the school a reputation for
training underprivileged students in math.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire industrialist Armand
Hammer has apparently ended an effort to collect $760,000 from the
estate of his brother.
   Victor Hammer, a Palm Beach resident and founder of New York's
renowned Hammer Galleries, died in 1985 and his brother was named
co-executor of the $1.5 million estate.
   Hammer, 88, chairman of Occidental Petroleum Corp., later filed
suit against the estate, claiming Victor never repaid loans made to
him between 1983 and 1985.
   Nancy Eilan, Victor Hammer's adopted daughter, sought
unsuccessfully to have Armand Hammer removed as co-executor.
   All issues were resolved April 12, when the parties, including
Victor Hammer's son, Armasha, a resident of the Soviet Union,
agreed to split the estate.
   Armand Hammer's portion is not specified in the agreement, but
it is not expected to equal his $760,000 request, his attorney, D.
Culver Smith, told The Fort Lauderdale News in a story published
Friday.
   Eilan's attorney, James Pressly, would not comment on the
settlement.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Justice Department is probing
Sylvester Stallone's production company as part of a grand jury
investigation of the Teamsters union's influence in the
entertainment industry, Daily Variety reported.
   The newspaper's unidentified sources said Stallone's White Eagle
company was not the focus of the investigation, but the government
is interested in the company's relationship with labor and studio
consultant Marty Bacow.
   The Justice Department, which subpoenaed records of Stallone's
company, also was looking into the relationship between Bacow, the
Teamsters and other unidentified Hollywood production companies,
Variety said Thursday.
   ``Let them keep fishing,'' Bacow told Variety. ``I haven't done
anything wrong.''
   Stallone attorney Steve Wehner declined to comment.
   Bacow's relationship with Stallone goes back to 1983, when Bacow
served as a consultant for the movie ``Rhinestone.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Shepard, America's first man in space, says
the Challenger space shuttle disaster may have been an ironic
result of the space agency's spectacular success in its effort to
put astronauts on the moon.
   ``NASA became overloaded, too successful. They did too good a
job,'' Shepard said in a speech marking the 27th anniversary of his
brief ride into space May 5, 1961.
   ``If, 30 years ago, we had said that we were only going to have
two incidents when we had fatalities, all of us would have said, `I
just hope we are that lucky,''' Shepard, now a businessman, told
the Rotary Club of Houston on Thursday.
   Seven crew members died when Challenger exploded in 1986, and
three astronauts died in a 1967 fire at the Kennedy Space Center
during a training exercise.
</TEXT>
