<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     05-07 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Testing In Ag Department To Emphasize Limited Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A little more than 3 percent of the 105,000
employees of the Agriculture Department nationwide will be checked
in the government's opening round of random drug testing among
federal workers.
   But Gerald Oakley of the department's Office of Finance and
Management said the 3,354 employees working at ``designated
positions'' in USDA will represent only the absolute minimum to be
tested initially.
   Under rules cleared by the Department of Health and Human
Services, the USDA program includes provisions that will allow
supervisors to request testing of workers under ``reasonable
suspicion'' of using drugs. Also, employees may voluntarily undergo
testing.
   The drugs listed by USDA in its testing program include
marijuana, cocaine, PCP, opiates and amphetamines. Officials
estimated the cost of the testing program at $1.6 million the first
year.
   Oakley and others said in interviews this week following the
unveiling of random drug testing plans by dozens of federal
agencies, that no serious objections have been raised so far by
USDA employee unions.
   ``Generally, the positions (to be tested) are high-level
employees or people with top-secret clearances, or people who have
special exposure _ at the U.S. borders or in security work,'' he
said. ``These people will be tested.''
   Oakley added: ``There might be others who might be tested, too.
We have no way of knowing, but I would think it would not be a very
large number.''
   Would a lone Forest Service employee in a fire tower be a
candidate for drug testing? Or a chicken inspector working in a
plant?
   ``Probably not, but it's possible, depending on whether the
Forest Service (or appropriate agency) selected the position as one
designated for testing,'' Oakley said. ``There was no intent to
pick a particular agency and focus on them.''
   High-level political appointees will not be exempt, not even
Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng and his aides, if it is
determined those jobs should be checked out.
   Drug testing in some federal agencies will involve a much larger
percentage of their employees. At the Defense Department, for
example, as many as 20 percent may be tested eventually.
   The initial USDA testing of around 3 percent of its employees is
relatively low because the department has so few highly sensitive
jobs, at least not in the same league with the Pentagon, State or
the White House.
   But Oakley said USDA deals with ``certain economic security
factors'' such as massive crop reports that could have an impact on
the nation's economy if leaked prematurely. Details of new farm
programs are other examples.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World sugar production in 1988-89 is forecast
at a record 104.1 million metric tons, up slightly from a revised
production of 103.6 million tons in 1987-88, the Agriculture
Department says.
   The department's first forecast for the coming year included
65.9 million tons of cane sugar, up 1 percent from 1987-88, and
38.2 million tons from sugar beets, down 1 percent.
   Tonnage was expressed in raw sugar equivalents. A metric ton is
about 2,205 pounds.
   According to the department's Foreign Agricultural Service,
which released the forecast, production in the European Economic
Community, which accounts for 13 percent of the global output, may
decline 2 percent in 1988-89 to about 13.8 million tons because of
``a return to more normal yields and a 1 percent decline in area to
be harvested.''
   Sugar production in the Soviet Union, the largest producer, was
forecast at 9.7 million tons, down 1 percent from last year's
revised output of 9.8 million tons.
   In Brazil, the third-ranking producer, production may be 8.4
million tons, down 1 percent from last season's revised total of
8.5 million tons, the report said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Want to contact the Leafy Greens Council? Or
the American Tarentaise Association?
   One source of information is a new reference book about
agriculture recently put on the market by Agricultural Resources &
Communications Inc., a private firm located in Washington, D.C.
   The 255-page volume, Directory of American Agriculture, is
described by the company as ``the first time all the people and
organizations who make up the world of American agriculture have
been compiled in one cohesive, organized fashion.''
   But the premier edition also notes that some names ``may be
missing, largely because some have failed to respond to our
inquiries.''
   Editor Judy Taggart said the book _ which doesn't carry
advertising _ includes lists of state and national agricultural
organizations, along with their officers, addresses and phone
numbers.
   The directory sells for $45 and can be ordered from:
Agricultural Resources & Communications Inc., 1000 Connecticut Ave.
NW, Suite 202, Washington, D.C. 20036.
   Oh, yes, the Leafy Greens Council's address is Box 76067, St.
Paul, Minn. 55175. Phone 612 222-3232.
   According to the directory, the council is ``a commodity
supplier, service, promotional and communications group that
promotes and provides consumer information for leafy greens via
supermarket and food service channels.''
   The American Tarentaise Association is at P.O. Box 446,
Reedpoint, Mont. 59069. Phone 406 326-2100. It ``registers and
promotes Tarentaise cattle,'' the directory said.
