<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     05-07 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ballet Has Four New Dances in One Evening</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three fascinating dances and one very pretty
confection, all of them new, make up one of the programs of the New
York City Ballet's three-week American Music Festival.
   On Friday night, ``Space,'' choreographed by Laura Dean to music
by Steve Reich, received the most applause. A large corps de
ballet, dancing wonderfully, fills the stage space at the New York
State Theater. Sometimes their movement across the stage, by spins,
steps, kicks and spins, looks haphazard, while at other times the
dancers move in rows or groups of three.
   The four principals don't have major solos as in most ballets.
More often they dance around a square formed by a spotlight or
dance surrounded by the corps. Miss Dean, artistic director of
Laura Dean Dancers and Musicians since 1976, likes to have
individual dancers spin. In ``Space'' it was as hypnotic as the
music.
   Peter Martin's ``The Waltz Project'' shows a sure choreographic
hand. The music _ 13 waltzes, none traditional, by 13 composers _
is played by pianist Jerry Zimmerman.
   The first, danced by four couples, has broken, repeated phrases,
and many rests. Diana White seemed to swim on David Otto's hip in
Joan Tower's ``Red Garnet Waltz.'' Martins was particularly
inventive entwining Helene Alexopoulos and Jeppe Mydtskov _ though
it was more acrobatics than dancing _ to Philip Glass' ``Modern
Love Waltz.''
   Heather Watts and Jock Soto in leotards _ a sign that the ballet
will be very modern _ danced Richard Tanner's ``Sonatas and
Interludes.'' John Cage composed the music in 1960 for prepared
piano. Tanner, artistic director of the Pennsylvania Ballet since
1984, choreogaphed the ballet duet for the Eglevsky Ballet in 1982.
It's neoclassic at base, angular and interesting.
   The evening began with ``Woodland Sketches,'' choreographed by
Rogert La Fosse, company member since 1986, to nine tunes by Edward
McDowell. The first was his famous ``To a Wild Rose.'' The music is
sweetly old-fashioned and the dance and costumes depict romance at
the idyllic stage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0145EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SeeingJustice Bjt   05-07 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seeing Justice, Bjt,0669</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lady Justice Gets A Facelift But Keeps Eyes Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIRGINIA CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She's a grande dame who came from New
York to witness the last days of the historic Comstock Lode gold
rush that helped build the West.
   The crowned Lady Justice arrived in 1877, barefoot, robed,
scales in hand and serene eyes unobscured by the traditional
blindfold, to oversee a new $117,000 courthouse where miners came
to answer charges of trespassing, claim jumping, thieving and
murder.
   Now, for the first time in 111 years, the 7-foot symbol of
justice has left her second-floor perch overlooking Virginia City,
the historic mining town that attracts thousands of tourists each
year.
   She's getting a face and body lift to restore the golden-bronze
color and luster lost after her Nevada arrival, which coincided
with the last rich and glorious days of the Comstock Lode.
   ``We're not going to put a blindfold on her, though; That's the
best thing about her,'' said sculptor Greg Melton, who is doing the
restoration. ``I think I'm even starting to fall in love with her.
I'll have a hard time giving her back to Virginia City.''
   But Lady Justice wasn't always the object of affection, says Ron
James, a state historian.
   ``Underneath she was made of zinc, which is just about the
ugliest of metals,'' James said recently. ``Then she got to looking
really bad in the 1940s.
   ``They painted her with silver skin and a rust-colored robe.
Soon it was flaking off and she looked like a leper. One of her
scales even fell off. It was a shame because she really is
beautiful.''
   The statue is scheduled to be rededicated on May 15, taking her
place once again above the town that Mark Twain helped make famous
with his blend of fact and fiction as a reporter for the
Territorial Enterprise in the early 1860s.
   Melton, whose bronze statue of Comstock mining and engineering
pioneer Adolph Sutro stands beside the state capitol in Carson
City, will paint the Lady Justice an almost golden bronze color
just as she was originally.
   ``She had a lot of cracks and she'd been beat up because of
weather conditions,'' the 41-year-old sculptor said. ``She's in
pretty bad shape, but not bad enough that I can't fix her.
   ``I give the restoration a 100-year guarantee. If after 100
years it collapses I'll come back and fix it. I guarantee all my
work.''
   The Virginia City Justice is one of only about 20 statues in the
U.S. without a blindfold, according to James, who is deputy state
historic preservation officer.
   ``She was ordered from a catalog for $203 and she could be
picked with or without the blindfold; It was just a matter of
taste,'' James said. ``I guess the people in Virginia City thought
justice might be intrinsically better if she could see both sides.
It seems to make sense.''
   The Lady Justice was brought to Virginia City as part of an
ambitious rebuilding project after three-quarters of the town 25
miles southeast of Reno was destroyed in the Great Fire of 1875.
   ``The city fathers were faced with the question of what to do
with the community after the fire,'' James said. ``They chose to
rebuild it in grand style.
   The state Comstock Historic District Commission, which James
oversees, is paying $2,800 for the restoration. The hollow statue
will be filled with ``letters to the future'' as a sort of time
capsule.
   James said people will be charged $25 to have a single-page
letter placed inside the Lady Justice. The money will go toward the
restoration of another historic project, the 111-year-old Fourth
Ward School in Virginia City.
   ``I hope she'll turn out just like when she was first put up,''
James said. ``She'll look at the sunrise each day and shine like
she used to. She deserves it.''
</TEXT>
