<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SecondChance     05-07 0745</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Second Chance,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Life's A Challenge For Suicide Survivor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 3rd graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OGV1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OGDEN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Polfreyman expected to die in 1980 when
he tucked the muzzle of a rifle under his chin and pulled the
trigger. But the bullet he hoped would obliterate his life instead
gave it new meaning.
   ``Life's now a challenge for me. I find happiness in a
challenge,'' said Polfreyman, who was blinded and disfigured by the
suicide attempt.
   The bullet severed his optic nerve, tore his lips and facial
cartilage, ripped his cheeks away and destroyed his sinuses and
palate. That it did not hit his brain before exiting between his
eyes he attributes to a ``higher power.''
   Today, Polfreyman, 25, is working on a history teaching degree
at Weber State College here, where his lanky figure is a familiar
sight as he strides across campus with Handy, his seeing-eye dog,
and Kris Porter, his girlfriend. Polfreyman hopes to work with
handicapped students after he graduates.
   ``I'm in a world that to me is so much nicer,'' he said. ``I see
people for who they are, not for what they have on. I see their
heart. A person is so much nicer when seen from the heart.''
   The world Polfreyman saw while growing up was not so nice. His
parents separated when he was in 10th grade, and living with his
father didn't work out.
   Handsome, artistic and above-average in intelligence, he was
bored, rambunctious and rebellious. ``If I was told by an authority
figure to do something, I'd do the opposite,'' he said.
   Jean Elmer, Polfreyman's mother, has remarried and lives in
Knightstown, Ind. She remembers that when she complained about her
son's grades, he vowed to make the honor roll. He did, but the
challenge was gone and he lapsed back to C's and D's. And he drank.
   ``I don't remember a lot of high school from being drunk,'' he
said.
   Polfreyman, the eldest of four boys, said his family was unaware
of his inner turmoil.
   Polfreyman lived in Denver for a time and in a foster home back
in Utah. During his senior year in high school he fought often,
hurting three students ``pretty bad,'' and eventually dropped out,
he said.
   ``One morning I woke up and decided I had lost complete control
of my life and there was no way I could go back,'' he said. ``I
didn't have a challenge in life or a goal that was not achievable.
It was too easy.''
   Deciding suicide was his only option, he left home to spend his
last week with friends in Denver. A note left for his mother said
simply, ``Mom, I've got something important to do. I love you.''
   When he ran out of money he drove to a field outside the city.
He wrote another note.
   ``I'm sorry for what I'm about to do,'' he wrote. ``(But) I
didn't die sad. I was quite happy.''
   A former Vietnam War medic just happened to be in the same field
trying out a new Jeep. He administered first aid and used his CB
radio to call for help.
   Polfreyman survived. His first conscious thought was that he was
blind. ``It was a peaceful feeling,'' he said.
   ``After I got out of the hospital I tried to find God to thank
him,'' said Polfreyman, who first became active in the Mormon
Church of his youth and later became a Seventh-day Adventist. ``I
am very much into what I call a higher power.''
   Adjusting to life without sight was difficult, but emotional
adjustments took even longer.
   ``The boy I used to call Johnny died,'' Mrs. Elmer said. ``The
boy who lives now I call JT. They're nothing alike. JT is more
independent and self-motivated. Johnny was more loving. He needed
love and gave more.''
   Polfreyman endured some 20 operations to restore his face,
several of which failed. Bone from his ankle was used to rebuild
his nose, but a four-inch depression in the left side of his
forehead remains, and now is covered by curly brown hair. Infection
forced doctors to remove a plate they had implanted over the spot.
   His cheeks, however, defied doctors' expectations and grew back.
   Mother and son attribute divine intervention to his survival and
the ``little miracles'' that have shaped his recovery.
   ``He has so much to give now that he didn't before,'' said Mrs.
Elmer. ``Only because he didn't know he had it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
