<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0237EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Caliguiri     05-07 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Caliguiri,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pittsburgh Mayor Dies of Rare Disease</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Richard S. Caliguiri, the city's chief
executive for more than a decade, died of heart failure at age 56
on the day he was scheduled to meet with doctors to discuss a
possible heart transplant.
   ``He was the kindest of men and always thought the best of
others,'' said City Council President Sophie Masloff, 70, who was
sworn in as mayor Friday about seven hours after Caliguiri's death.
   Mrs. Masloff, a Democrat, becomes the city's first woman mayor.
She will complete Caliguiri's term, which expires in January 1990,
and retain her council seat. She said she would carry out
Caliguiri's policies.
   Meanwhile, friends, associates and even former political foes of
the late mayor praised him Friday.
   Gov. Robert Casey ordered flags on state property flown at
half-staff Friday and called the late mayor ``a vibrant force for
the good of our people, our state and our nation.''
   ``His death is a tragic loss, not only to the family he loved so
deeply, but to the city that has been his life's work,'' said U.S.
Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa.
   Lynn Williams, president of the United Steelworkers, which is
based in Pittsburgh, described Caliguiri as ``a man of vision and
compassion'' who was ``committed to efforts to revitalize the many
communities in this region that have been buffeted by economic
turmoil.''
   One of Caliguiri's frequent adversaries, Councilwoman Michelle
Madoff, said she remained a friend of the mayor despite their
disagreements and added, ``He didn't have a mean bone in his body.''
   The mayor's wife, Jeanne, called for an ambulance just after
midnight Friday when she noticed her husband was pale and she could
not awaken him, said Dr. James O'Toole, Caliguiri's cardiologist.
   Paramedics worked for 1{ hours to resuscitate him, but the mayor
never regained consciousness and was declared dead at Shadyside
Hospital at 1:36 a.m., officials said.
   Caliguiri, a popular Democrat, suffered from amyloidosis, a rare
disorder that deposits protein in the heart, kidneys and other
major organs. The deposits stiffened his heart. Doctors inserted a
pacemaker to stabilize an irregular heart beat in December and were
considering a transplant.
   A meeting had been planned Friday ``to discuss the timing'' of a
possible transplant, said Dr. Joel Weinberg, one of the mayor's
physicians.
   Caliguiri went to work Thursday, and though he was visibly
growing weaker, doctors, friends and colleagues said his death was
unexpected.
   ``We would have expected a slightly more gradual downhill
course,'' O'Toole said.
   Caliguiri was sworn in April 10, 1977. He is credited with
helping shift Pittsburgh from its dependence on the steel industry
to a progressive, technically oriented city of 365,000 people. The
turnaround earned Pittsburgh national recognition.
   Caliguiri became a director of the Pittsburgh Pirates through
his efforts to keep the major league baseball team in the city
after it was offered for sale three years ago. A consortium of
business leaders bought the team in 1985, ensuring it would remain
for at least five years.
   The Pirates saluted Caliguiri in a brief memorial before Friday
night's home game. Church bells also were rung throughout the city
at 7 p.m. in honor of the late mayor.
   In addition to his wife, Caliguiri is survived by two sons.
   Visitors will be received at H. Samson Funeral Home tonight and
Sunday. The mayor's body then will be moved to the City County
Building for a viewing Monday.
   Mass of Christian burial will be celebrated Tuesday morning at
St. Paul's Cathedral. Burial will be private. The site was not
disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
