<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Kuwait-Blast     05-07 0163</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Blast,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Blast In Two Weeks In Downtown Kuwait</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion ripped through a downtown Kuwait
complex that houses airlines offices early Saturday and appeared to
have caused considerable damage, residents said.
   It could not immediately be determined whether there were any
injuries in the 7:23 a.m. (12:23 a.m. EDT) explosion, which
occurred about an hour before offices open.
   At least one ambulance was heard rushing in the direction of the
blast, which was a block away from offices of Saudi Arabia's
national airlines that were bombed less that two weeks ago.
   That explosion, which the government said was caused by a time
bomb, injured a guard and severely damaged the ground-floor offices.
   Kuwait, the country closest ot the Iran-Iraq war front, has in
recent months been the target of several such bombings _ and a
hijacking.
   The incidents are widely believed to have been masterminded by
Iran, which accuses Kuwait of aiding Iraq in their 7{-year-old war.
</TEXT>
