<DOCNO> AP880507-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Elections     05-07 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Elections,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Campaign Ends in With Joy Over Releases, But Political
Bickering</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the eve of Sunday's presidential runoff,
Socialist leaders claimed politics had a role in the freeing this
week of Frenchmen held captive in Lebanon and New Caledonia. Still,
the releases brought joy.
   Campaigning is prohibited today.
   Socialist President Francois Mitterrand and Conservative Premier
Jacques Chirac staged final rallies Friday in the south.
   Chirac basked in the release in Beirut Wednesday after three
years in captivity of Marcel Fontaine, 45, Marcel Carton, 62, and
Jean-Paul Kauffmann, 44, and in the freeing Thursday of 23 French
lawmen held by Melanesian separatists in New Caledonia.
   The release from exile Friday of a French spy convicted in the
1985 sinking of the Greenpeace ship Rainbow Warrior was another
dose of good news for Chirac supporters.
   It wasn't clear how the hostage releases would affect Chirac's
chances in the runoff, because polls are forbidden in the final
week of the campaign. Most political analysts felt any benefits
would be insufficient to overcome the wide lead held by Mitterrand
in the final opinion surveys last week.
   Mitterrand, seeking a second seven-year term, said he welcomed
the hostage releases and made no insinuations about his opponent.
   But Lionel Jospin, first secretary of the Socialist Party,
claimed Friday that Chirac ``and his team is working public opinion
with force in a formidable attempt to manipulate the end of the
campaign.''
   Chirac rejected allegations that his actions were motivated by
the elections. He said it was ``my duty to do everything possible,
even if it could lead to critical comments, to get the last
(French) hostages out of Lebanon.''
   Jacques Toubon, secretary-general of Chirac's Rally for the
Republic party, denounced what he called the ``wet blankets, the
grumblers who split hairs when they should simply be happy.''
   The last polls indicated Mitterrand was favored by 53 percent to
57 percent of voters, compared to Chirac's 43 percent to 47 percent
rating.
   The men advanced to the runoff by being the top two vote-getters
in the first round of voting April 24. In that vote, Mitterrand won
34.1 percent of the vote and Chirac received 19.9 percent.
   Mitterrand named Chirac premier in 1986 after the Conservatives
and an allied party won a slim majority in the National Assembly.
   In Paris' central Place de la Concorde, 40,000 Chirac backers
gathered Friday for a final outpouring of support.
   ``France needs a president who decides,'' Interior Minister
Charles Pasqua told the crowd. ``When it was necessary to decide
for the liberation of hostages in Lebanon, Chirac knew how to
decide. When it was necessary to decide to free the hostages in New
Caledonia, Chirac knew how to decide.''
   On Thursday morning, French security forces stormed a cave in
the French island territory of New Caledonia, freeing 23 hostages.
Two assault team members and 19 Melanesian separatist kidnappers
were killed.
   On Friday, the government announced that Capt. Dominique Prieur,
one of two French agents convicted in New Zealand of the 1985
bombing of an anti-nuclear Greenpeace ship, had been allowed to
leave her island exile for France.
   Chirac said she was freed because she is pregnant.
   Ms. Prieur and the other agent, who has already returned to
France, were convicted of manslaughter in the bombing, which killed
a photographer aboard the Rainbow Warrior.
   Ten-year New Zealand prison terms for the two were suspended
under a U.N.-sponsored agreement provided the two remained in exile
on a French Pacific atoll.
   New Zealand complained that the return to France violated
international law.
   The left-leaning newspaper Le Monde said it was difficult to
believe that Mrs. Prieur's condition required that she be brought
back to France just 48 hours before the election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0030 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     05-07 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>D'Amato Says Biaggi Wasn't Reason He Helped Wedtech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato says his intercession with
the Pentagon on behalf of Wedtech Corp. had nothing to do with Rep.
Mario Biaggi, although the congressman had asked him to lobby for
the company.
   D'Amato, called as a prosecution witness at the federal
racketeering trial of Biaggi and six others Friday, conceded that
he or his staff wrote and called Army and Small Business
Administration officials on behalf of Wedtech, a now-bankrupt
defense contractor in the South Bronx.
   D'Amato, who has not been accused of any wrongdoing, also said
Biaggi, D-N.Y., had contacted him as many as eight times on
Wedtech's behalf.
   But under questioning by Biaggi's defense lawyer, the New York
Republican said he felt Wedtech was being treated unfairly and, at
the time, thought he was helping a local business in an
economically deprived area.
   ``And you would have done that if you never met Mario Biaggi?''
asked the lawyer, James LaRossa.
   ``That is correct,'' said D'Amato.
   Prosecutors charge that Biaggi, a Bronx Democrat, extorted cash
and stock from Wedtech in return for his influence on Capitol Hill.
The government contends that Biaggi, working through his former law
partner Bernard Ehrlich, enlisted D'Amato and the late Rep. Joseph
Addabbo, a powerful Queens Democrat, to help Wedtech obtain no-bid
defense contracts.
   Asked if he would have helped Wedtech if he knew Biaggi held
stock in the company, D'Amato replied, ``I don't know. I think it
would've given me pause to reflect. I just don't know.''
   D'Amato said he appointed Ehrlich, formerly a general in the New
York National Guard, as his unpaid military consultant and hired
Ehrlich's daughter as a press aide.
   D'Amato also testified that he arranged a White House meeting
through a top aide of then-presidential counselor Edwin Meese among
Army, SBA and Wedtech officials to help Wedtech obtain a
multimillion dollar small engine contract. The Army had been
opposed to giving Wedtech the contract.
   Asked by Assistant U.S. Attorney Edward J.M. Little if Wedtech
got the Army contract after that meeting, D'Amato replied,
``Essentially, yes.''
   On cross examination by LaRossa, D'Amato said that his office
prided itself on helping constituent companies cut through red
tape. He also said he assisted Wedtech because he believed the
company was not being treated fairly by the Army.
   Later, D'Amato said under questioning by Little that the only
other time Biaggi had sought his assistance on behalf of a military
contractor was for a Brooklyn ship repair company, Coastal Dry Dock
and Repair Corp.
   Biaggi's involvement with Coastal Dry Dock led to his conviction
last year for taking an unlawful gratuity. Biaggi, who was
sentenced to 30 months, is free pending appeal.
   Prosecutors contend Biaggi, Ehrlich and some of the other
defendants helped Wedtech illegally obtain SBA approval to
participate in a program that set aside no-bid government contracts
for minority-controlled businesses.
   There are no allegations of wrongdoing by Addabbo.
</TEXT>
