<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-CopterCrash     05-07 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Copter Crash,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Air Force Helicopter Crashes; Two Killed, Seven Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British air force helicopter
taxiing at an air show hit a loading ramp and burst into flames,
killing two people and seriously injuring at least seven, officials
said.
   Air show visitors ran for cover Friday after the rear rotor of a
U.S.-made Chinook helicopter crashed into the ramp about 15 feet
above the ground.
   ``It was like a bad dream, like a bomb went off,'' said a woman
who identified herself as Caren Niewisch, 27, of Los Angeles.
``Panic broke out. People fell and tried to get away.''
   The crash set off several explosions aboard the helicopter,
officials said.
   One explosion blew off one of the legs of a British soldier
guiding the helicopter to its parking position, the Royal Air Force
said.
   The two who died and three of the injured were aboard the
helicopter, airport officials said.
   The officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
``numerous others'' on the ground had slighter injuries from flying
debris.
   British military officials were investigating the accident. The
helicopter was based in an air base at Guetersloh, about 65 miles
southwest of Hanover.
   Ms. Niewisch said she had come to the air show with a man who
identified himself as Marcus Fontaine, also of Los Angeles.
   The couple escaped without injuries.
   Fontaine, who said he was a pilot, said he believed the accident
was not caused by pilot error.
   ``It wasn't the pilot's fault,'' he said. ``The man on the
ground underestimated the radius of the rotor blades in the turn.''
   Officials said flames shot up more than 25 feet in the air and
it took fire crews more than 30 minutes to extinguish the blaze.
   The accident occurred shortly after the day's air show
activities had concluded, but crowds were milling around the
exhibitions, officials said.
   More than 420 exhibitors from 16 countries are participating in
the air show, which opened Wednesday.
</TEXT>
