<1ST_LINE>r w PM-HeatCost     05-07 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heat Cost,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Heat: A Tiny Saving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heating costs averaged $648.54 per household
last winter, the government reports.
   The figure is 56 cents below normal for the winter, the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration said in its seasonal climate
impact summary.
   The summary, released Friday, estimated Americans spent a total
of $46.6 billion on heating from October through April. That total
was $40 million less than would have been expected if winter
conditions had been the same as the average of the last 20 years.
   Households with oil heat spent about $4 more during the winter
than normal, but that was balanced by savings for those using gas
and electricity for heat, the NOAA climatologists reported.
   Costs varied considerably from place to place, depending on
region.
   Here is a regional rundown of the winter season heating cost for
a typical home, and the difference from what would be been expected
in average winter conditions:
   _Middle Atlantic: $892.86, $6.35 more than normal. Includes New
York, New Jersey and Pennsylvania.
   _New England: $795.12, $4.88 more than normal. Includes Maine,
Vermont, New Hampshire, Massachusetts, Connecticut and Rhode Island.
   _East North Central: $749.63, $2.92 above normal. Includes
Wisconsin, Michigan, Illinois, Indiana and Ohio.
   _East South Central: $671.05, $10.53 above normal. Includes
Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi and Alabama.
   _West North Central: $626.42, $7.55 below normal. Includes North
Dakota, South Dakota, Minnesota, Nebraska, Iowa, Kansas and
Missouri.
   _Mountain: $608.57, $17.14 below normal. Includes Montana,
Idaho, Wyoming, Nevada, Colorado, Utah, Arizona and New Mexico.
   _South Atlantic: $584.07, $12.39 above normal. Includes
Maryland, Delaware, District of Columbia, West Virginia, Virginia,
North Carolina, South Carolina, Georgia and Florida.
   _West South Central: $419.18, $8.22 above normal. Includes
Oklahoma, Arkansas, Texas and Louisiana.
   _Pacific: $400.00, $29.52 below normal. Includes Washington,
Oregon and California.
   The climate impact assessments do not include heating cost
estimates for Alaska or Hawaii.
</TEXT>
