<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CapitolFire 1stLd-Writethru   05-07 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Capitol Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru,440</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 1st graf to change amount of damage done by fire</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fire In Wright's Office Touches Off Debate Over Capitol Safety</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $120,000 fire in the office of House Speaker
Jim Wright has sparked a debate over the safety of congresssional
buildings.
   Elliott Carroll, executive assistant to Capitol Architect George
M. White, said Friday that the congressional buildings are made of
stone and brick and are ``as safe as any place in the world.''
   But Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a former fire chief whose office is
next to Wright's, says there should be stricter fire safety
standards for all federal buildings.
   The issue came up after a small electrical fire Thursday evening
damaged a kitchenette in the office of Wright, D-Texas, in the
Longworth House Office Building.
   The fire broke out about 6 p.m. on the second-floor suite that
houses Wright's district staff in a building across the street from
the Capitol. Carroll said the fire started in a copying machine in
the kitchenette.
   Weldon complained Thursday night and Friday morning that the
fire, which lasted 10 minutes, could have been contained more
quickly had there been fire hoses in hall cabinets and alarms in
the offices.
   Weldon said the fire points to the need for Congress and the
federal government to come under the national fire standards that
govern the buildings of private industry.
   ``We need one set of standards, all over,'' Weldon told
reporters. ``The federal government should accept no federal
standards less than they require of private businesses downtown.''
   He said the Longworth building lacks closed stairways, fire
alarms and smoke detectors in addition to fire hoses.
   Carroll denied that Congress had once again exempted itself from
legislation it has passed for everyone else in the nation, such as
the civil rights, occupational safety and health and minimum wage
laws.
   He said the congressional complex is exempt from District of
Columbia fire regulations, not by a law but because all federal
buildings are exempt from local fire codes.
   However, he said, the Capitol Hill buildings would meet the D.C.
code and they ``meet and exceed'' the national standard.
   Carroll also said the architect's office has begun a $47.5
million modernization program to make the buildings safer against
fire, especially with the installation of voice fire alarms and
smoke detectors.
   ``All these buildings are fireproof,'' said Carroll. ``The
modernization program will make them safer.''
   Weldon remained unconvinced, saying he would move as quickly as
possible to enact legislation to require that fire safety standards
apply to all federal buildings.
   ``It should come quickly,'' he said. ``It's a wonder the
government hasn't been caught with its pants down previously.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
