<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   05-07 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Bush Refers To Jackson As ``Hustler From Chicago''
^By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush wound up three days of campaigning in
the West by referring to Democrat Jesse Jackson as a ``hustler from
Chicago'' and saying he was ``troubled by some of the allegations''
against Attorney General Edwin Meesee III.
   Democratic front-runner Michael Dukakis, meanwhile, added to his
``super delegate'' totals by picking up the endorsement of six
Democratic governors. Jackson was crisscrossing California in
pursuit of the 314 delegates at stake in the season-ending primary
June 7.
   ``I'm not going to be out-hustled by the hustler from Chicago or
from that traditional liberal Democrat from Massachusetts,'' Bush
told a group of Republicans during a stop in Lincoln, Neb., on
Friday.
   The all-but-certain Republican nominee, making a clear reference
to Jackson, who has a home in Chicago, and the Massachusetts
governor, also promised he'd be back.
   Bush spokesman Stephen Hart said there was ``nothing
derogatory'' in Bush's comments. The vice president ``was talking
about how hard he (Jackson) has hustled,'' said Hart.
   ``Bush is just trying to sound tough,'' said Jackson as he left
a fund-raiser in San Francisco. ``He's petrified at the thought of
having to face me in a series of debates. So he's already whining.
   ``I do not know the context of his statement, but that type of
name-calling is beneath the dignity of the vice president of this
country.''
   In an effort to head off the controversy that plagued him during
the New York primary, the first in a recent series of 2-1 Dukakis
primary victories, Jackson has set a May 18 meeting with about 100
Jewish leaders in Los Angeles.
   Dukakis gained the endorsements of the six governors while he
took a break from campaigning to handle some statehouse business in
Boston and have a private weekend with his wife, Kitty.
   The endorsement was announced by Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton, who
has been mentioned as a possible running mate for Dukakis.
   Clinton said he and the other five governors _ Cecil Andrus of
Idaho, Steve Cowper of Alaska, Ted Schwinden of Montana, George
Sinner of North Dakota and Michael Sullivan of Wyoming _ had
withheld their endorsements until now to avoid the appearance of a
stop-Jackson movement.
   Dukakis also got signals from from Sen. John Glenn of Ohio, a
former astronaut and himself a 1984 presidential candidate, that he
was available as a running mate if Dukakis wanted him. Glenn said
he was not campaigning for the job but that he would be glad to
``sit down and discuss it.''
   Earlier in the day Bush, trying to counteract comments by aides
depicting Meese as a liability, told reporters in Iowa he hadn't
``authorized anything.''
   ``I know him well, favorably, but I must say I am troubled by
some of the allegations,'' Bush said of Meese. ``I think fair play
dictates that the system go forward and make the determination.''
   Meese, who denies any wrongdoing, has been the subject of
several investigations by an independent counsel for almost a year.
The attorney general has said he doesn't intend to resign, and Bush
has never urged him to do so.
   But recent comments by Bush aides, reported in the Detroit News,
have provided Democrats with campaign ammunition and turned Meese
into a political embarrassment in the eyes of some Republican
strategists.
   ``Meese is a liability,'' Peter Teeley, Bush's communications
director, told the newspaper.
   ``What a guy like Meese does is take away the opportunity to
discuss the issues that you really want to discuss,'' Teeley said.
``I mean, you are consistently asked about Meese's problems, how
you deal with it, how you stand, one thing or another, and that
just totally diverts attention from the message that you are trying
to get across.''
   And senior campaign adviser Robert Teeter said in interviews in
Washington this week: ``All things considered, you would rather not
have that problem going on right now.''
</TEXT>
