<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru   05-07 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru,720</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Changes dateline; Tops with 4 grafs, picks up pvs 2nd graf
bgng ``California has ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jackson Goes His Last Lap In Delegate-Rich California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson is barnstorming across
California, hammering home his anti-drug message, beseeching voters
to shun reports that Michael Dukakis has the Democratic
presidential nomination sewn up and making a pitch for party unity.
   In a speech to a $500 per person get-out-the-vote fundraiser,
featuring celebrities and top California Democrats Jackson made an
impassioned plea for party unity but did not mention his recent
complaint about the delegate selection process.
   ``I really want to win in November but the party must win and
the nation must be saved,'' he said.
   Jackson focused his speech to the more than 1,000 dinnergoers on
the need to expand the Democratic party to include the downtrodden
and those ``abandoned by law.''
   ``California has the power to determine the next nominee of our
party,'' he said in Los Angeles where he made a series of
appearances Friday before flying to Northern California.
   He urged his supporters not to be discouraged by reports that
the large delegate lead held by Dukakis means the Massachusetts
governor will get the Democratic nomination.
   ``We can win this campaign. We come to California _ the press,
the pundits and the party, all writing off the Jackson candidacy,''
he told a rally at East Los Angeles College. ``Don't be deceived.
   ``We're coming on the last lap now. It's a long ways, but I kept
the faith.''
   In search of California votes for the biggest remaining hurdle
in the primary season, Jackson on Friday crisscrossed the
metropolitan Los Angeles area from sunny beachfront Santa Monica to
the heavily Hispanic east side of town.
   In one of the more dramatic events of a campaign known for its
flair, Jackson delivered a stern lecture against gang violence and
drugs to high school students in an area known for heavy gang
activity.
   He then got about 300 of the students voluntarily to ``come on
down'' from the bleachers and admit to drug use, and promise to do
better.
   ``I challenge you because I love you, because I care, because
I'm not scared of you,'' he said at Fremont High School in San
Pedro. Some of the 3,000 youths listening to him wore gang colors.
   ``You know and I know it's wrong to bring guns to school,'' he
said. ``You don't need them. ... No civilized, caring person leaves
home looking for somebody to hurt, maim and destroy.''
   He then got the youths to pledge they would quit using drugs.
   Jackson also appealed to Hispanic voters with a pledge to fight
the movement to make English the official language in the United
States.
   ``English-only limits our culture,'' he said. ``Our future is in
expanding our language base, expanding our culture, expanding our
economy.''
   He also called for an extension of this week's deadline for
undocumented foreigners to apply for amnesty, and stressed his
proposal for a hemispheric energy plan and economic cooperation
between the United States and Latin American nations.
   Jackson continued calling for ``fairness'' in the Democratic
presidential delegate selection system _ to make the delegate count
proportionate to the popular vote in each congressional district.
   He told reporters he was not trying to provoke a party fight or
mount a rules challenge as he had in 1984. But he clearly laid down
a gauntlet when he said party leaders should make sure that the
delegate count comes out to correspond with the popular vote, even
though the party rules to not require that.
   Jackson trails Dukakis in the popular vote by 28 percent to 37
percent, but because not all delegates are chosen by popular vote,
Dukakis leads Jackson in delegates by 1,505 to 927, according to
the Associated Press tallies.
   Addressing an issue important to people dependent on
California's large defense contracting industry, Jackson also
proposed non-military development of space as a way to recover
defense industry jobs that would be lost under his proposed
military budget freeze.
   Jackson declined to give specifics when asked by reporters to
elaborate on how many jobs could be created in space development or
how much spending he proposed.
</TEXT>
