<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua     05-07 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Government Troops Shot by Rebels, Soldiers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista soldiers said rebels shot
and wounded four government troops in what appeared to be the
second violation of a cease-fire in as many days.
   Two government soldiers said Friday that the shootings came late
Thursday after they tried to speak with the rebels.
   On Thursday, the Defense Ministry charged that Honduras-based
Contras used speedboats to attack a Nicaraguan military position
Wednesday. The rebels did not comment on this.
   Offensive military operations between the leftist Sandinista
government and the U.S.-backed rebels known as Contras were
suspended on March 21.
   Leaders of the two sides reached a cease-fire agreement two days
later, and a 60-day truce went into effect April 1 during which
they are attempting to negotiate a lasting peace.
   Luis Noel Solano Jarquin, a Sandinista People's Army soldier,
told The Associated Press he was among a group of government troops
who approached 40 Contras in the town of El Colorado, 140 miles
southeast of Managua.
   The Contras told the soldiers that only top rebel and government
leaders could conduct ``conversations between the two sides,''
Solano Jarquin said from a hospital room in Juigalpa, about 65
miles east of the capital.
   ``Suddenly we heard shots and had to disband,'' he said.
   Solano Jarquin was wounded in his left arm. Another Sandinista
soldier, Trinidad Bermudez, received fractured ribs and a broken
forearm.
   They said two other Sandinista soldiers were wounded and being
treated at a hospital in Ciudad Rama, about 140 miles east of
Managua.
   A Defense Ministry official said he had no information on the
incident.
   Solano Jarquin and Bermudez said several armed confrontations
have occurred between Sandinista and rebel forces since the
cease-fire was declared.
   Adan Artola, a commander for the Indian rebel group known as
Yatama, said Friday that government troops recently attacked rebel
positions in Auya-Pinhi, 270 miles northeast of Managua.
   In a telephone interview from Miami, Artola said Yatama fighters
killed seven Sandinista soldiers and wounded 23 in the incident.
   Yatama claims to have more than 4,000 guerrillas whose objective
is autonomy for Nicaragua's Indian populations on the Caribbean
coast. It is not formally linked to the Contras.
   The government says more than 26,000 people have been killed
since November 1981, when the U.S.-backed Contras began fighting
the Sandinista government.
</TEXT>
