<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Poland-Scene     05-07 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Scene,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Young Striker Tries To Jump From Window, But Walesa Raises Spirits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A column of police vehicles moved to the
Lenin shipyard's main gate, directing powerful beams of light at
strikers manning it.
   Over a loudspeaker, police said, ``Good evening, gentlemen.''
   They revved the engines and came to a screeching halt about 35
feet from the gate. Columns of riot police on both sides of the
vehicles started beating the sides of the vehicles with their
truncheons.
   A few minutes later, police withdrew.
   Again, about three hours later, police directed a powerful
spotlight at the main gate. A phalanx of police in full riot gear
marched toward the gate banging their shields with truncheons.
   The strikers, instructed not to resist if the yard were stormed,
emptied the dining hall and rushed to the gate.
   ``There was no panic, they were very disciplined. They just
stood there silently,'' said a reporter who was on hand. ``But they
were visibly shaken.''
   Most of the strikers are young _ in their teens or early 20s.
   Later Friday, the tension apparently got to a young striker.
   The man suddenly rushed to a window of the big, second-floor
cafeteria where most of the strikers have been gathering, smashed
the glass and tried to jump out, according to Western reporters at
the scene.
   He was caught by his friends, pulled in and taken to the nearby
shipyard infirmary, bleeding from his hands and face. No one could
say what prompted the action.
   Lech Walesa immediately raced to the dining hall and climbed on
a chair.
   ``I have a personal request,'' the Solidarity leader began.
``You know that Solidarity is also taking care of the person next
to you.
   ``Everyone has a thousand problems: because he loves his wife
and he must stay here, another left 500 zlotys ($1.25) to his wife
when he left. Suddenly he realizes she has nothing to live on,''
Walesa told the crowd.
   ``Solidarity must be big here.''
   Reporters said tension eased immediately after Walesa's
impromptu speech.
   The stoppage that began Monday in the yard where the
now-outlawed Solidarity free trade union movement was born in 1980
was the only major strike remaining in a wave of labor unrest that
began nearly two weeks ago.
   Early Thursday, riot police violently crushed a 10-day
occupation strike at the huge Nowa Huta steelworks outside the
southern city of Krakow.
   At about the same time, hundreds of riot police threw a security
cordon around the Gdansk shipyard.
   On Friday, the yard was under virtual siege, with police turning
away food shipments.
   Walesa has clearly emerged as the man in charge of the strike,
although it is being coordinated by a 12-man committee. He gives
advice and pep talks, chats and jokes with strikers and tries to
organize entertainment.
   He sleeps on the floor on a styrofoam mat with the rest of the
strikers, using his tweed jacket as a pillow.
   Walesa helped found of Solidarity, the only officialy recognized
independent labor federation in the Soviet bloc before it was
outlawed after a 1981 military crackdown.
   After Friday's attempted leap and Walesa's speech, the strike
committee quickly organized a song festival. Strikers played
guitars and banjos and sang folk tunes and Solidarity songs.
   A member of the strike committee invited workers to come up and
tell jokes.
   Strikers also undertook some chores, such as cleaning the gate
area.
   The food situation was noticeably worse on Friday. After having
soup, loaves of bread, sausage and spreads for their main meal
Thursday, the strikers had only sauerkraut soup for lunch Friday.
   There were 800 to 1,000 strikers left inside the plant,
according to reporters. Most of the strikers spend their time in
the dining hall, while the rest guard the shipyard's eight gates.
   They have radios and listened closely to Western news broadcasts.
</TEXT>
