<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EasternSuit Bjt   05-07 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Suit, Bjt,0625</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Sues Unions For $1.5 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and labor leaders traded
recriminations after the financially troubled carrier sued two of
its unions for $1.5 billion, accusing pilots and machinists of
``Eastern-bashing.''
   The Miami-based airline and its parent company, Texas Air Corp.
of Houston, charged the unions Friday with trying to drive down the
carrier's value so the unions could buy it cheaply.
   ``The smear campaign is one of a number of tactics to facilitate
a takeover,'' Texas Air attorney Parker Folse III said of the suit,
filed in U.S. District Court in Miami.
   But Henry Duffy, national chairman of the Air Line Pilots
Association, called the suit ``a desperate attempt to draw
attention away from Texas Air's and Eastern's growing problems.''
   Eastern's ALPA chairman, John Bavis, said the suit ``is like the
lions suing the Christians for animal abuse.'' He also dismissed it
as a tactic to divert attention from a federal probe of the
finances and safety of Eastern and Continental Airlines, also owned
by Texas Air.
   ``It's clear evidence of a last-ditch effort by a very desperate
man, and that man's (Texas Air Chairman) Frank Lorenzo,'' added
Machinists local President Charles Bryan in Atlanta. He accused
Eastern of attempting to shift public opinion, which he claimed was
leaning toward the employees.
   Bavis and Bryan are named in the suit, as are 11 other officers
of the machinists union and the entire 26-member governing council
of the pilots union. Some 3,500 members of Eastern's work force
belong to the pilots union; 12,000 mechanics and other ground
workers belong to the Machinists.
   The Machinists contract dispute with Eastern _ which seeks wage
cuts of up to 50 percent _ is in federal mediation. The pilots'
contract comes open for amendment July 1.
   ALPA, the Machinists and Eastern's Transport Worker Union tried
to buy Eastern before Texas Air bought it in 1986 for $676 million,
a sale they then tried to block.
   When the unions failed to block Eastern's sale to Texas Air,
they fought in court to overturn it and lost. Since then, there
have been several other suits and countersuits.
   The Eastern suit says the two unions still hope to obtain
Eastern, which lost $900 million in the past 10 years.
   ``They seek this by an all-out effort to injure Eastern's
business _ to make it a financial millstone for Texas Air _ by
means of ... mail fraud, wire fraud, extortion. ... Further, they
have set out to destroy Eastern's good will and reputation,'' the
suit says.
   The suit also claims that ``by promoting deceitful accusations
about the safety of Eastern, defendants have induced the news media
to join in an `Eastern bashing' effort,'' and have led the
Department of Transportation and the Federal Aviation
Administration ``to conduct costly investigations of the airline,
all of which have further damaged Eastern's business.''
   The House Public Works and Transportation Committee approved a
non-binding resolution Thursday urging the Transportation
Department, parent of the FAA, to widen the probe of Eastern and
Texas Air to include how the public and workers might be affected
by company policies.
   Last month, the FAA announced it was seeking $823,000 in
penalties from Eastern for past safety violations. It then began a
plane-by-plane inspection of the carrier. Last year, Eastern paid a
$9.5 million fine for violations.
   Also Friday, Texas Air spokesmen partly blamed unions for
first-quarter losses of $124.3 million on revenues of $2.1 billion.
Eastern lost $64.5 million on revenues of $1.1 billion, but the
sale of $33.5 million in assets reduced that carrier's net loss to
$31 million.
</TEXT>
