<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     05-07 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Warns of Poison Ipecac Danger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Adminsitration is urging
parents of small children to return any bottles of Humco brand
syrup of Ipecac that remain in their home because they may contain
a deadly poison.
   As many as 400,000 1-ounce bottles have been mislabeled Ipecac,
a product normally used to induce vomiting in children who are
suspected of having eaten some dangerous product, the agency said
Friday.
   The mislabeled bottles may actually contain oil of eucalyptus
which could prove fatal if given to children, the agency said.
   Eucaluptus oil is used in minute amounts in vaporizers. But if
taken internally it can cause convulsions and coma, officials said.
As little as a teaspoonful could prove fatal, FDA reported.
   The FDA initially announced a recall of the Humco brand Ipecac
April 29, after the label mix-up was discovered. However, since
then it has learned that thousands of bottles of the product have
been distributed to consumers across the country as part of poison
prevention week activities.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Geomagnetic Storm May Interfere With Communications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you have trouble with your telephone or
other electronic equipment or notice a display of lights in the
northern sky this weekend it may not be your imagination.
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration reported
Friday a geomagnetic storm sweeping over the Earth may interfere
with satellite, radio and telephone communications.
   It may also cause an electrical phenomenon induced by current
from the sun, resulting in a display of northern lights known as
the aurora borealis, said Joe Hirman of the Space Environment
Services Center in Boulder, Colo. They should be visible for a few
nights, he said.
   Hirman said the disturbance originated in a huge flare that
erupted from the sun on Wednesday.
   It took about a day for the effects to reach Earth, and those
peaked on Friday, he said.
   However the worst should be over by Sunday he said. But, Sunday
is Mother's Day, one of the busiest days of the year for the
nation's telephone companies and Hirman warned it may not be
possible to communicate with Europe via high frequency radio
channels for a time.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Leukemia Risk Not Great Enough to Ban Growth Hormone Treatment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists from several countries say the
benefits of synthetic growth hormones received by some children
outweigh the possibly slightly higher risk of developing leukemia
those children face.
   The cancer and growth experts who met to review 15 cases of
leukemia worldwide in patients treated with synthetic growth
hormones said an increased risk had not been proven but even if it
had it is not great enough to warrant withholding treatment.
   ``There is no therapy that is risk-free,'' said a statement by
the Lawson Wilkins Pediatric Endocrine Society, which represents
doctors and scientists working in the field. ``Because GH therapy
is essential for optimal growth and development in GH deficient
children, it would be inappropriate and unwise to withhold such
treatment from needy patients.''
   The incidence of leukemia among patients taking growth hormone
worldwide is estimated at 1 in 21,000 patient-years of treatment,
the society said, while a reasonable estimate of the risk among
nonpatients in the same age range is 1 in 42,000.
   The meetings were prompted by reports of leukemia in five
Japanese children who had received the treatment.
   The society said that if there is a relationship between growth
hormone treatment and leukemia the cause could be the effect of the
hormone on bone marrow cells.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Savings Bond Sales Dip in April</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S. savings bonds dropped for the
first time in eight months in April, falling 6.4 percent to $661
million.
   The Treasury Department said Friday that April sales were $45
million lower than in March, when sales were $706 million, and an
identical amount lower than sales a year ago.
   Still, with the inclusion of interest earnings, the value of
outstanding bonds rose by $1.07 billion to total $105.09 billion in
April, 10 percent higher than a year ago. Sales had increased for
seven consecutive months, from September through March.
   The Treasury Department is hoping a new program, which began
Tuesday, will boost bond sales. Investors now can use a credit card
to buy bonds by calling a toll-free number, 1-800-US-BONDS, 24
hours a day.
</TEXT>
