<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CyanideDeaths     05-07 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cyanide Deaths,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cyanide Jury Says They're Stuck; Judge Says Try Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors hearing the nation's first
death-by-product-tampering case will return Monday to try to break
their stalemate in the trial of a woman charged with poisoning two
people with cyanide-laced headache capsules.
   U.S. District Judge William Dwyer refused to declare a mistrial
Friday in the case against Stella Nickell despite a note from the
jury foreman saying the panel appeared deadlocked during the fourth
day of deliberations.
   ``After three votes taken over the last three days we have been
unable to reach a unanimous decision. No juror has changed his-her
vote during this time. We await your instructions,'' said the note
from foreman Murray M. Andrews.
   Before the jury returned, Dwyer told attorneys in open court he
wanted to avoid a retrial in the case against Mrs. Nickell, who is
accused of poisoning her husband and another woman.
   ``I don't think we should give up on this jury yet. ... a
retrial is quite lengthy,'' Dwyer said.
   At the request of the seven-woman, five-man panel, Dwyer later
read jurors a supplemental instruction on the legal term
``reasonable doubt.''
   On Thursday, Dwyer refused to let the jury review testimony on
whether the government's star witness, Cindy Hamilton, who is Mrs.
Nickell's daughter, first went to the FBI on her own with
information against her mother or was approached by agents. But the
judge relented Friday and directed the court reporter to read that
testimony to the panel Monday.
   Mrs. Nickell, 44, of suburban Auburn is charged with two counts
of causing death by tampering with a product involved in interstate
commerce and three counts of tampering.
   The death counts carry maximum sentences of life in prison,
while the maximum for tampering is 10 years on each count.
   The case is the first involving death by product tampering to go
to trial. A case concerning seven deaths from tainted Tylenol
capsules in Chicago remains unsolved.
   The federal charges stem from the deaths of Mrs. Nickell's
husband, Bruce Nickell, 52, and Sue Katherine Snow, 40, also of
Auburn, after they swallowed cyanide-laced Extra-Strength Excedrin
capsules in June 1986.
   During the ensuing scare, three bottles containing tainted pain
relief capsules also were found on store shelves in and near
Auburn, and Excedrin manufacturer Bristol-Myers recalled all its
over-the-counter drug capsules.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joanne Maida charged in closing
arguments that Mrs. Nickell decided to end her marriage and money
woes by killing her husband and collecting as much as $176,000 in
life-insurance benefits, then tried to cover up the crime by
placing tainted capsules in stores to give the appearance of random
tampering.
   Ms. Snow was an innocent stranger caught in the scheme, Ms.
Maida said.
   Federal public defender Thomas Hillier accused Ms. Hamilton of
lying when she said her mother talked of killing her stepfather
with a drug overdose or by hiring a hit man before the tampering.
Hillier also said there was no proof Mrs. Nickell purchased any
cyanide.
</TEXT>
