<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope     05-07 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Departs on Ninth Latin American Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II departed today for Latin America,
describing his ninth tour of the region _ this time Uruguay,
Bolivia, Peru and Paraguay _ as a mission against hate, violence
and lies.
   The 12-day pilgrimage is expected to focus on the pontiff's
campaign against drug trafficking and poverty in countries
struggling with inflation and huge foreign debt.
   Montevideo, the capital of Uruguay, was set as John Paul's first
stop after a 13{-hour flight from Rome on a special Alitalia Boeing
747.
   The Vatican on Friday released the text of a radio message by
the pope to Uruguay.
   John Paul said he was traveling as a ``messenger of the Good
News who promotes in the world a struggle, without truce, of love
against hate, unity against rivalry, generosity against
selfishness, peace against violence, truth against lies. In a word:
the victory of good over evil.''
   Vatican officials say the trip, John Paul's 37th foreign
pilgrimage in his nearly 10-year-old papacy, is a sign of the
importance the church gives to an area expected to include half the
world's Roman Catholics by the year 2000.
   In Peru, the government on Friday banned marches, meetings and
other large public gatherings in Lima before and during the
pontiff's May 14-16 visit to the nation. It takes effect Sunday.
   During the pope's only other visit to Peru, in February 1985,
leftist guerrillas caused a widespread power outage, plunging
Lima's airport into blackness as the pope's plane was landing. The
craft touched down safely.
   Uruguay, where the pope stopped briefly en route to Chile in
1987, is considered the most secular country in the region.
President Julio Sanguinetti is an agnostic, teaching of religion is
banned in public schools and divorce has been legal since 1917.
   Sanguinetti took office in 1985 after a 12-year military regime
collapsed.
   From Uruguay, John Paul goes to Bolivia, where he is to spend
five days that will include a stop in Santa Cruz, an eastern city
where cocaine traffickers are said to operate with impunity.
   After Bolivia, the pope travels to Lima to deliver the closing
address of a regional religious conference.
   In Paraguay, the pope is scheduled to meet with Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner, who came to power in an army coup in 1954 and was
recently re-elected to an eighth term. Opposition politicians
claimed the election was rigged.
   John Paul will turn 68 while in Paraguay on May 18. Vatican
spokesman Joaquin Navarro said the pope's doctors suggested he
should consider slowing his pace during two stops at 2{-mile high
altitudes of Bolivia but John Paul replied this wasn't possible.
</TEXT>
