<HEAD>President's Daughter Criticizes Ex-Aides</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXNARD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's outspoken daughter took
a few verbal swings at two former presidential aides who have done
some speaking out themselves.
   Maureen Reagan blasted former presidential spokesman Larry
Speakes, who said he created quotes and attributed them to the
president without his knowledge.
   She called Speakes' claims of fabricating presidential quotes
``one of the great creative exercises of all time.''
   ``So far, I haven't been able to find anyone to corroborate
anything in the book. Speakes made up so much of it, it's hard to
distinguish,'' said Ms. Reagan, who was here Thursday to address
about 200 people at a dinner sponsored by the Ventura County
Republican Central Committee.
   Ms. Reagan also criticized former White House chief of staff
Donald Regan, whose new book, ``For the Record: From Wall Street to
Washington,'' states that the first couple consults astrologers.
   ``I never saw any astrologers in the house,'' Ms. Reagan said.
White House officials have conceded that first lady Nancy Reagan is
interested in astrology and used it to advise her husband.
   Ms. Reagan said the former chief of staff, who resigned under
pressure in February 1987, ``never understood what his position
was. There were a lot of us who said he had to leave.''
   The president also criticized Regan during a photo session in
Washington on Friday. Reagan said he didn't ``look kindly'' on
reports that Regan had criticized the first lady in the book.
   Tom Dawson, a Regan spokesman, said Regan ``has had and will
have no comments regarding his book until it is published.'' He
said the book is expected to be in stores beginning Monday.
