<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0502EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PanamaExpulsion     05-07 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama Expulsion,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Party Official Roughed Up, Expelled to Miami</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of a Panamanian opposition party who
was expelled from his homeland said Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's
supporters are growing ``more and more desperate'' in their efforts
to stay in power.
   Ivan Romero, secretary general of the Christian Democratic
Party, said he was forced to board a plane Friday to Miami after
being arrested, beaten with a rock and held overnight in prison.
   Romero was detained Thursday when he flew back to Panama after a
weeklong visit to the United States, said Perry Rivkind, local
director of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   ``They apparently interpreted something he said in New York as
unflattering to Gen. Noriega,'' Rivkind said.
   Noriega is under indictment for drug trafficking in Florida, and
the United States has called for his ouster from power.
   Romero told reporters he was taken to a military barracks
immediately upon his arrival in Panama, stripped to his underwear
and interrogated. His interrogator held a sock containing a round
stone which he swung in circles and twice used to hit Romero on his
feet, he said.
   He was asked a barrage of questions, including what orders he
received from the U.S. ambassador, what his party's plans were for
the month of May, and what his activities were with the opposition
umbrella group National Civic Crusade.
   At one point, he said, he hesitated ``and they reached down and
hit me hard on the ankles,'' said Romero.
   ``I thought they were going to tear my foot off,'' said Romero.
He said he refused to answer more questions and they stopped
hitting him, telling him later such methods were normal for getting
answers.
   Romero said he was kept standing for seven hours and was
initially told he was going to Chile.
   But Friday morning his captors drove him to the airport, stopped
a Pan American flight already on the runway, and put him on it
bound for Miami.
   ``They are getting more and more desperate,'' said Romero.
``They cannot accept that the opposition is spontaneous.''
   In Panama City, the Christian Democratic Party's president,
Ricardo Arias Calderon, told reporters that the party planned to
protest to the Federal Attorney General's Office. He said no reason
was given for Romero's detention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
