<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0529EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Quake     05-07 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Quake,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Hits Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake shook northern Japan today,
disrupting local transportation briefly but causing no serious
damage or injuries, officials said.
   Central Meteorological Agency officials said the quake, which
struck at 10:59 a.m. (9:59 p.m. EDT Friday), measured a preliminary
6.4 on the Richter scale and was centered off the coast of
Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost main island.
   Earthquakes registering six on the Richter scale are considered
severe and capable of causing widespread damage, but the officials
said little damage occurred because of the depth of the quake's
epicenter. An earthquake registering seven on the scale is
considered a major earthquake.
   A Hokkaido Prefectural Police official said there were no
reports of serious damage or injuries, but trains on two local
lines were halted briefly while tracks were inspected.
   There have been two major earthquakes in Hokkaido in the past 35
years. In 1968, the Tokachi-Oki earthquake killed 52 people.
   The earthquake registered four on the Japanese scale of seven in
Kushiro, 560 miles northwest of Tokyo, three in Aomori, 360 miles
away, and one in Tokyo, the agency said.
   A tremor measuring four on the Japanese scale, which measures
ground motion at particular locations, can shake houses.
   The open-ended Richter scale measures the total magnitude of a
quake at its epicenter. Every increase of one digit represents a
tenfold increase in magnitude, thus a reading of 7.4 would be 10
times stronger than one of 6.4.
   The Japanese and Richter scales are not convertible.
</TEXT>
