<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0537EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WilsonCase     05-07 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wilson Case,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conviction Of Youth Overturned In Death Of Basketball Star</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murder conviction of a teen-ager charged in
the 1984 death of high school basketball star Ben Wilson has been
overturned by a three-judge state appellate court panel.
   In a unanimous ruling Friday, the appeals court said Circuit
Judge James M. Bailey had violated the constitutional rights of
Omar Dixon by refusing to try him separately from another
defendant, William Moore.
   The court ordered a re-trial for Dixon.
   The 17-year-old Wilson, one of the country's leading prep
basketball players, was gunned down near Chicago's Simeon High
School during the school lunch hour on Nov. 20, 1984.
   Dixon, then 16, and Moore, 17, were convicted of murder and
attempted armed robbery in October 1985. Dixon was sentenced to
concurrent terms of 30 years for murder and 10 years for attempted
armed robbery, and Moore was sentenced to 40 years for murder and
10 for attempted armed robbery.
   The defendants did not face the death penalty because of their
age. Bailey said then that he levied a lighter sentence on Dixon
because he had done well in his jailroom classes.
   ``What we have to do now is decide what to do,'' said Terry
Levin, a spokesman for the Cook County state's attorney's office.
``Prosecutors are reviewing the appeals court decision,'' he said
Friday.
   Before the trial, attorneys for Dixon had filed a motion to
separate his trial from Moore's, arguing that a joint trial would
prevent Dixon from challenging incriminating statements made by
Moore.
   By denying that motion, the appeals court said, Bailey denied
Dixon his constitutional right to challenge his accuser.
</TEXT>
