<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Punjab     05-07 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Punjab,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nine More Deaths Blamed on Sikh Militants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Militant Sikh separatists killed nine
people in the continuing spree of violence that has plagued the
troubled northern state of Punjab for six years, the United News of
India reported today.
   The news agency said Sikhs opened fire at a poor farmers' hamlet
late Friday night in Kapurthala District in central Punjab, killing
seven people and wounding four.
   UNI also said two Hindu shopkeepers were killed overnight in
separate attacks in Punjab.
   The latest deaths brought to at least 916 the number of people
killed by militants in Punjab this year. The extremists have killed
both moderate Sikhs and Hindus.
   Sikhs, whose religion was formed about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they are discriminated
against by India's majority Hindus. They make up less than 2
percent of India's 800 million population but are a majority in
Punjab.
   Militants have mounted a campaign of violence and terror in an
attempt to create a separate state they call Khalistan in Punjab.
Khalistan in Punjabi means ``land of the pure.''
   The government of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, in an attempt to
curb the growing violence, has imposed direct federal rule in the
state.
</TEXT>
