<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-07 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winter Storm Hits the Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A wintry storm settled into the Rocky Mountains today after
dumping 14 inches of snow on parts of Nevada and unleashing
tornadoes that descended on several Midwestern states.
   A winter storm warning was posted today in the mountains and
foothills of Montana as the storm drifted toward the Rockies, east
of the Continental Divide.
   A snow advisory went into effect in the Big Horn Mountains of
Wyoming this morning and a high wind warning covered eastern
Wyoming. A frost advisory also was posted over the west-central
valleys of Colorado this morning.
   The heavy snowfall in eastern Nevada ended Friday night, leaving
14 inches of snow at Jackpot and Austin Summit.
   In Wyoming, 5 inches of snow fell at Burgess Junction while
Yellowstone National Park received at least 3 inches of snow.
   Meanwhile, tornadoes touched down Friday afternoon and evening
in Wyoming, several areas of South Dakota, North Dakota, and
Montana. No injuries were reported.
   But there were reports of damage from thunderstorm wind gusts in
Wyoming, South Dakota and Texas. In Texas, golf-ball-sized hail
pelted an area south of Hermleigh while Crowell and Rule reported
an onslaught of three-quarter inch hail.
   Today's forecast called for rain over the northern Rockies and
the central California coast; showers and thunderstorms from the
northern Plains across the middle Mississippi and lower Missouri
valleys into Oklahoma and north-central Texas; showers from the
central Pacific coast across the Great Basin; snow over northern
and central Nevada; and gusty winds from the central Rockies across
the central Plains and the Great Lakes.
   Highs were expected in the 70s or 80s across much of the nation
east of the Rockies; in the 50s and 60s west of the Rockies from
the Pacific coast across the northern and central Rockies; in the
60s near the shores of the Great Lakes, across much of New England
and along the northern Atlantic coast; and into the 90s over much
of Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 75 degrees at the
Naval Air Station near Corpus Christi and Laredo, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 60 fair; Boston 51 foggy; Buffalo 50 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 57 fair; Cincinnati 50 fair; Cleveland 46 fair;
Detroit 50 fair; Miami 63 fair; New York 57 cloudy; Philadelphia 58
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 54 fair; Washington 56 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 56 cloudy; Chicago 52 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 70 windy; Denver 48 fair; Des Moines 67 partly
cloudy; Indianapolis 56 fair; Kansas City 70 windy; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 69 cloudy; Nashville 52 fair; New Orleans 60 fair; St. Louis
64 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 50 fair; Anchorage 47 cloudy; Las Vegas 54
fair; Los Angeles 53 fair; Phoenix 61 fair; Salt Lake City 41
cloudy; San Diego 56 fair; San Francisco 52 rain; Seattle 45 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 57 fair; Toronto 45 fair.
</TEXT>
