<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RFKRemembered 1stLd-Writethru a0427 05-07 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RFK Remembered, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf to change date</NOTE>
<HEAD>Family, Friends, Admirers To Gather At Arlington Cemetery To
Remember RFK</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of family, friends and admirers of
the late Robert F. Kennedy are expected to gather at his gravesite
next month for a memorial service on the 20th anniversary of his
assassination.
   The June 6 sunset Mass at Arlington National Cemetery will be
open to the public, Chuck McDermott, an aide to Rep. Joseph P.
Kennedy II, D-Mass., the late senator's eldest son, said Friday.
   ``Twenty years later, there seems to be a great emotional need
from people all over the country to express their sense of loss as
well as rededication,'' said Melody Miller, a spokeswoman for Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy and a former RFK aide.
   ``I've gotten calls over the past month from Indiana,
Philadelphia, Oregon ... not staff people, simply John Q. Public
who loved Robert Kennedy,'' Miller said. ``People are planning
their vacations around it. I have been very touched by that and so
has the family.
   ``It was one of the reasons that they wanted to have it this
year, so many people called from out of the blue to join the family
in a celebration of his life.''
   A longtime friend of the Kennedy clan will celebrate the Mass,
which will have a theme of ``rebirth and rededication.''
   Former aides and family members are helping Kennedy's widow,
Ethel, organize the event.
   Family members, including Sen. Kennedy, Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis and RFK's children, grandchildren, sisters, nieces, nephews
and in-laws, are expected to gather at the gravesite, located near
the grave of his brother, John Kennedy. The public will gather on a
nearby hill. Everyone will be given a candle.
   Rose Kennedy, the late senator's ailing mother, is not expected
to attend.
   There will be a 40-person gospel choir and a 40-voice children's
choir at the ceremony, which starts at 7 p.m. Andy Williams, who
sang at Kennedy's funeral in 1968, also will sing at the service.
   Kennedy was gunned down June 5, 1968, in Los Angeles during his
campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
