<HEAD>Oklahoma Coach Files $3 Million Suit Over 1983 Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University of Oklahoma head basketball
coach Billy Tubbs has filed a $3 million lawsuit in federal court
against the woman whose car struck and injured him in 1983.
   In the lawsuit, filed Friday in U.S. District Court in Oklahoma
City, Tubbs alleges that Angela M. Harrell failed to exercise
proper care when her car struck Tubbs while he was jogging in south
Norman on Feb. 20, 1983.
   A similar lawsuit was filed in Oklahoma County court in 1984 and
is set for trial. Harrell was dismissed from the first lawsuit, but
her insurance company remains a defendant.
   Tubbs' attorney, Larry Tawwater, said the federal lawsuit was
filed to avoid missing the expiration of the statute of limitations.
   The lawsuits allege that Tubbs suffered injuries to his head,
neck, back, arms, shoulders legs and entire body.
