<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     05-07 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Names New Police, Intelligence Chiefs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo today put a
moderate in charge of the nation's intelligence agency but chose a
confidant as national police chief in a Cabinet shakeup that
followed a major election setback.
   The moves came as Kim Dae-jung, whose party emerged as the main
opposition party in the April 26 National Assembly elections,
called for political neutrality by the police and the intelligence
agency.
   Roh named a former justice minister, 55-year-old Bae Myung-in,
to head the powerful Agency for National Security Planning,
replacing An Moo-hyuk, a former general.
   As home affairs minister, in charge of the nation's
140,000-member police force, the president selected Lee Chun-gu,
53, a former general with military background. He replaces Lee
Sang-hee, 56.
   The new home minister said he would make ``order and stability''
his highest priority. ``At any cost, I will eliminate violent
leftist forces and activities that hurt the social order.''
   The presidential office said the shakeup reflected Roh's will to
``execute state affairs in harmony.''
   Kim Dae-jung said today that he would work to ``open a new era
of democratic development through sincere dialogue'' if Roh carries
out his promise for democratic reforms.
   Kim made the call in his acceptance speech at a convention of
the Party for Peace and Democracy, which voted him back into the
party presidency. He had resigned the post in March after losing in
the December presidential election.
   About 1,000 supporters wildly applauded Kim's return as formal
leader of his party, and another 1,000 cheering people stood
outside the convention hall in the rain.
   As delegates repeatedly chanted his name, Kim said, ``We will
spare no efforts to cooperate in democratic reforms of the Roh
regime.''
   After Roh's Democratic Justice Party lost its parliamentary
majority in April's elections, the president said he would
``humbly'' accept the outcome and indicated he would work with
three major opposition parties to expand democracy.
   Last week, Roh replaced the head of the party with a moderate
senior politician and filled other senior party posts with
moderates.
   Meanwhile, Kim urged the government to release all political
prisoners and wipe out corruption and all restrictions on civil
rights and political freedom.
   In his speech, he demanded that the National Assembly probe
misdeeds under the government of Roh's predecessor, Chun Doo-hwan,
and into corruption allegedly involving Chun's family.
   ``We could forgive criminals but we must know clearly what
really happened in Kwangju,'' Kim said, referring to the
government's suppression of the 1980 civil uprising in Kwangju in
which at least 193 people were killed.
   Kim, 62, and his supporters split from the former main
opposition party, the Reunification Democratic Party, when both Kim
and party leader Kim Young-sam insisted on running for president
last December.
   With the opposition split, Roh won the election with 36.6
percent of the vote. He took office Feb. 25. The result brought
public criticism of the two Kims, and Kim Dae-jung resigned as his
party's head on March 17 in an effort to make it easier for the two
parties to reunite.
   The two parties remained divided, however, and the Party for
Peace and Democracy's strong showing in the April 26 election
propelled Kim Dae-jung back to political life.
</TEXT>
