<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GuentherSentenced     05-07 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Guenther Sentenced,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Used `Make My Day' Defense Gets Life In Separate Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who used a ``Make My Day''
self-defense law to defend himself in the shooting of a neighbor
has been sentenced to life in prison in the 1987 shooting death of
his estranged wife.
   David Guenther made headlines when he successfully used the
then-new self-defense law after he was charged with shooting a
neighbor and wounding two other people during a neighborhood feud
in April 1986. The state law allows residents to use deadly force
in their homes against intruders.
   However, the Colorado Supreme Court overturned that lower-court
ruling, saying the law had been misapplied, and made Guenther stand
trial. A jury acquitted him last October, finding he acted in
self-defense.
   On March 1, 1987, Guenther shot and killed his wife, Pamela, 30,
and wounded her boyfriend, Stanley Stinson, outside a Commerce City
restaurant. Guenther was free on bond at the time.
   Adams County District Judge Harlan Bockman imposed the life
sentence Friday, which offers no chance of parole for 40 years. He
also sentenced Guenther, 35, to a consecutive eight-year term for
the wounding of Stinson during the shooting.
   Guenther's lawyers have planned an appeal.
   Both prosecution and defense lawyers agreed Guenther killed his
wife and shot Stinson. But the prosecution contended Guenther acted
with deliberation, while the defense claimed Guenther fired eights
shots from his pistol in the ``heat of passion'' as he saw his wife
kissing Stinson in the parking lot.
</TEXT>
