<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Norway-PlaneCrash     05-07 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Norway-Plane Crash,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thirty-Six Norwegians Killed In Domestic Air Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Norwegian airliner on a domestic flight
crashed into a coastal mountainside in cloudy night skies and poor
visibility, killing all the 36 Norwegians aboard, police said today.
   The four-engine turbo-prop Dash-7 crashed Friday night about 9
miles southwest of its destination, the Norwegian Sea coastal town
of Broennoeysund, about 440 miles north of Oslo.
   The 50-seat Wideroe Airline plane, on a flight from Namsos,
crashed into the west wall of the 890-foot Torghatten mountain
about 8:30 p.m. (2:30 p.m. EDT), said police chief Olav Soenderland
in nearby Bodoe.
   He said the control tower at Broennoeysund airport lost contact
with the plane about five minutes earlier. The plane was scheduled
to land at 8:35 p.m. ``Rescue personnel and four doctors reaching
the crash site by helicopters reported soon after 11 p.m. that
there was no sign of survivors,'' Soenderland said on national NRK
television.
   ``They reported that there was still fire and small explosions
in the severely damaged main fuselage and in debris spred widely
around in steep and rough terrain,'' Soenderland said.
   The national NTB news agency said the crash site was about 300
feet above sea level.
   Authorities said the cause of the crash was under investigation.
   The three crew members and all the 33 passengers, 12 women and
21 men, were identified today by the police and the airline.
   Among the passengers killed was a family of five from Langevaag
in western Norway that included two boys aged 19 and 17 and a
16-year-old girl.
   The crash was among the worst in Norway since World War II.
Forty people were killed in a domestic Braathen SAFE airline crash
near Oslo on Dec. 23, 1972. Five people survived.
</TEXT>
