<HEAD>Eight Party Officials Reported Killed In Afghanistan's
Second-Largest City</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas attacked
Afghanistan's second largest city with rockets and grenades,
killing eight Communist Party officials, it was reported today.
   Agency Afghan Press, a private Pakistani newsletter, said the
strike occurred last Saturday in the provincial capital of
Kandahar, 280 miles south of Kabul.
   It said the officials of the ruling People's Democratic Party of
Afghanistan were meeting at the party office protected by an
armored vehicle outside. AAP said the vehicle was destroyed after
its Afghan crew escaped.
   The statement said five other officials ``were captured when
they were fleeing away.'' It said all five were taken to rebel-held
areas for trial.
   There was no independent confirmation of the report.
   Guerrillas fighting Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government are
known to control most of the mountains and desert plains
surrounding Kandahar, whose population of 200,000 reportedly has
dwindled to 20,000 since the war began nearly 10 years ago.
   The guerrillas have captured a series of important posts
recently in eastern Afghanistan as Soviet forces have turned them
over to government troops in preparation for the scheduled May 15
start of the Soviet withdrawal.
   About 115,000 Soviet troops intervened in Afghanistan in
December 1979 to back the government. The Soviets have agreed to
pull out under an April 14 agreement in Geneva.
   The fall of Kandahar would be a serious blow to the Marxist
government of President Najib. It would reinforce widespread fears
that the Afghan army will be no match for the heavily-armed
guerrillas once the Soviets leave.
</TEXT>
