<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Violence, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0496,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>40 Dead, 61 Wounded In Second Day Of Factional Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE casualty toll. Picks up 6th
graf, `As the...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias battled with
tanks, rockets and howitzers today for control of the slums of
south Beirut. Police said at least 40 people were killed and 61
wounded.
   Explosions echoed across the capital and smoke billowed from
fires in apartment blocks in several parts of the densely-populated
district. Hospitals issued urgent appeals for blood.
   Most of south Beirut's estimated 250,000 residents spent the
night in basements and bomb shelters as gunmen fought in the narrow
alleyways.
   Police said firefighters could not enter the area to quell
blazes set by the rival groups.
   According to police count, 56 people have been killed and 111
have been wounded in two days of fighting between the pro-Syrian
Amal militia and the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God.
   As the Shiites battled, calm prevailed in two nearby Palestinian
refugee camps after heavy clashes Friday between rival guerrilla
factions in which police said 14 fighters were killed and 46
wounded.
   A police official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Amal
deployed dozens of Soviet-made T-54 tanks early today in a bid to
storm Hezbollah's three main strongholds in south Beirut.
   Hezbollah, made up of Shiite zealots loyal to Iran's Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, is believed to be an umbrella for pro-Iranian
factions holding most of 18 foreign hostages, including nine
Americans, in Lebanon.
   Most of the captives are believed to be held in the southern
slums.
   Amal also shelled key intersections in an effort to block
Hezbollah's supply lines, the police spokesman said.
   The fighting broke out before dawn Friday when four Amal
militiamen were killed in a south Beirut ambush. Amal blamed
Hezbollah.
   The Lebanese Red Cross and civil defense said their teams
evacuated dozens of casualties from the battle zones.
   ``Dozens of other casualties remain in the streets in areas
subjected to shelling and automatic weapons fire. We haven't been
able to evacuate them,'' a civil defense spokesman said on
condition of anonymity.
   Machine-gun fire closed the main highway leading to Beirut
airport on the southwestern edge of the disputed area. But
travelers managed to reach the airport through side streets and
flight schedules were not affected, police said.
   The clashes were the heaviest between the two factions since
Amal cracked down on Hezbollah in Shiite-dominated south Lebanon
last month. Sixty-two people were killed and 150 wounded in that
four-day battle.
   Syria is Iran's main Arab ally in the 7{-year-old war against
Iraq, but the Syrians have become increasingly alarmed at the
Iran-backed Hezbollah's drive to dominate Lebanon's 1.2 million
Shiites, the biggest single sect in the country.
   The fundamentalists seek to create an Iranian-style Islamic
republic in Lebanon, considered by neighboring Syria to be its zone
of influence.
   Police said it could not be determined if the feuding
Palestinian factions had agreed on a cease-fire.
   Friday's fighting was the latest in a series of confrontations
in the battered camps between guerrillas loyal to Palestine
Liberation Organization Chairman Yasser Arafat and the radical
Fatah-Uprising group.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, sent 7,500 troops into
Moslem west Beirut Feb. 22, 1987 in a bid to end three years of
militia anarchy.
   But the Syrians have not moved into the Shiite stronghold of
south Beirut, apparently to avoid a head-on collision with Iran's
allies.
   Syria also maintains 25,000 troops in eastern and norther
Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate linked to the
13-year-old civil war between Lebanon's Christians and Moslems.
</TEXT>
