<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Gulf-Pool 1stLd-Writethru   05-07 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pool, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0500,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., British Warships Escort Tankers Through Strait of Hormuz</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS EDT time in 3rd graf, `He said...' to 6 sted 7 p.m.
Pick up 4th graf, ``They either...</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following dispatch is from Robert Kearns of
Reuters, the press representative in the Pentagon news pool in the
Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS JACK WILLIAMS IN ThE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large
convoy of oil tankers and merchant vessels, escorted by U.S. and
British warships, sailed through the tense Strait of Hormuz without
hearing so much as a peep from Iran.
   ``It was as though Iran did not exist,'' this guided missile
frigate's captain, Edward Mann, told a Pentagon media pool of
Friday's remarkably quiet voyage into the Gulf of Oman.
   He said that no Iranian gunboats or warships were sighted nor
was there even any routine radio or radar conyact during the
cruise, which reached the open waters off Oman near midnight (6
p.m. EDT).
   ``They either learned a lesson or are planning something new,''
one crewman said on the darkened bridge as the convoy left behind
the strait.
   The Williams and a British destroyer, HMS Gloucester, made their
way through the strait riding shotgun for a herd of tankers and
merchant vessels.
   About 10 ships traveled along with the warships in the largest
convoy through the waterway since fierce U.S.-Iranian naval clashes
April 18.
   Other convoys are waiting for escort service at the mouth of the
strait.
   President Reagan last week gave permission to the navy to aid
ships flying other than American flags if they come under attack.
   But Cmdr. Mann said that when the British convoy moved alongside
Dubai, it was little more than coincidence.
   ``It's a small ocean out here,'' he said earlier on his
sun-baked bridge as British and American helicopters crossed in the
sky ahead of the convoy. The deck temperature on the Williams was
measured at 126 degrees Friday afternoon.
   ``Diplomatically I guess it has been difficult to get all these
countries to agree to coordinate their polices,'' he said. ``But we
keep in touch out here and I certainly would not sit by and watch
if any aircraft attacked the Gloucester''.
   The 3,700-ton guided missile frigate Williams protected two
Kuwaiti-owned but American-flagged oil tankers. It was flanked by
four tankers escorted by the 4,000-ton Glouchester.
   Iraq on Thursday said it hit an Iranian naval target. This has
in the past provoked quick Iranian retaliation on ships in the Gulf
and Tehran has also vowed revenge for its losing battle with the
U.S. Navy on April 18th.
   This was the fourth U.S.-led convoy that passed unchallenged
through the strait within range of Iran's Silkworm missile
batteries since the April 18 clashes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
