<2ND_LINE>PM-Askew, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0504,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspapers: Askew Dropping Out of Florida Senate Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th pvs, ``Askew has xxx, with
reaction, background</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popular former Florida Gov. Reubin
Askew has apparently decided to drop out of the race for a U.S.
Senate seat, saying that he does not like having to ask
contributors for money, according to reports published today.
   Askew, 59, had been the favorite to win both the primary and the
general election, and had collected about $1 million for his
campaign warchest so far.
   Both the Tallahassee Democrat and The Orlando Sentinel quoted
anonymous sources as saying that Askew had decided to drop out
because he did not want to raise more money for his campaign.
   A source who refused to be identified told the Democrat that
Askew telephoned party officials from a central Florida campaign
stop Friday with the news, the newspaper said.
   Democratic Party Chairman Charles Whitehead declined official
comment on Askew's announcement Friday night, the newspapers said.
   Askew has held a commanding lead over his Democratic primary
challenger, U.S. Rep. Dan Mica, in all polls published to date.
Polls also showed Askew with a lead over Republican senate
candidate U.S. Rep. Connie Mack.
   ``I would be shocked if it were true,'' said Mica. ``But I'm
ready to take the nomination.''
   Florida campaigns have become increasingly expensive in the
1980s. Sen. Bob Graham and then-Sen. Paula Hawkins spent $15
million in their 1986 Senate battle.
   With a July qualifying deadline, the favorite's departure might
encourage other candidates to jump into the field.
   A meeting of Askew's campaign staff was scheduled for later
today.
   Askew's departure would be the second jolt to the Democratic
Party in this year's senate race. The first came last December when
incumbent Lawton Chiles announced plans to retire after three terms.
   The State Democratic Executive Committee was scheduled to select
its final 47 delegates to the partly's national convention today in
Tallahassee, where reports of Askew's decision disappointed his
supporters and party regulars.
</TEXT>
