<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0448 05-07 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0448,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Wounded Today In Clashes, Leaflet Calls For More Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with violence today. PICKS up 5th graf, `U.S.
Ambassador ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers shot and wounded two
Palestinian protesters today, an Arab report said, and Islamic
leaders tried to spur the Arab uprising by issuing leaflets calling
for ``more attacks on the enemy.''
   In Jerusalem, Mubarak Awad, an Arab-American ordered deported by
Israel for encouraging the Palestinian uprising, was on a hunger
strike in his jail cell, his wife, Nancy Nye, said.
   She said Awad, 44, began the strike after being arrested
Thursday night but revealed it to his attorney, Jonathan Kuttab,
today.
   Ms. Nye said prison officials took away Awad's mattress and
blanket today ``as punishment for refusing to eat,'' but that her
husband planned to continue the action ``until the (deportation)
order is rescinded.''
   The United States protested the order and urged Israel to
reconsider deporting Awad, an advocate of non-violent protests to
end Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israel accused Awad of playing a role in inciting the five-month
rebellion. According to U.N. figures, the uprising has claimed the
lives of 184 Palestinians and two Israelis.
   Violence broke out Friday night in the West Bank town of
Tulkarem, an army spokesman and hospital officials said.
   The army said troops on patrol in the town ran into a barricade
of burning tires and then fired live ammunition at an Arab-owned
automobile that was heading away from the riot.
   An Arab reporter in Tulkarem said a 40-year-old man driving the
car and a 24-year-old passenger suffered bullet wounds from the
incident. He said the driver denied the soldiers gave any order to
stop before firing. A third Arab was injured by broken glass.
   The army said three injured people were taken to Tulkarem
Hospital after the incident and that it was checking the source of
their injuries.
   Soldiers fired rubber bullets at protesters who blocked a main
road with boulders in Anabta, a town near Tulkarem, said the Arab
reporter, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Hospital officials said a 25-year-old woman was treated after
being hit by four rubber bullets. The army said it was checking the
reports.
   Also today, soldiers fired tear gas to disperse protesters who
threw stones and blocked roads with burning tires in Rafah, Arab
witnesses said. They said teen-agers also burned tires in the city
of Gaza and in Khan Yunis.
   The violence occurred hours after Moslem preachers distributed
leaflets at morning prayers urging Palestinians to step up the
uprising during the last 10 days of the holy month of Ramadan.
   The leaflet was printed Friday by ``Hamas,'' an Arabic acronym
for the Islamic Resistance Movement, one of the undeground groups
leading the uprising.
   Referring to Israel, the page-long flyer said ``the Zionist
entity and collaborators and enemies of the nation try to silence
the voice of the intefadeh (Arabic for uprising).''
   ``We will continue our intefadeh with all our strength and
determination, whatever sacrifices are necessary,'' the leaflet
added. ``More sacrifices, more attacks on the enemy, the enemy of
the nation.''
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, several merchants
opened their shops but later obeyed military orders to shut them,
witnesses said.
   A leaflet issued by a PLO underground had urged the merchants to
open today in defiance of a military order which ordered the
businesses closed through today.
   The army edict was the latest attempt to break Palestinian
obedience to underground leaders.
   By Israeli law, Awad has three days to appeal to the Supreme
Court. Kuttab, Awad's lawyer,said an appeal is likely.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas Pickering asked an official in Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's office to reconsider the move, according
to a State Department official in Washington.
   Awad, who also has a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio, heads the
Jerusalem-based Center for Non-Violent Studies and has also served
as a spokesman for the Palestinian cause.
   Avi Pazner, spokesman for Shamir, said Awad, ``beneath his
disguise of non-violence ... is one of the most dangerous people
working behind the scenes of these riots.''
   Shamir signed the deportation order, which prompted quick
protests from left-wing Israelis.
   Awad issued a statement, saying he thought he was being
victimized by Israeli extremists but believed coexistence between
Israelis and Palestinians was possible.
   ``I also believe the Palestinians can get their rights through
non-violence and a campaign of civil disobedience. This has been
the message of the uprising,'' the statement said. ``It is a much
better way the our attempting to kill one another.''
   Palestinian leaders of the uprising have adopted many of Awad's
strategies for resistance, including commercial strikes, nonpayment
of taxes, and a boycott of Israeli products.
</TEXT>
