<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Japan-Korea     05-07 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-Korea,0173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Cancels Visit by Zoo Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea has canceled a visit of two animal
experts to Japan because of a political dispute over the crash of a
South Korean jetliner in November, zoo officials said Saturday.
   Kyoto Zoo officials said they received a telegram from North
Korean officials Friday saying the government ``had been forced to
reconsider'' the visit because of sanctions imposed by Japan after
the plane disappeared.
   All 115 people aboard died after the plane blew up Nov. 29 near
Burma. The Japanese government blamed North Korean agents for
sabotaging the jet and announced it would prohibit North Korean
officials from entering Japan and sharply limit diplomatic contacts.
   North Korea has denied any connection with the crash.
   Despite the sanctions, Japan's Justice Ministry had issued visas
for the two zoological experts after it deemed they were local
rather than national government officials. They were to arrive
Tuesday to present a rare Korean wolf to the Kyoto zoo.
</TEXT>
