<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietsinWashington     05-07 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets in Washington,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Mount Pre-Summit Media Offensive in Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a month before the summit in Moscow,
Washington has been hit by a deluge of Kremlin advisers, who have
been issuing reports, shaking hands and posing for pictures with
American politicians, academics and journalists.
   The Soviets have been refining their techniques for wooing
Americans since the first meeting between President Reagan and
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev in November 1985 in Geneva.
   In Geneva, articulate Soviet spokesmen appeared before American
television cameras, explaining Gorbachev's policies and opening up
some previously taboo topics to debate.
   At the Iceland summit in October 1986, the Soviets put on an
even better show. Gennady Gerasimov, the smooth-talking foreign
ministry spokesman, got officials who usually operate behind the
scenes to dutifully field questions.
   For the Washington summit last December, the Soviets trotted out
even more bigwigs, including arms control expert Gen. Nikolai
Chervov, economist Abel Aganbegyan and others thought to have the
ear of Kremlin decision-makers.
   The U.S. Advisory Commission on Public Diplomacy, a government
board, said ``the Washington summit was as much of a worldwide
media event as it was a bilateral encounter.''
   And it said ``to combat'' the proliferation of Soviet officials
made available to the media, the American government should send
its officials and spokesmen to Moscow before the summit begins
there on May 29 ``to explain and advocate U.S. summit objectives.''
   Hundreds of American journalists are expected to travel to
Moscow for the May 29-June 2 summit, and Valentin Falin, head of
the semiofficial Novosti News Agency, said in an interview they
would have ``priority access to Soviet officials during the
summit.''
   Just to make sure the Soviet message gets across, Falin and
other top Soviet spokesmen have visited Washington and other U.S.
cities over the past few weeks.
   Falin arrived April 19 at the head of an impressive delegation
of Soviet media heavies, including Gerasimov, deputy heads of the
state broadcasting and film monopolies, the first deputy minister
of culture, deputy editors of the official TASS news agency and
government newspaper Izvestia and others of only slightly lesser
prominence.
   The parade continued on April 25 with the arrival of Yevgeny
Velikhov, who is president of the Soviet Academy of Sciences and is
thought to be a close adviser to Gorbachev on Star Wars, nuclear
and other technical issues.
   During his stay, Velikhov signed an agreement with the U.S.
Nuclear Regulatory Commission to exchange safety information, met
with Department of Energy officials and attended a series of
seismological tests near the Nevada test site to prove the
feasibility of monitoring low-level nuclear tests.
   Another Kremlin insider, space scientist Roald Sagdeyev, was hot
on Velikhov's heels, delivering an address before the National
Academy of Sciences on the possibility of a joint expedition to the
Martian moon, Phobos.
   Sagdeyev, head of the Soviet Institute for Space Research, then
jetted to the West coast, and was to return early this week for
conferences sponsored by the World Resources Institute and the
Federation of American Scientists.
   The social sciences have been well represented. Georgi Arbatov,
who is a Gorbachev adviser and head of Moscow's USA-Canada
Institute, led a delegation of scholars to a conference in Austin,
Texas, then came to Washington to release a joint report with a
group of Americans about reducing military competition between the
superpowers.
   On Tuesday, Alexei Glukhov of the Soviet foreign ministry
arrives with four other officials to try to work out a summit
agreement on cultural relations.
   The arts have not been overlooked. The Hirshhorn Museum and
Sculpture Garden is opening an exhibit, ``Russian and Soviet
Paintings 1900-1930,'' featuring canvases by Vasily Kandinsky,
Kasimir Malevich and Marc Chagall that for decades were hidden in
the basements of museums in Moscow and Leningrad.
   The Soviets also sent 11 important works by French
post-Impressionist Paul Gauguin to the National Gallery of Art, as
well as works by Dutch and Flemish masters to the Metropolitan
Museum in New York.
   Additionally, the Corcoran Gallery is showing paintings by three
official Soviet artists, and the American History Museum next opens
an exhibit on Russian Orthodox icons next Friday.
   The New York Philharmonic goes to the Soviet Union at the end of
May, and the Soviet State Symphony Orchestra comes to the United
States in October.
   And what is billed as the first ever joint U.S.-Soviet
orchestra, with 110 Americans and Soviets aged 17-23, will open a
tour of the United States and Soviet Union with an Aug. 5
performance in Washington.
</TEXT>
