<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bishops-Youth     05-07 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bishops-Youth,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishops Urge Youths to Avoid Clinics for Sex Guidance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops have told
young people to avoid school-based clinics that offer
contraceptives, and to accept instead that ``the only 100 percent
safe way to avoid pregnancy is to reserve sexual activity for
marriage.''
   In a 1,000-word message addressed to ``the youth of our
country,'' the National Conference of Catholic Bishops asserted
this past week that clinic operators believe that ``the only way to
help you cope with your sexuality is to provide you with
contraceptives.''
   ``They assume that young people will be involved in sexual
activity and cannot achieve self-control that will lead to healthy
physical and spiritual growth. We know that there are better
solutions,'' the bishops said.
   The bishops' message, contained in brochures available for
widespread distribution, said that unlike clinics, ``schools,
parents and churches ... teach you honesty, moral responsibility,
promise-keeping, self-control, commitment and respect for other
persons to help you reserve sexual activity for marriage.''
   The bishops rejected the argument that school-based clinics
which dispense contraceptives help decrease the number of unwanted
pregnancies among teen-agers. They said ``We believe that the wide
availability of contraceptives confirms teen-agers in their harmful
sexual behavior.''
</TEXT>
