<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlligatorHunt     05-07 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alligator Hunt,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Game Commission OKs 28 Alligator Hunting Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alligators once were threatened with
extinction in Florida, but now they're all over the place and will
be subject to legal hunting this fall for the first time in 26
years, a state agency has decided.
   The Florida Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission agreed Friday
to hunting in 28 selected areas after the Florida Audubon Society
challenged rules that would have permitted a county-by-county or
statewide hunt.
   Audubon officials said the larger hunt would have killed too
many alligators and wasn't what the Legislature intended when it
passed a law that lifted 'gator-hunting restrictions.
   ``We did what they asked,'' said Scott Ball, a spokesman for the
commission. The designations were approved without debate.
   ``The next step is to go to those areas and decide how many
alligators can be taken from each,'' Ball said.
   The commission is scheduled to make that decision in July after
staffers conduct an alligator census in the swamps and lakes.
   The commission plans to permit 15 percent of the adult 'gators
in each area to be harvested.
   Alligator hunting and trapping was banned in the early 1960s
when the reptiles were threatened with extinction and they were
given national endangered species status in 1973. They have since
made a comeback and have been removed from endangered and
threatened species lists.
   Biologists say there is no way to make a firm estimate of the
statewide population, but rough guesses have ranged from 1 million
to 6 million. Biologists say they have evidence the gators are
outgrowing their habitat and some may starve if the population
isn't reduced.
</TEXT>
