<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Change Bjt-2Takes   05-07 1032</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Change, Bjt-2 Takes,1061</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate Close-up: Jackson's Evolution from Confronter to
Mediator</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Another in an intermittent series taking a closer look at
aspects in the lives and careers of the remaining presidential
contenders. This story discusses how Jesse Jackson has changed over
his years as a figure in the public eye. Also moved in advance as
b0611-b0612.</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businessman Guy Smith met Jesse Jackson across a
negotiating table in 1981 when Smith was a vice president for 7Up
Corp. and Jackson was pressuring corporations to expand
opportunities for blacks.
   They met several times with subordinates and alone, coming up
with a ``covenant'' under which 7Up agreed to spend $61 million to
improve its minority hiring and spending program.
   Today, Smith says, `I am a Republican, but if Jesse is the
(Democratic) nominee, I will vote for him.''
   ``He never one time wanted us to give something to somebody. He
wanted us to give opportunity,'' for blacks, which ultimately was
great for the 7Up business, recalled Smith, now a Phillip Morris
vice president.
   It was a different side of Jesse Jackson that Smith and other
corporate executives saw _ different from the man the public had
come to know as a fiery spokesman for black concerns, who led
street demonstrations, railed against City Hall, blasted the
administration in Washington and spouted militant rhetoric.
   The public Jackson, as head of his civil rights organization
Operation PUSH (People United to Serve Humanity), was honing his
skills as a champion headline grabber, always able to seize on an
issue or tactic that would put PUSH in the news.
   During those years, he began to develop a less flamboyant side,
with the tactics of conciliatory persuasion that he is showcasing
in his campaign for the 1988 Democratic presidential nomination.
   For instance, he was given credit for successful mediation of
the devastating 1980 Chicago firefighters' strike _ 22 people died
in fires during the strike _ after marathon sessions with blacks,
who were insisting on affirmative action before they would unite
with white unionists, and with white firefighters and city
officials.
   That side of Jackson has become more dominant in the years since
his 1984 presidential bid.
   Gone are the dashikis, blue jeans and leather vests that were
the uniform of Jackson's youthful protest days.
   Also gone is much of the confrontational rhetoric typified by
his remarks on the day he launched PUSH in 1971: ``Power must not
be blind. It must be used ... to picket, vote and if necessary to
engage in civil disobedience ... We will be as nonviolent as we can
be, and as violent as we must be.''
   In Chicago, it is difficult to find many associates who don't
offer the observation that Jackson has grown and matured since
those days.
   Today, in impeccable business suits and silk ties, Jackson
projects himself as a conciliator and mediator, holding himself
above the fray of campaign attacks and holding out the promise of
understanding to all constituencies.
   Even in the heat of the New York primary, when Mayor Ed Koch
called Jackson a liar, Jackson brushed it off.
   One former critic, Chicago radio commentator Lu Palmer, says he
set aside his misgivings about Jackson after determining his ego
wasn't as big as it used to be.
   ``I was one of Jesse's greatest critics in the 70s. I was not
convinced he was as serious about the movement as he was about
himself,'' Palmer said. ``I had quit attending PUSH because I was
convinced Jesse was not for real. Now I'm one of his biggest
supporters.''
   But some say it's the old Jackson in a new package.
   ``Jesse is for Jesse. Everything else is No. 2,'' said Marshall
Field, former owner of the Sun-Times newspaper. He declined further
comment.
   Many who have been critical in the past seem reluctant to say
anything negative about Jackson today as he glows in the successes
of his presidential campaign.
   Former Chicago Mayor Jane Byrne contends Jackson was always
capable of both protesting and trying to bring people together. ``I
don't see him any different today,'' she said.
   But Jackson backers point out that times have changed since the
South Carolina native arrived in Chicago as a semininary student in
the early 1960s _ and Jackson has changed with them.
   ``Those were the days when he was absolutely confrontational,''
said Bishop H.H. Brookins of the African Methodist Episcopal
Church, a longtime ally. ``That was the only way he got coverage
was to be confrontational ... He's much more thoughtful now than he
once was. I attribute that to maturing at the public level.''
   In the PUSH days, when Jackson was fighting to improve the
economic and political clout of blacks, he achieved many of his
goals through boycotts or the threat of boycotts, public attacks on
adversaries during revival-style PUSH meetings and an ability to
mobilize black followers.
   Recognized today as a master at using the news media, Jackson
made every effort to cultivate reporters, especially those from the
black press, said Nate Clay, a former PUSH spokesman and now editor
of the weekly Chicago Metro News.
   A workaholic who has skimmed several newspapers by 6 a.m.,
Jackson knew how to make headlines, Clay said. He gave his staff
tips on how to give reporters short, snappy quotations.
   ``He did not hesitate to call up editors and make his views
known on editorials and stories,'' and before long Jackson was the
one who was called by reporters for comment on the various civil
rights stories of the day.
   ``If I was critical of him, he'd almost always call and try to
talk it out,'' said Chicago Tribune columnist Mike Royko. ``Even if
I was 100 percent right, I'd spend the next three days walking
around with my liberal guilt throbbing.''
   Royko said Jackson tried to persuade rather than intimidate him.
But a former Chicago Sun-Times official said that Jackson would
make threatening calls ``unless the Sun-Times did exactly what he
wanted.''
   ``He would say it was anti-black,'' and threaten to make a
public uproar over the matter, said the newspaper official, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1215EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson-Change Bjt-1stAdd   05-07 0850</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Change, Bjt-1st Add,0876</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CHICAGO: of anonymity.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   On one occasion, Jackson saw a new black reporter on TV, Clay
recalled.
   ``He started asking around the room, `Who is that?' A week or so
later, this reporter was at Jesse's house. Jesse told him he had an
exclusive for him.''
   That was typical of the way Jackson would ``cultivate anybody
who could do him a favor,'' Clay said. ``Jesse has a knack of going
around picking up people like some people pick up stray dogs.''
   ``He certainly was very fiery,'' in those days, said Chicago
political consultant Don Rose, who now says his previously reported
description of Jackson conniving to grab the mantle of the slain
Dr. Martin Luther King has been overblown.
   Rose said in a recent interview that the day after King's 1968
assassination in Memphis, Jackson asked Rose to set up a couple of
TV interviews for him in Chicago.
   In general conversation, according to Rose, the two subsequently
fell to discussing how Jackson ``had terrific potential to become
the leader of the movement.''
   But Rose said there was no concerted plan, as he had been quoted
saying, to engineer that eventuality.
   In any event, Jackson for two days wore a turtleneck _ even in a
King memorial service of the Chicago City Council _ stained with
what he said was King's blood.
   He told the council: ``I come here with a heavy heart because on
my chest is the stain of blood from Dr. King's head.''
   Jackson's biographer, Barbara Reynolds, said that more than 100
articles in the year after King's assassination reported that
King's blood was on Jackson's shirt and that Jackson had cradled
the dying leader or that he was the last person King had spoken to.
All these details are disputed by some King associates who were
present on the balcony of the Lorraine motel in Memphis, Tenn.,
where King was shot.
   Jackson has been vague in more resent interviews on the events
in Memphis. He said in an interview on television's Phil Donahue
show in April that it was not true he had not touched the dying
King. He said he ran up to the balcony after a sheet had been put
over the body. ``I then got up from a very bloody scene,'' he said.
``Blood was everywhere.''
   Mistrust of Jackson lingers from those days. King's widow,
Coretta Scott King, and some other civil rights colleagues refuse
to endorse Jackson.
   In his campaign, Jackson frequently cites his ties to King, but
the Rev. Hosea Williams, an Atlanta city councilman, said Jackson
``could never work as a team person,'' with King or other members
of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
   Williams recalled a staff meeting where Jackson stubbornly
challenged King's ideas.
   ``It got so ridiculous that Dr. King got up and walked out. As
he got to the door, he turned around and he said, `Jesse, if you
want to start your own national orgnization you can do so, but you
don't have to destroy me ...''
   Ultimately, Jackson split with SCLC leaders over finances and
the leadership of the Operation Breadbasket arm of SCLC which he
headed.
   Jackson's longtime friend and pastor, the Rev. Clay Evans,
contended some were jealous of Jackson because of his stature and
support.
   In Chicago, ``he was the movement,'' Evans said. ``Without him
there wouldn't have been any movement.''
   Jackson's fame grew as he took on everything from housing
discrimination and youth problems and signed minority opportunity
pacts with such companies as Anheuser Busch, Burger King, Heublein
and Coca Cola.
   One day he would be launching boycott against Coca Cola, telling
blacks ``Don't choke on Coke.'' The next day he might be pledging
to defeat a proposed police chief or school board member.
   ``Nobody wants to be on PUSH's so-called list,'' said Heublein
spokesman Erik Pierce. ``He wasn't just a ragtag individual. He was
head of a significant organization.''
   PUSH had 32 chapters nationwide and Jackson's weekly sermons
were carried on live radio every Saturday.
   ``I think anybody that was in business knew about Jesse
Jackson,'' said Frank Sellinger, former head of Schlitz Brewery.
   The Schlitz-PUSH pact was signed before Sellinger arrived in the
late 1970s. But he said he heard from Jackson later when Jackson
fought the brewery's efforts to force out an unprofitable black
distributor.
   ``If PUSH decided to get on your case about something, you got a
real fight on your hands,'' said Evans. ``PUSH became the eyes, the
ears and the feet of the black community.''
   Those who dealt with Jackson say he was as canny and in control
behind closed corporate doors as he was firing up his followers.
   ``It wasn't a lot of yelling ... but it was, `You're going to do
this,''' said Pierce of Heublein.
   ``He was very businesslike. I found him to be tough but fair,''
said former Schlitz spokesman Ben Barkin. He said Jackson `'made it
clear his demands were either, or else.''
   Former Heublein spokesman John Cox said he never dreaded going
to the PUSH negotiations. Jackson was ``electric and charismatic,''
and a sharp negotiator.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MethodistMeeting Bjt   05-07 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Methodist Meeting, Bjt,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United Methodist Conference Moves Church Toward Middle Ground</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberal and conservative wings of the United
Methodist church, often in conflict over issues such as
homosexuality, seemed to find a middle ground and reached a
surprising reconciliation at their just-concluded governing
conference.
   ``We've seen here a real coming together,'' said the Rev. Dennis
M. Campbell of Duke University Divinity School in North Carolina.
``There has been a great spirit of inclusiveness and openness.''
   Bishop Earl G. Hunt of Lakeland, Fla., outgoing president of the
Council of Bishops, said, ``We moved back to our moorings.''
   The 9.6-million-member United Methodist church, the second
largest in American Protestantism next to the Southern Baptist
Convention, wound up its 11-day conference Friday night.
   The conference's centerpiece achievement was a new doctrinal
summary, adopted overwhelmingly by the nearly 1,000 delegates after
keen differences between liberals and conservatives were amicably
resolved in committee.
   That 10,000-word document covers basic beliefs, emphasizing the
primacy of Scripture but also affirming the value of theological
exploration.
   As the church's compass for the years ahead, it drew accolades
from all sides, conservative, liberal and in-between.
   Terming it ``a miracle,'' the Rev. Donald Messer, a Denver
theologian who had objected to an earlier draft as suppressive,
applauded the modified and approved version as a win for everyone.
   It also was hailed by conservatives. The Rev. James Heidinger of
Wilmore, Ky., head of an evangelical caucus called Good News, said
it provided ``a good distinction between doctrinal norms and
theological process.''
   Both wings also indicated that same sort of satisfaction with
other major decisions by the conference, including its adoption of
a new hymnal and stands on homosexuality.
   While the church traditionally has been socially activist,
conservatives had charged that it had swung too far in that
direction.
   ``Righteousness prevailed,'' said the Rev. Edmond Robb, an
evangelist from Marshall, Texas. ``Liberals listened to the grass
roots. There has been a mellowing on both sides.''
   From the other camp, the Rev. James A. Wall of Chicago,
influential Methodist editor of the ecumenical weekly Christian
Century, said: ``What impressed me was the more conciliatory mood.
As a liberal, I was not bothered to see a clear shift to
accommodate conservatives in the church.''
   He said national church leadership previously had gotten ``out
of step with the constituency'' and called the new position ``more
centrist.''
   The high level of consensus was indicated by overwhelming
concurrence in the key votes, usually more than 80 or 90 percent of
the delegates. Only on subsidiary matters did any wide divisions
show up, and these were rare.
   The lengthiest debate, nearly four hours, came on the issue of
homosexuality. The debate ended with the church reaffirming its ban
on active homosexuals in the ministry and condemning such activity
generally.
   But the vote on that also showed strong support _ 80 percent _
in affirming this stand: ``Although we do not condone the practice
of homosexuality and consider this practice incompatible with
Christian teaching, we affirm that God's grace is available to
all.''
   That phrase was added to point up inclusion of everyone,
whatever their sins, within the church's caring. So were several
confessions of the church's insufficient understandings of sexual
complexities.
   The church ordered a comprehensive scientific-theological
inquiry into homosexuality as well biblical-ethical analysis.
   ``Homosexuality has proved to be particularly troubling to
conscientious Christians of differing opinions,'' the church said,
with ``important questions'' remaining in dispute.
   ``It's a tacit recognition that there is some legitimacy to
various points of view,'' said the Rev. George McClain of New
York's Staten Island, executive of the Methodist Federation for
Social Action.
   A big conference step was adoption of an updated 960-page book
of ritual, psalms and hymns, sticking to masculine imagery in the
lyrics about God, but using sexually inclusive language about
people.
   There also are three new hymns allegorically portraying the
feminine aspects of God, and added Hispanic, black, Korean and
other ethnic songs and spirituals.
   Delegates stiffened their stand on abortion, condemning it as
means of birth control or for selecting a baby's sex.
   Summing up the conference, the Rev. Spurgeon Dunnam of Dallas
said:
   ``Traditional categories of right and left just don't fit this
conference. The pronounced effort has been to come together to
build consensus. I've sensed a lot of moving toward each other.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
