<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SwissFamily     05-07 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swiss Family,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Naturalizes Family, Stops Immigration Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge was moved by a Swiss family's
problems with immigration officials, so he had his clerk draw up
the paperwork and made them citizens on the spot.
   ``You come off the bench thinking this is what they hired you to
do,'' said U.S. District Judge Carl Rubin. ``It's called justice.''
   Pietro and Birgitte Semadeni and their sons, Reto and Fortunat,
have been in the United States since 1975 and in the Cincinnati
area for six years.
   They thought the Immigration and Naturalization Service had
granted their request for permanent residence in 1981, so they
applied for citizenship.
   Nothing happened.
   They hired an attorney, Hope Levitt Frye, who asked Rubin on
Friday to order the INS to act on the citizenship request. She said
INS agents in New York repeatedly lost the family's request for
residency and that unusual paperwork delays occurred after their
residency hearing took place.
   Ms. Frye said that despite the delays, INS officers assured
Semadeni that his permanent residency had been approved and told
him he could switch jobs.
   Semadeni came to the United States with a Swiss company and left
to join Borden Chemical Co. in Cincinnati. He now runs his own
import-export chemical company.
   INS attorney Russell A. Elzot admitted the agency made mistakes,
but argued that the Semadenis were in this country illegally
because the head of the family switched jobs before winning
permanent residence.
   Rubin ordered the INS to include the Semadenis in a June
naturalization ceremony, but Ms. Frye jumped up and urged Rubin,
``Do it today.''
   She explained that the INS could initiate deportation
proceedings before the naturalization ceremony and that the
Semadenis could be ineligible for naturalization if immediate
action were not taken.
   ``This thing got to me emotionally,'' the judge said later. ``I
had to adjourn court for a while.''
   He returned to the bench and ordered the clerk's office to
prepare citizenship certificates. ``They were up here in 10
minutes,'' Rubin said.
   Courtroom deputy Stephen Snyder administered the oath.
   ``I don't think I have ever seen a judge understand what was at
stake so quickly and fix it,'' Ms. Frye said.
   Elzot said the INS reserved the right to appeal Rubin's ruling,
but said the decision was out of his hands.
</TEXT>
