<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Election Bjt   05-07 0794</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election, Bjt,0819</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The French Choose A President Sunday</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters got 24 hours of calm Saturday to decide who
will be their next president after a tumultuous week during which
hostages were freed in Lebanon and New Caledonia and the candidates
ended their campaigns.
   President Francois Mitterrand, 71, a Socialist seeking a second
seven-year term, remained the favorite in Sunday's runoff against
55-year-old conservative Premier Jacques Chirac.
   Still, Chirac was expected to benefit from the release Wednesday
of the last three French hostages in Lebanon and the assault
Thursday on Melanesian separatists in New Caledonia that freed 22
policemen and a prosecutor.
   Under French law, no polls can be published the week before an
election, so it was impossible to determine how much Chirac may
have gained.
   The official campaign ended Friday night with the last political
rallies, the final radio and television appeals to France's 38.3
million registered voters. The law prohibits campaigning on the day
before an election.
   In the first round of the election April 24, Mitterrand won 34.1
percent of the vote in the field of nine candidates. Chirac was
second with 19.9 percent. The last polls, published a week ago,
predicted Mitterrand would win from 53 to 57 percent of the vote.
   Speaking before an estimated 50,000 people at a final rally
Friday night in the southwestern city of Toulouse, the president
said he was waging his ``ultimate political battle,'' noting that
he needed more than just Socialist votes to win a new term.
   ``We are not sufficiently numerous ourselves,'' he said. ``We
need Frenchmen beyond our ranks, to surpass our own borders.''
   Mitterrand flew to the Netherlands on Saturday to address the
closing session of the European International Movement, a private
organization formed in 1948 to promote the idea of Europe-wide
cooperation.
   Chirac, in an interview Saturday in the right-wing newspaper Le
Figaro, asked voters to think carefully.
   ``Who, between Mr. Mitterrand and myself, allowed unemployment
and insecurity to grow?'' he asked. ``Who has started to reduce
them? Who encouraged clandestine immigration? Who, to the contrary,
put an end to laxism?''
   He said that when the French compare the results of five years
of Socialist government, from 1981 to 1986, and two years of
center-right government following the conservative victory in the
1986 legislative elections, they will see who has succeeded.
   Chirac said the incidents in Lebanon and New Caledonia were not
timed to coincide with the election. He also said the return to
France of a secret agent who was convicted in New Zealand of
sinking a Greenpeace ship was not related to the campaign.
   ``The conditions of the release of the hostages in Lebanon
conformed with honor and dignity, without a shadow of a deal with
terrorist groups, without the shadow of reciprocity,'' he said.
   Nonetheless, the events became an element in the last hours of
the campaign.
   ``France has recovered one by one its children, held far from
here,'' said Culture Minister Francois Leotard. ``It would not be
appropriate if the real author of this French success, Jacques
Chirac, is unrewarded on Sunday.''
   Despite the fact that the releases were the work of the Chirac
government, Mitterrand said he ``contributed'' to the success.
   ``There is no distinction between the government and me in such
a sensitive matter,'' he said.
   Attention also was focused on what would happen immediately
after the election results are known Sunday night.
   For the past two years, Mitterrand and Chirac have been living
in an uneasy marriage, known as ``cohabitation,'' created when the
right ousted the Socialists from control of the National Assembly.
   Chirac's conservatives still have a majority in the Assembly,
whose term does not end until 1991.
   If Chirac wins, the matter is simple. He will continue his
present policies with a government similar to the one now in place.
   But, Mitterrand has the power to dissolve the Assembly and call
new elections. But he has said that if he wins, he will try to work
with the present Parliament and attempt to form a center-left
coalition with wavering center-right deputies.
   If that does not succeed, he will call new elections.
   Most analysts believe that the man Mitterrand names as his
premier will depend on his margin of victory. Two former Socialist
finance ministers, Pierre Beregovoy and Jacques Delors, are
frequently mentioned, as are Jean-Louis Bianco, his chief of staff,
and popular former Agriculture Minister Michel Rocard.
   If the margin is narrow, he could opt for a centrist outside the
ranks of the Socialist Party.
   The surprising strength of extreme right leader Jean-Marie Le
Pen, who won 14.4 percent of the first-round vote, has increased
speculation that some centrists who backed Chirac would join a
Mitterrand coalition.
</TEXT>
