<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Nivola     05-07 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Nivola,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian-Born Sculptor Dies On Long Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costantino Nivola, a sculptor whose
work ranged from huge bas-relief murals for public buildings to
female figurines on an intimate scale, has died of a heart attack
at the age of 76.
   Nivola died Thursday at Southampton Hospital.
   The native of Italy moved to New York in 1939 with his wife,
Ruth, and became an early champion of modern architecture, serving
as art director for Progressive Architecture and Interiors magazine.
   Among his commissions are a 110-foot-long mural for the Mutual
Insurance Co. of Hartford (Conn.) building; a war memorial in Falls
Church, Va.; a dramatic sand-sculptured wall for the former
Olivetti Co. showroom on Fifth Avenue, now at Harvard; and numerous
sculptures and wall paintings for playgrounds in and around New
York.
   He leaves unfinished a sculptural commission for a combined
police precinct and firehouse in Manhattan.
   His sculpture is currently on view in ``Three Italo-American
Artists,'' an exhibition touring in Italy.
   Nivola is survived by his wife, a son, daughter, four
grandchildren, five sisters and a brother.
</TEXT>
