<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Breakdance     05-07 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Breakdance,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beijing Holds First Breakdance Contest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of teen-agers decked out in colorful gym
shoes, glittering shirts and black leather gloves gyrated to the
sound of pulsating American rock 'n' roll Saturday in Beijing's
first breakdance contest.
   The two-day competition at the Chongwen District Culture Center
drew 420 dancers, mostly teen-age boys.
   Disco dancing and breakdancing have been critized by Chinese
officials as decadent, and dance halls in some cities have been
closed down. Only recently have authorities given reluctant
approval to the dancing.
   ``The government originally took a policy of banning rock music
and disco, but that was not correct,'' said Li Chunqing, an
official of the culture center. ``If we properly direct the
enthusiasm for breakdancing, it is very healthy.''
   Breakdancing became popular in China last year after the release
of the American film ``Breakdance.''
   There have been reports in the official media of youngsters
skipping school so they can practice their moves.
   ``I hide my breakdancing from my parents,'' said Xie Maojie, 19,
a computer company employee. Xie, wearing a sailor cap, large round
glasses and a thin tie, said he had entered the contest ``just for
the fun of it.''
   ``My parents told me I could breakdance as long as I don't
become crazy about it,'' said 15-year-old Lu Si, a student of opera
and one of the few girls in the competition.
   Most of the dancers wore baggy pants and sweatshirts. Red gym
shoes with military camouflage pants were a popular combination.
Some sported sunglasses, glittering shirts, leg warmers and black
gloves.
   Colored lights flashed from the floor and ceiling of the hall as
the dancers performed in groups of seven and eight for seven
judges. Chen Ailian, a well-known classical dancer, led the judges'
panel.
   The port city of Tianjin sponsored what might have been China's
first breakdance contest in January, and several cities have opened
breakdance classes to try to channel the dancing craze.
   Earlier reports said the far north city of Harbin had started a
dozen breakdance classes and that Beijing has 10 privately run
classes. The official Xinhua News Agency said 200 signed up for one
class of 40 in Beijing.
</TEXT>
