<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Scavenger     05-07 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Scavenger,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wild Scavenger Hunt In Two Cities Nets Odd Items, 11 Arrests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENICIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone started a scavenger hunt that
sent people racing around two cities for objects like mail boxes
and lawn chairs, but the only winners were police officers who lay
in wait for players at a meeting point.
   When it was over officers had dozens of odd items as evidence
and arrested 11 people on theft and burglary charges.
   ``We don't know who staged this, but we'd like to. We don't know
if it was a con or not,'' officer Frank Hartig said of the strange
events late Thursday.
   He said the stage was set sometime during the day when a flier
was distributed that advertised a ``scavenger hunt,'' listing
numerous items that were to be brought to the edge of town by
midnight. The winner would get a prize.
   Police found out about the hunt and ``happened to see a couple
of them driving down the road with some of the items.''
   ``We found out where the meeting was to take place,'' said
Hartig. ``As they came to drop something off, we'd take them out of
there and wait for some more.''
   When the hunt was over, police had nine adults and two juveniles
under arrest and an evidence box stuffed with mail boxes, tennis
court nets, hubcaps, windshield wipers, house plants, pay phone
receivers, house numbers, signs, garbage cans, basketball hoops,
toilet seat covers, lawn chairs and hoses.
   ``That stuff was stolen,'' Hartig said. ``They were vandalizing
and stealing.
   Hartig said the loot was lifted from Benicia and nearby Vallejo.
   ``It would be nice if we had clues to this,'' said Hartig. ``Any
help would be appreciated.'
</TEXT>
