<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Hungary-Kadar     05-07 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Hungary-Kadar,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungarian Leader Says Gorbachev Certain to Succeed in Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev is certain
to succeed in revamping Soviet society but it could take ``some
tough years,'' predicts Janos Kadar, who has led communist Hungary
for more than three decades.
   Kadar, in a U.S. television interview being broadcast Sunday,
also said there is no internal need for the 64,000 Soviet soldiers
still in Hungary, only ``international reasons.'' Hopefully in the
coming decade, he said, ``relations in Europe will develop in such
a manner that there will be no need for them.''
   The process of perestroika, or restructuring, launched by
Gorbachev ``will be victorious in spite of all the difficulties''
because it means progress for the Soviet people and because ``the
situation is ripe for it,'' Kadar said.
   But there are differences over the pace of change and ``it will
take years before serious results can be seen ... some tough
years,'' said the 75-year-old Hungarian communist party chief whose
reputation as an Eastern block reformer predates that of Gorbachev.
   Kadar talked in Budapest on April 25 with Washington-based
journalist John McLaughlin. The taped interview was scheduled for
broadcast on McLaughlin's ``One on One'' program.
   Kadar became head of the Hungarian Socialist Workers (Communist)
Party after Soviet forces invaded in 1956 to crush a popular
uprising.
   If American forces had intervened in the 1956 upheaval, a
U.S.-Soviet clash would have been inevitable, Kadar said. The West
did not intervene.
   ``I wish that Soviet and American troops never meet anywhere as
enemies in battle,'' he said. ``But as a Hungarian, I desired least
of all that they come into conflict on Hungarian soil,'' he added.
   Kadar, who in Western eyes a villain of the 1956 Hungarian
tragedy, gained a new image in the next three decades as a
dedicated architect of political and economic liberalization aimed
at improving Hungarian life.
   Today, Hungary is one of the more prosperous of the Soviet bloc
countries, one of the easiest to visit for Westerners, including
refugees of 1956, and its citizens have the easiest time leaving.
   Hungarian reform does not serve as a model for Moscow but
Gorbachev admits the Kremlin can learn from Hungary and Soviet
changes make it ``easier for us now,'' Kadar said.
   He acknowledged that the Hungarian economy, after some dynamic
growth, slowed down and started having serious problems seven or
eight years ago, but said ``the path continues to be that of
reform.''
   On the political side, Kadar said Hungary's rulers recognize
today that ``If we cannot convince people about the necessity of
certain steps ... it is possible to decree, but in reality it
cannot be carried out.''
   A Western multiparty system ``cannot be constructed in
Hungary,'' Kadar said. But in June, at the first general party
conference since 1957, efforts will be made to create ``socialist
pluralism'' reducing party control, improving consultation and
giving more responsibility to non-party bodies, he continued.
   The line, however, will be drawn against anarchy, and groups
``working against the system'' will not be legalized, he said.
</TEXT>
