<DOCNO> AP880507-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1317EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     05-07 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebels Pick Through Rubble Of Soviet-Afghan Garrison</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARIKOT, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A poster of Vladimir I. Lenin peers
out from behind heaps of dusty rubble onto a main street choked
with thousands of Afghan army uniforms.
   The green-and-white flag of the Moslem resistance, hung atop the
old local headquarters of the Soviet army, flaps in the mountain
wind.
   Below, Moslem insurgents pick through the remains of their
prize: the former Soviet-Afghan garrison of Barikot.
   On April 20, anti-communist guerrillas launched a furious rocket
and grenade attack on this strategic post, about a mile west of the
Pakistan border.
   The town soon fell but not before Soviet and Afghan forces fled
in a series of helicopter airlifts.
   Barikot was the first of at least six outposts in eastern
Afghanistan that have fallen to the guerrillas since the Soviets
began pulling away from the region in preparation for their
withdrawal from Afghanistan, set to begin May 15.
   It also opened an important new supply route in the insurgents'
fight to oust the communist government in Kabul.
   ``The fall of Barikot opens the transportation route to the
provinces of Badakshan, Kunduz, Baghlan, Laghman and Parwan,'' said
Commander Lalgul of the Hezb-I-Islami Yunis Khalis faction.
   Those Afghanistan provinces lie to the east, north and west of
Kabul, and include the main route which the Soviets are expected to
take as they head home to the Soviet Union.
   The Soviet army entered Afghaninstan eight years ago to replace
one communist administration with another and fight Afghan
guerrillas who opposed the Soviet-backed government in Kabul.
   On April 14, the Soviet Union agreed to withdraw its estimated
115,000 troops from Afghanistan under a plan it signed in Geneva
with Pakistan, Afghanistan and the United States. The guerrillas do
not recognize the agreement and have vowed to keep fighting until
they smash the Kabul government.
   The victory at Barikot did much for their cause.
   About 60 percent of this sun-baked town was destroyed in massive
Soviet-Afghan bombings following the evacuation.
   But plenty remains: huge stashes of arms, artillery, ammunition,
armored and conventional military vehicles, and deadly booby traps.
   Guerrillas say as many as 10 returning Afghan refugees were
killed by land mines as they returned to the garrison town from
Pakistan.
   But as the death toll mounted, guerrillas pushed the refugees
back across the precarious wood-plank suspension bridge that spans
the Kunar River to Pakistan and only guerrillas were allowed near
the town.
   Traveling on narrow footpaths, the insurgents keep their eyes on
the ground, searching for booby traps and mines.
   In the grassy, rock-strewn fields around Barikot, remnants of
helicopters rust in the sun. The guerrillas say they were downed
with U.S.-supplied Stinger anti-aircraft missiles.
   ``Commander Shahafullah is the Stinger commander. He shot down a
(Soviet) MiG-27,'' boasted Zahir Khan, a member of the Khalis
faction.
   Lalgul said an old man left behind in the village told him many
villagers were forced to board waiting helicopters at gunpoint.
   When the army served notice that every man, woman and child
would be flown out of Barikot, Lalgul said the old man told him:
   ``Women kissed the wall and asked, `Why do we want to go?'''
   The commander said Afghan militia and army officers were taken
to Mazar-E-Sharif, about 45 miles south of the Soviet border in
order ``to fortify the north.''
   He did not elaborate.
   Guerrillas and Western diplomats have said they believe the
Soviets and Afghanistan's Marxist leaders will create a security
zone in the north in case Kabul falls. Some have even suggested
that the Soviets want to create a ``communist zone'' in the north.
   Despite fears that the seven main guerrilla factions would begin
fighting each other once they defeat the communists, the flags of
four insurgent groups fly in Barikot.
   While members of Khalis' party show off some heavy artillery,
fighters of Gulbaddin Hekmatyar's Hezb-I-Islami crowd into an
abandoned truck to pose for pictures.
   On the road into town, Khalis commanders stop to greet
guerriilas of Burhanuddin Rabbani's Jamiat-I-Islami.
   On the outskirts, Zahir Khan points out the office of Abdul
Sayyaf's Ittihad-I-Islami.
   He dismissed charges that the guerrillas will turn their weapons
on each other.
   ``We are all brothers ... like one hand,'' he said.
</TEXT>
