<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SiameseTwins     05-07 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Siamese Twins,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Separated Siamese Twins Recovering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Siamese twin girls who were
joined at the head until an operation four days ago are out of
intensive care and recovering well, hospital officials said
Saturday.
   Mpho and Mphonyana Mathibela, aged 17 months, were separated in
a 7{-hour operation Tuesday by a 40-member medical team at
Baragwanath Hospital, in a black township outside Johannesburg.
   Mphonyana, the smaller and weaker of the two, required brief
follow-up surgery Wednesday. Her condition has since improved
steadily, and she was taken from the intensive care ward Friday to
join her sister in the neurosurgical ward, hospital officials said.
   Mpho has been eating solid food and taking milk from a bottle,
they said.
   Doctors said that if all goes well, the girls will need only one
more operation sometime before they reach age 6.
   Baragwanath doctors said they took a different approach to
separating the girls than a medical team used at Johns Hopkins
University in Baltimore.
   In September, the Johns Hopkins doctors separated West German
Siamese twins also joined at the head in a 22-hour operation. Since
then, Benjamin and Patrick Binder have required a dozen follow-up
operations.
   Both survived and returned to West Germany last month.
   The Baragwanath team led by Dr. Robert Lipschitz instead
performed two preliminary operations in October on the Mathibela
twins. They partially clamped a shared blood vein in hopes that
smaller vessels would take over in each child.
   The preliminary operations allowed the Baragwanath doctors to
separate the girls in a shorter final operation.
   ``We could have used the same technique they did but decided to
do diametrically the opposite because of the problems they hit,''
Lipschitz said.
   Sophie Mathibela, the mother of the twins, is a 33-year-old
unmarried domestic worker who earns about $60 a month. She was
asked to make a $5 contribution to the costs of the operations,
estimated at $700,000.
   The costs are being covered by the hospital and the University
of the Witwatersrand medical school.
</TEXT>
