<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Reagan-ArmsControl     05-07 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Arms Control,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Urges Swift Senate Ratification of Arms Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Saturday urged the Senate
to swiftly ratify a pending arms control treaty and ``enable us to
get on with the job of eliminating these nuclear missiles.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., has tentatively
set Wednesday for the start of Senate debate on the treaty, which,
if ratified, would require the elimination of U.S. and Soviet
ground-launched intermediate- and shorter-range nuclear weapons.
   Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed the treaty
at their summit in Washington in December, and Reagan submitted it
to the Senate the following month.
   The president said Saturday he is confident that the treaty will
be ratified. He has said previously that he hopes this will be done
before he goes to Moscow for another meeting with Gorbachev on May
29-June 2.
   The two superpowers are currently negotiating another treaty,
dealing with longer-range intercontinental missiles, but that pact
is not expected to be completed before the Moscow summit.
   Reagan's remarks, in his weekly radio address, made no reference
to Byrd's demand for written assurances that the treaty will cover
futuristic weapons, like those using laser rays.
   An administration official, however, speaking on condition he
not be identified, said the issue has been discussed with the
Soviets and is currently being discussed with Senate leaders. The
official said the administration was confident an accomodation
could be reached.
   Reagan spoke from Camp David, the presidential retreat in the
Catoctin Mountains of Maryland.
   ``It is my hope that, in recognition of the important role they
play in this process, the 100 members of the United States Senate
will now proceed expeditiously in their debate,'' he said. ``Senate
appoval of the treaty will enable us to get on with the job of
eliminating these nuclear missiles.''
   Reviewing the history of the pact, the president said, ``We held
fast to what we wanted, and we got it. And this is what comes from
negoitiating from strength. It's the same successful formula,
dealing from strength, that we're applying to our other
negotiations with the Soviet Union as well.''
   ``I can assure you if we don't get what we want in these other
areas, if we don't get good treaties, there will be no treaties,''
he said.
   ``Now that the treaty is moving to floor debate in the Senate,
let the debate be vigorous and full,'' the president said. ``And
let it proceed without delay. For I'm confident that the final vote
will indeed give advice and consent to this historic treaty.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
