<DOCNO> AP880507-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1324EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-ElectionGlance     05-07 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election Glance,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Presidential Election at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are facts and figures on France's runoff
election on Sunday between President Francois Mitterrand and
Premier Jacques Chirac:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WHO'S ELIGIBLE:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   There are 38.3 million eligible voters, including those in
French territories in the Caribbean and Polynesia.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AT STAKE:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The presidency, a seven-year term.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE SYSTEM</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   This is the second round of voting, limited to the two
candidates who finished first and second in the first round April
24. The results of that election were: Mitterrand (Socialist) 34.1
percent, Chirac (conservative) 19.9 percent, Raymond Barre
(centrist) 16.6 percent, Jean-Marie Le Pen (extreme-right) 14.4
percent, Andre Lajoinie (Communist), 6.8 percent, Antoine Waechter
(ecologist) 3.8 percent, Pierre Juquin (splinter Communist) 2.1
percent, Arlette Laguiller (Trotskyist) 2.0 percent, Pierre Boussel
(Trotskyist) 0.4 percent.
   Presidential candidates distance themselves from their own
parties in order to attract supporters of other parties.
   Since a center-right coalition won the March 1986 legislative
elections, Chirac and Mitterrand have been governing uncomfortably
together in a power-sharing arrangement called ``cohabitation.'' If
Chirac wins, he will have control of both power centers. If
Mitterrand wins, he will still have to find a way of governing with
a right-leaning assembly _ or else call new legislative elections
in hope of a victory by the left.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE ISSUES:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Chirac and Mitterrand have few important differences in foreign
policy. In economic affairs, Chirac would continue privatization of
state-owned firms, which Mitterrand says he would halt. Mitterrand
would re-establish the Socialist wealth tax, abolished under
Chirac, and use the proceeds for a minumum guaranteed income.
   Just when it seemed Chirac had no chance of winning, his
government engineered the liberation of the last three French
hostages in Lebanon, the assault freeing police held hostage in New
Caledonia, and the popular return of a French spy from exile in the
Pacific.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>THE POLLS:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   No polls may be published in the campaign's final week. The last
surveys showed Mitterrand winning 53 percent to 57 percent of the
vote, but they could be out of date.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NewCaledonia     05-07 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Caledonia,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Separatists Vow To Continue Fighting Colonial Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL DONNET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thousand Melanesian separatists
marched Saturday in the capital of this French Pacific territory to
protest the killing of 19 kidnappers during a dramatic rescue of 23
French lawmen.
   About 500 policemen lined the streets in Noumea, but no violence
was reported during the five-hour march and rally.
   About 7,000 French police and military personnel remained on
full alert Saturday, although the Kanak Socialist National
Liberation Front, the main separatist group, said it would not
disrupt voting Sunday in the French presidential runoff.
   The first round of voting April 24 was marked by shooting, the
erection of barricades and threats of violence that kept some
polling stations closed.
   During that election, voters also chose a local territorial
council which the separatists oppose. The council is part of an
administrative plan for the archipelego set up by conservative
Premier Jacques Chirac, who received 74.6 percent of the
territory's first-round vote.
   Extreme right National Front candidate Jean-Marie Le Pen
received 12.3 percent of the vote. Socialist President Francois
Mitterrand, who Chirac faces in Sunday's runoff, garnered 4.9
percent of the vote.
   Two days before ballotting, Melanesian separatists stormed a
police station on the island of Ouvea, northeast of New Caledonia's
main island, killing four gendarmes and abducting 27 others.
   Twelve hostages were later released, but on April 27, eight
lawmen were seized while they attempted to negotiate for the
release of the other hostages, held in a cave on the north coast of
Ouvea.
   On Thursday, police stormed the cave and freed the hostages,
killing 19 of the kidnappers. Two members of the assualt team also
died. Five people were injured.
   In Paris, 57 gendarmes arrived on a commercial flight from New
Caledonia on Saturday and were greeted by Defense Minister Andre
Giraud. Among the gendarmes were 10 who had been injuried in the
latest wave of violence that began April 22.
   The gendarmes preceded Bernard Pons, minister for overseas
territories, who left Noumea for Paris on Saturday, saying his
mission had been completed with the freeing of the hostages.
   ``If I am sad because there were some dead, I also say that
those who attack someone, who attack a bank, who commit a terrorist
act, take some risks and should be ready to assume them,'' Pons
told reporters before leaving.
   Yeiwene Yeiwene, second-ranking leader of the liberation
movement, accused France of choosing blood over mediation.
   ``The nationalist Kanaks never wanted to kill the hostages. They
had all the means, they had all the time to do so had they wished.
But there were no hostages killed,'' Yeiwene said in an interview
on Radio Djiido. ``The massacre was perpetrated deliberately by Mr.
Pons, who knew ... that there was no question of killing the
hostages.''
   Speaking to separatists at the rally, liberation front spokesman
Leopold Joredie, said ``It it because the Kanak people have been
cornered that some of our sons chose the action on Ouvea.''
   Joredie said reports from separatists on Ouvea indicated that
some of the kidnappers were hunted down and killed after the attack
at the cave.
   A French armed forces spokesman denied the allegation.
   French authorities have promised that the 27 people arrested in
connection with the Ouvea kidnapping would remain in the territory
for trial. Since April 22, 49 people have been arrested for acts of
separatist violence in the territory.
   Native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, make up 36 percent of the
145,000 inhabitants of the territory. Forty-three percent are
European settlers, with the rest of the population made up of
Asians and Polynesians.
   New Caledonia was colonized by France in 1853.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
