<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-Trade     05-07 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Trade,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats: Trade Bill Veto Would Play Into Hands Of Foreign
Interests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trade bill veto would play into the hands of
foreign governments who conducted massive lobbying against the
measure, a Democratic lawmaker said Saturday in response to
President Reagan's weekly radio address.
   Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., said the bill would ``stop trade
cheating by foreign nations'' and urged Reagan to sign the
legislation.
   Reagan has said he plans to veto the bill because of a plant
closing notification provision.
   The bill would overhaul the nation's system for imposing import
curbs to retaliate against international trade violations and aid
American industries threatened by stepped-up foreign competition.
   Supporters say the revised rules would force other nations,
particularly Japan, Korea and Taiwan, to open their markets to U.S.
goods.
   ``Every citizen should urge President Reagan to sign the trade
bill,'' said Riegle, an author of some of the bill's provisions.
   He cited an estimate by the New York Federal Reserve Board that
the United States within three years will owe the rest of the world
$1 trillion, and noted that the trade deficit was building each
year.
   ``We must reverse the trade deficit now. We must stop this
massive debt accumulation, and keep our jobs and our money from
hemorrhaging overseas,'' he said.
   Riegle urged Reagan ``to reject the massive lobbying power of
foreign governments and companies, who have gotten rich on unfair
trade'' and who worked ``day and night to kill this trade bill.''
   ``Many nations will not let U.S. products be sold in their
countries. Yes, they sell to us, but they refuse to buy from us,''
Riegle said.
   He cited the failure last week of negotiations between the
United States and Japan over Japanese restrictions on imports of
beef and oranges.
   ``Just this week they said `no' again to U.S. beef and citrus
products. That's wrong, and it must be changed,'' Riegle said.
   Riegle said the trade crisis ``threatens every job in America.''
He said the plant-closing provision that prompted Reagan's veto
promise is necessary to help workers prepare for ``the shock of a
major job loss.''
   The provision would require all but the smallest employers to
provide 60-day notice of closings and large-scale layoffs. The
administration opposes the provision, saying it would cramp U.S.
economic growth and encourage companies to locate elsewhere by
adding new federal regulation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
