<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CongressmanTransplant     05-07 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressman Transplant,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Doing Well Following Rare Double Lung Transplant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., should fully
recover from Saturday's rare double-lung transplant before
November, when voters have to decide whether to give him a 10th
term in office, his doctor said.
   ``I think the Congressman has tremendous spirit. He wants to do
things. I suspect his recovery period should be very short,'' said
the leader of the University of Mississippi Medical Center
transplant team, Dr. Seshadri Raju.
   Raju said the 60-year-old Spence was on a respirator in critical
but stable condition after five hours of surgery concluded about 3
a.m. Saturday.
   Spence suffered from chronic obstructive lung disease, a
hereditary and debilitating illness that doctors say would have
taken his life without the transplant.
   ``If everything goes satisfactorily, I think he will be
recovered much, much earlier than that (November),'' Raju said. The
congressman should be able to take calls from his bed ``within a
week a two I'm sure, maybe sooner.''
   Prior to the surgery, Raju had said Spence would be able to
resume a normal schedule within six months with ``surprisingly
little'' in the way of physical restrictions.
   Spence had awakened from the anesthesia by noon Saturday and was
visited by his fiancee, 37-year-old Deborah Williams of Lexington,
S.C., said the congressman's press secretary, Randy Mashburn.
Spence is a widower.
   The congressman's four sons also were with him, Mashburn said.
   However, Mashburn declined to comment on the possibility the
congressman would be campaigning before his November contest
against Democratic challenger Jim Leventis.
   ``I don't want to answer any political questions right now. We
just want to get this man healthy and back on his feet,'' Mashburn
said.
   Confined at times to a wheelchair and occasionally in need of
oxygen, Spence has made few public appearances since last October,
when he went on a list of potential organ transplant recipients.
   The hospital is a member of an organ donor network that seeks to
match organs with recipients, medical center spokeswoman Barbara
Austin said.
   Spence's new lungs were flown in from a donor in Tyler, Texas,
and Friday night Spence was flown to Jackson.
   ``Floyd had been meeting with his constitutents in his
congressional office (in Columbia, S.C.) all afternoon when his
beeper went off,' Mashburn said. ``We took off.''
   Double-lung transplants have been performed 30 times worldwide
and only 13 times in North America, Austin said.
   The Jackson hospital has now done four of the transplants, but
two of the patients died. Medical Center officials attributed one
of the deaths to factors unrelated to either the surgery or
respiratory ailments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1358EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Democrats-Text     05-07 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Text,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Text Of Democratic Response To Reagan's Radio Address</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Democrats-Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is the text of the Democratic response
Saturday to President Reagan's weekly radio address.
   This is Senator Don Riegle from Michigan. If you work for a
living, or have children or other family members who work for a
living, then you have a vital stake in the trade bill just passed
by Congress.
   America today faces a trade crisis. That trade crisis threatens
every job in America. There's an urgent need to change our trade
laws in order to save and create American jobs.
   Congress has passed a strong trade bill that will strengthen
America and stop other nations from cheating us in world trade. We
need this law _ and every citizen should urge President Reagan to
sign the trade bill.
   Listen to these figures. Our trade deficit as a nation is
running at the rate of $166 billion a year. The most recent monthly
trade deficit was so bad it knocked the stock market down over 100
points in a single day. We have become the largest debtor nation,
and are adding new international debt at the rate of $1 billion
every two and a half days. That's right _ $1 billion of new foreign
debt every two and a half days. This poses great dangers to our
future.
   The New York Federal Reserve Board says that within three years,
we will owe the rest of the world $1 trillion. A trillion dollars
is a thousand billion. It's incredible.
   We must reverse the trade deficit now. We must stop this massive
debt accumulation _ and keep our jobs and our money from
hemorrhagging overseas.
   Now, here's what the trade bill will do _ first, it will stop
trade cheating by foreign nations. Many nations will not let U.S.
products be sold in their countries. They sell to us _ but refuse
to buy from us. Japan alone is running a $60 billion trade surplus
with the United States _ and draining $5 billion of capital a month
from our economic system.
   Yet Japan will not allow many U.S. products to be sold in Japan.
Just this week they said ``no'' again to U.S. beef and citrus
products. That's wrong, and it must be changed.
   This trade bill requires fair, open, two-way trade. We must
insist on fair trade _ if we're going to preserve America's
economic strength and our leadership in the world.
   The trade bill also provides needed help and retraining for U.S.
workers who lose their jobs because of the trade invasion. Now that
makes good sense. No American worker should be thrown on the scrap
heap. We should help every citizen remain productive and
self-sufficient. It is a responsibility we have to each other.
   Another key provision of the trade bill requires 60 days advance
notice when large plant closings or layoffs are going to take
place. That's only fair. Workers and communities need this advance
warning to prepare for the shock of a major job loss. Maybe a way
can be found to prevent the closing.
   Companies that cannot foresee the closing ahead of time are
exempt from this new law. Advance notice makes good sense.
Management, workers and communities should share this information
for the good of all. We must care about each other _ and really
work as a team, if we're going to increase productivity, lift our
living standard and fight off foreign competition. If management
knows ahead of time that a plant will close, why shouldn't workers
and the community?
   Overall then, the trade bill insists on fair trading rules and
helps our country adjust to the tough new demands of world
competition.
   Mr. President, we urge you to listen to the American people and
to the large bipartisan majority in Congress that wrote this vital
trade bill. Our economic future is at stake.
   We ask you to sign the bill. Let's give America the tools it
needs to sell overseas and stop the massive mortgage of foreign
debt being strapped on every person in America. Let's act while
there's still time.
   We ask you to stand up for our country, to stand up for trade
fairness, to stand up for the job future of every young person in
America. We can win _ if the trade rules are fair.
   We ask you to reject the massive lobbying power of foreign
governments and companies _ who have gotten rich on unfair trade _
and who are working day and night to kill this trade bill with a
presidential veto.
   Mr. President _ sign the trade bill into law and give us all the
chance to build a strong economic future the old-fashioned American
way: top notch individual effort, teamwork and fair rules. American
can win _ if we have a fair chance.
</TEXT>
