<DOCNO> AP880507-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Tailors Bjt   05-07 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tailors, Bjt,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men of the Cloth Celebrate Despite Zoning Threat To Savile Row</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tailors of Savile Row, Britain's world-famous
custom tailoring district, took to the street with their needles,
thread and scissors Saturday for a fitting centennial celebration.
   To kick off events marking the Federation of Merchant Tailors'
100th anniversary, a team of 20 cutters, tailors and finishers
assembled a gray striped woolen suit in just nine hours.
   The cornerstone of a gentleman's wardrobe normally would take
eight weeks to complete, require one or two fittings, and cost
$1,400 to $2,250, said federation president Robert Bright.
   ``I'm taking the opportunity of the centenary to remove the
metaphoric frosted windows and curtained windows that were a
feature of tailor shops for far too long,'' said Bright, also
chairman of the 159-year-old Wells of Mayfair firm.
   Savile Row, a short, narrow street in central London, was sealed
off to traffic and tents were erected where passers-by could watch
the 90 separate steps involved in fashioning a three-piece suit.
   The marathon pinning, basting and sewing session began at 9 a.m.
with the cutting of the fabric, and the last button was in place by
6:12 p.m.
   Martyn Lewis, a British Broadcasting Corp. TV anchorman with a
34-inch waist and 41-inch chest, was the guinea pig. He requested
only that the garment be made ``for sitting down in'' so he could
read the news without any inelegant wrinkling of the lapel of his
``bespoke'' suit _ a term derived from customers ``bespeaking''
their individual requirements.
   ``One of the aspects of a bespoke suit is that it is only right
for the person for whom it's made,'' Bright said, adding that Lewis
was getting the suit for free. ``The whole styling and the cutting
needs to embrace his personality and coloring as well as his
figuration.''
   Savile Row has been synonymous with conservative men's fashions
since the mid-1800s, when Henry Poole and Co. opened its back door
onto the street.
   Other tailors followed and the influx of tradesmen so upset
wealthy doctors living in the fashionable residential neighborhood
that they fled to Harley Street.
   Now, Savile Row is threatened by new planning laws, Bright said.
   Until last summer, light industry and offices were separate
planning categories, and permission was required to change from one
to the other. Both now fall into a new general business category.
   The government said it was trying to revitalize inner cities by
loosening planning laws. But Bright said that means tailors'
workshops in Savile Row and adjoining Soho can be redeveloped into
more lucrative office space without official permission.
   He expects rents to quadruple, followed by tax increases. Some
landlords already are asking about $95 a square foot, he said.
   ``It is an enormous threat. There is no way the French would
just pass up their haute couture industry, and yet this government
is quite prepared to write off the top of the British clothing
industry as if it didn't matter.''
   Bright said it's difficult to find words to describe the
pleasures of bespoke tailoring.
   ``It's an experience. It is a feeling of confidence that you
know that you are projecting just the image that you want to
project, the part of your personality that you want to speak ... We
are, in fact, creating a portrait in cloth,'' he said.
   With a ready-made suit ``you have to conform not only to a given
set of measures, but also to what the designer wants you to look
like when he hasn't even seen you,'' Bright said.
   A bespoke suit should last a decade, providing it hangs in the
closet for six days between wearings so the wool can recover its
bounce; hence, the advice that a proper English gentleman owns
seven suits, one for each day of the week.
   Bright said Savile Row does $48 million annual business,
including $32 million overseas.
   Anderson and Sheppard are known as the royal tailors, although
several windows on the row prominently display royal warrants,
proving they do business with Buckingham Palace.
   Poole's received it first royal warrant from Napoleon, and later
outfitted Ethiopia's Emperor Haile Selassie.
   Huntsman and Sons, which keeps saddles in each of its five
fitting rooms, made riding breeches for King Edward VIII, who
abdicated to marry the American, Wallis Simpson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0122 </DOCNO>
