<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-07 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLIANCE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A monument of old cars set upright in the
ground to resemble Great Britain's Stonehenge can stay so long as
it's insured and vandals don't turn the area into a junkyard, the
City Council said.
   ``Carhenge'' creator James Reinders, formerly of Alliance, now
of Houston, built the monument last June on land he owns north of
here. It consists of cars set in the ground and other cars welded
across the top.
   The council approved the permit request on a 4-0 vote Thursday
with four stipulations.
   Reinders must obtain $100,000 worth of liability insurance, get
the necessary permits from the Nebraska Department of Roads to
construct an apron off the highway, build a parking lot and provide
a performance bond to ensure Carhenge is kept up.
   City Manager Wolfgang Bauer said state officials agree that if
the vehicles are vandalized, Carhenge would become a junkyard.
   Mayor Rich Robb said some rural people have had nothing positive
to say about Carhenge.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MARIETTA, GA. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The idea of plunking down money for the
privilege of quaffing some ritzy, imported bubbly stuff _ water,
that is _ apparently doesn't go over as well in Georgia as it does
in California.
   Owners of a ``water bar'' restaurant decided to close down after
demand for their non-alcoholic, health-related beverages dried up.
   Club Soda opened in this Atlanta suburb in October as an
alternative to Atlanta's innumerable bars and nightclubs. In
addition to a regular menu and alcoholic drinks, it offered as many
as 75 kinds of water and seltzer for up to $6 for a large bottle of
the deluxe stuff.
   But it didn't catch on, said owner Jim Killeen, despite the
success of similar establishments in California.
   ``We felt it was strong enough to warrant investing a
half-million dollars into the concept,'' Killeen said. ``But it
never materialized. People just weren't interested in coming into
that type of establishment for health-related beverages.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SHALLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top students at West Brunswick High
School can parlay their potential into bonuses including free
lunches, bumper stickers, sunglasses and preferred seating at
athletic events.
   ``It encourages perhaps-borderline students to do better,''
Spanish teacher Nancy Turner said. ``I've heard kids say they are
one point away, and they want to make it.''
   The new rewards program, modeled after a 4-year-old program in
Conway, S.C., has created excitement about achievement, she said.
   At the end of each six-week grading period, the program doles
out gold cards to students who earn all A's. Green cards go to
students who receive all A's and B's.
   Card-holders qualify for certain privileges _ preferred seating
at home athletic events and close-in parking spaces, time off for
independent study _ and various material items.
   ``Last year, we didn't get anything,'' said Brent Tyndall.
``This makes you want to maintain your grades because each six
weeks you get something every day.''
   An alternate opinion was voiced by Martin Bolick.
   ``I don't see myself busting my tail for a T-shirt,'' he said.
   But some who earned C's said the program had inspired them to
work harder.
   ``I miss it every week by one point,'' said Veronica Jenrette.
``I think it is a good idea, though. It gives them recognition.''
</TEXT>
