<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1438EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HassamFlags     05-07 0399</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hassam Flags,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flag Paintings Show Opens at National Gallery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rare exhibition of American impressionist
painter Childe Hassam's flag pictures explodes into view Sunday at
the National Gallery of Art with all the brilliant optimism of a
Fourth of July fireworks display.
   It is the first time since 1922, before the artist's death, that
his patriotic canvases from World War I have been drawn from widely
scattered public museums and private collections and shown
together. The lenders include IBM, Frank Sinatra and the White
House.
   Hassam, the most important American impressionist at the turn of
the century, was enthralled by the majesty and symbolic power of
the U.S. and Allied flags, banners and bunting that festooned New
York City streets _ mostly along Fifth Avenue _ for wartime parades
and fund-raising rallies.
   His 31 flag pictures, painted from 1916 until the war ended in
1919, are ``pre-eminent examples of how art could serve
patriotism,'' says Ilene Susan Fort, associate curator of American
art at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art which organized the
exhibition.
   Hassam's flags frequently are framed by Manhattan churches and
skyscrapers as symbols of the moral force of the Allied cause and
America's emergence as a world power, she said.
   The National Gallery exhibition includes 23 of the flag
paintings, which were sold individually after 1922 after failure of
a plan to purchase a group of them as a war memorial for New York
City.
   Ms. Fort said five of the flag paintings sold in the 1920s,
including three depicting women watching parades from flag-draped
windows, have since vanished and their whereabouts _ if they still
exist _ are unknown. She said she hoped that word of the exhibition
might encourage the owners to step forward.
   When the show closes at the National Gallery on July 18, it will
travel to the Los Angeles museum, Aug. 21 through Oct. 30, the Amon
Carter Museum at Fort Worth, Texas, Jan. 7 through March 12, and
the New York Historical Society, April 20 through June 25.
   The National Gallery show is the second in a three-part series
devoted to American impressionist artists and underwritten by Bell
Atlantic. The first was an exhibition of paintings by William
Merritt Chase last year. The series will end in the fall of 1989
with the works of John Twachtman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1439EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-Pool     05-07 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Pool,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Iranian Ships Cross Warily in Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The following dispatch is from Robert Kearns of
Reuters, the press representative in the Pentagon news pool in the
Persian Gulf.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS JACK WILLIAMS IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neither
side blinked when U.S. and Iranian ships glided silently past each
other Saturday in their closest encounter since a naval battle
three weeks ago.
   The 3,700-ton guided missile frigate Jack Williams spotted the
Booshehr, a 354-foot Iranian supply boat on early morning patrol,
after the Williams crossed the tense strait of Hormuz twice in less
than 24 hours.
   The two ships sailed within about 2,500 yards of each other on
opposite courses in the rolling blue seas about 20 miles east of
Abu Musa, a heavily fortified island where Iran maintains a gunboat
base and air field.
   The ships passed without any radio or other routine
acknowledgement in an area almost within range of Iran's land-based
Chinese-made Silkworm missiles. The U.S. Navy calls the area ``The
Silkworm Envelope,'' but the crew uses the nickname ``The
Wormhole.''
   ``They are probably on patrol, like us, tracking ship movement,
gathering information,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Mark Van Dyke.
   The Booshehr's presence attracted curious crewmembers and their
cameras.
   A mine-spotting crewman stood at the bow of the Iranian boat, a
sign of an apparent split between the regular Iranian navy and the
country's Revolutionary Guards, who seem to lay mines with autonomy.
   ``That's nice,'' a lookout on the Williams told reporters when
he saw his counterpart on the drab gray Iranian ship. ``Even they
don't know where the mines are.''
   American officers said the Booshehr is one of only a few
sightings of Iranian warships that have crept out of port since the
April 18 fighting.
   The Williams was at the center of those clashes, which took
place near where the ships passed Saturday. The U.S. Navy said
after the April 18 clashes that it sank an Iranian frigate,
disabled a second, and hit four other ships _ a major loss for
Iran's small navy.
   A calm has settled over the Persian Gulf since then, despite
Iranian threats of retaliation.
   ``It's nice to see their entire navy passing,'' joked a chief
petty officer on the bridge.
   However, Iran still has its fleet of gunboats and other vessels,
as well as the ability to lay mines, and the U.S. Navy has tried to
remain vigilant.
   Before meeting the Iranian boat, the Williams had completed
escorting two tankers through the strait and into the Gulf of Oman.
A British destroyer, HMS Gloucester, rode shotgun for four tankers
in the same convoy.
   ``It was as though Iran did not exist,'' Cmdr. Edward Mann,
captain of the Williams, said of the quiet trip.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0126 </DOCNO>
