<DOCNO> AP880507-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1456EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Caliguiri     05-07 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caliguiri,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fan Says Late Mayor Took Care of Pittsburgh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The late Richard S. Caliguiri was known as a
mayor who cared for people more than politics during his 11 years
in office, and fans said Saturday that's the way people will
remember the popular Democrat.
   ``He took care of Pittsburgh just like it was his family,'' said
bartender Donald Jones, 36. ``That's what they need in all
government, somebody like him.''
   ``You could be the lowest person, but he still spoke to you,
he'd see you and wave,'' Jones said as he wiped counters at The
Oyster House, a century-old downtown restaurant and tavern.
   Caliguiri died Friday at the age of 56 of heart failure
triggered by amyloidosis, a rare disorder in which protein deposits
build up in the heart and other major organs. The deposits
stiffened his heart muscle.
   Dave Welty, Caliguiri's press secretary, said the mayor made
friends everywhere.
   ``He's sort of been a mayor for the people and of the people,''
Welty said. ``He did not seclude himself. Dick genuinely liked
people.''
   ``He wasn't just out in a political year when he was out looking
for votes. Dick was out all the time, so the people knew him.''
   Theresa Fuchs, 63, of Pittsburgh, said she saw Caliguiri at many
parades and events.
   ``He was really a human being,'' she said. ``He never looked
down on anybody.''
   Caliguiri was credited with helping shift Pittsburgh away from
its dependence on the steel industry to make it a progressive city
of 365,000 people. The turnaround earned Pittsburgh national
recognition.
   Church bells rang simultaneously across the city Friday evening
and flags flew at half-staff on state property in Pennsylvania.
   The Pittsburgh Pirates announced players will have Caliguiri's
initials sewn on the right sleeve of their uniforms for the rest of
the season. The mayor led a drive in 1985 to keep the baseball team
in Pittsburgh.
   City employees draped black bunting and placed black wreaths
around entrances to the City County Building, which houses the
mayor's office.
   City Council President Sophie Masloff, 70, was sworn in as mayor
Friday morning. She ordered city offices closed Monday, when the
mayor's body will be moved to the City County Building. Schools,
museums and the city's zoo also will be closed.
   Mrs. Masloff is the city's first woman and first Jewish mayor.
Under the city charter, she will serve the remainder of Caliguiri's
term, which expires Dec. 31, 1989.
   As council president in 1977, Caliguiri was tapped to be interim
mayor when incumbent Pete Flaherty joined the Carter adminstration.
He ran for mayor in November 1977, as an independent, and beat a
popular Democrat.
   He was twice re-elected by landslide margins during a rocky
period in which the region lost more than 75,000 jobs, suffered the
departure of Gulf Corp. in 1984 and experienced unemployment rates
as high as 19 percent in 1982.
   A Mass of Christian burial will be celebrated Tuesday morning at
St. Paul's Cathedral.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
