<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacialDiscrimination     05-07 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Discrimination,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Race, Sex Discrimination Pervasive At Waste Control
Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racial and sexual harassment and
discrimination have been pervasive at the agency which handles most
of the waste treatment in the Minneapolis-St. Paul area, the state
Human Rights Department says.
   ``The extent of it was large,'' Human Rights Commissioner
Stephen Cooper said Friday when the report about the Metropolitan
Waste Control Commission was released.
   ``There was a very lax effort to do anything about known
problems,'' Cooper added.
   Women and minority workers faced hostile work environments and,
at times, have been subject to different discipline than white male
workers, the report said.
   The waste control commission, which has an annual budget of $108
million, operates waste treatment plants that process 80 percent of
the sewage in the metropolitan area. It has about 980 employees,
and recent figures showed there were more than 140 women and almost
100 minority group members.
   Commission officials said Friday they will work with the Human
Rights Department in making changes recommended in the report. They
are to meet with Cooper May 16 to discuss the recommendations.
   ``We can't control how people think, but we can say what is not
tolerated,'' said Peter Meintsma, commission chairman. ``The
Metropolitan Waste Control Commission does and will continue to
provide a fair and equitable work place.''
   Meintsma said anyone who discriminates or harasses faces
dismissal. He said he did not expect major turnovers while the
recommendations are carried out.
   Human Rights Department recommendations have the authority of
law. If the commission rejects them, the department can sue the
commission.
   Investigators found that racial discrimination sometimes
included remarks or acts condoned by supervisors. Until recently,
the report said, employees have been unclear about what sex
discrimination is.
   The report said the commission's disability-leave policy also is
discriminatory. In addition, the agency does not have an
affirmative action staff to investigate discrimination complaints,
the report said.
   The commission needs to set up training on racial and sexual
harassment, as well as disciplinary measures, the report said.
   Meintsma said the commission already has enacted some of the
recommendations. Sexual harassment training will be finished for
all employees by the end of June, and training on racial
discrimination will follow, he said.
   The commission also is forming a 15-member affirmative action
committee and a staff member is examining the affirmative action
office.
   However, a black former employee said he doubts the commission's
commitment to change.
   ``People cause this problem and problem people cannot be
expected to straighten this out,'' said Makolle Williams, a former
machinist at the commission who has filed suit against the
commission alleging racial discrimination and harassment.
</TEXT>
