<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PregnancyWarning     05-07 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pregnancy Warning,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grocers Use Bags Promoting Health Care For Pregnant Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Illinois shoppers are getting a
new message at the checkout counter: Pregnant women need medical
attention before their babies are born.
   The message, distributed in conjunction with Mother's Day, is
printed on shopping bags and is designed to reduce infant mortality.
   Illinois' infant death rate has been above the national average
for 22 consecutive years.
   Independent grocers throughout the state and some big chains
have agreed to use the bags, said U.S. Rep. Richard Durbin, D-Ill.
They began appearing Friday, and soon up to 600 grocers will be
helping to pass the message along, Durbin said.
   The message, under a headline ``A healthy mother means a healthy
baby,'' tells women that a ``baby's life depends on early health
care'' and provides a toll-free number at the Illinois Department
of Public Health.
   The state's public health chief, Dr. Bernard J. Turnock, said
his agency would provide information for pregnant woman who have no
insurance, cannot afford a doctor or have other questions or
problems.
   He said women calling the hotline can be referred to local
agencies and may be eligible for financial help.
   Durbin said he thought of the grocery bag idea after similar
campaigns were used to help search for missing children. He posed
the idea to lobbyists representing grocery stores, and they agreed.
   ``I have young kids myself. It's a good way of communicating,''
Mark Niederkorn, manager of Kennedy's Market in Decatur, said
Saturday.
   Turnock said infant mortality is one of the major problems
facing the state, particularly in central and southern Illinois.
   Illinois ranks among the top 10 states in infant death rates and
is the worst among northern industrial states.
   Last year, more than 2,000 Illinois babies died before reaching
their first birthday. The infant mortality rate equalled 11.5
deaths per 1,000 live births.
   Turnock said poverty in cities and the decreasing numbers of
hospitals and doctors who provide obstetric care in rural areas are
two of the biggest reasons for infant mortality.
   Durbin, a member of the House Select Committee on Children,
represents the 20th Congressional District, which stretches from
central Illinois west to the Mississippi River.
   His goal is to circulate 5 million of the bags each week, but
about 180,000 a week are being circulated for starters, he said.
</TEXT>
