<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev     05-07 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Asks Support From Journalists, Artists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev went before top
journalists and artists on Saturday and asked them to back his
program of reforms, Tass said.
   Also on Saturday, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda called on
representatives who will attend an important party conference next
month to blunt those conservatives who doubt Gorbachev's reforms.
   Tass said Gorbachev addressed a meeting in the Communist Party
Central Committee of editors of top state-run newspapers and
literary journals, and heads of artistic unions.
   He called on editors and artists to ``all the more energetically
help in the renewal of all sides of our life,'' said the brief Tass
report. It said a full report on the meeting would be published
later.
   Pravda's front-page article contained more criticism of a March
13 article in another organ of the official press that questioned
whether Gorbachev's reforms had gone too far. That article has
caused an ideological controversy in the Soviet press.
   Soviet officials rarely given any definitive word about
ideological disputes in the party hierarchy, but clues often appear
in newspaper articles.
   Unconfirmed reports in Moscow have said the article that started
the dispute _ a letter by Leningrad teacher Nina Andreyeva praising
dictator Josef V. Stalin's role in Soviet history _ had the backing
of Kremlin No. 2 man Yegor K. Ligachev, and led to a showdown
between him and Gorbachev.
   Ligachev, who is responsible for the party's ideology, has
struck a more conservative note than Gorbachev, especially on the
Soviet party chief's call for ``glasnost,'' or greater openness in
discussing social issues.
   Tass said Ligachev attended the meeting in the Central
Committee, as would be expected of the party's chief ideologist.
   At several such meetings in recent months, Gorbachev has sought
to define the limits of what is permissible in the Soviet press
under his more open policies.
   Delegates to the party conference scheduled for late June ``will
not only have to defend the revolutionary way of thinking and
acting, but should the need arise, give a courageous rebuff to
conservative aspirations,'' Pravda said.
   ``A lot will depend on their firm and principled stand. Most
important _ the destiny of perestroika will depend on it,'' Pravda
said. ``Perestroika'' is the term Gorbachev uses for his economic
and social reforms.
   The party conference gives Gorbachev a chance in between
congresses held every five years to change the makeup of the
policy-making Central Committee, thereby strengthening his support
in the top levels of the Communist Party.
   The conference could be a major test of Gorbachev's strength and
determine how forcefully he can pursue reform.
   Two days after Pravda printed its original response attacking
the Andreyeva letter on April 4, Sovietskaya Rossiya was forced to
recant by publishing the Pravda article in full without commentary.
Pravda said in April that Ms. Andreyeva's letter should not have
been printed.
   But the debate in the press has not died out. In the past week,
three papers have defend the right of Gorbachev's opponents to
speak out even if the party judges them to be wrong.
   Pravda said Saturday that Gorbachev's opponents had been
underestimated, but that they betrayed their true values through
Ms. Andreyeva's letter.
   The newspaper also tried to tie opponents of Gorbachev's reforms
to the ethnic disputes in the southern Soviet republics of
Azerbaijan and Armenia, where at least 32 people died in late
February and early March.
   It said that party members were among the officials who either
shirked their responsibilties or were afraid to act to stop rioting
in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait. Such people must be ready to
take initiative, and if they cannot, must step aside for leaders
who will, Pravda said.
</TEXT>
