<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CzechDissident     05-07 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czech Dissident,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Paper Rejects Charges of Brutality in Activist's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Communist Party newspaper on
Saturday dismissed claims from dissidents and U.S. officials that
authorities brutalized a human rights activist who died in prison.
   The daily Rude Pravo made its statement in its first report on
the April 26 death of Pavel Wonka, who was buried Friday.
   Wonka served 21 months on subversion charges before being
arrested again on April 5 and accused of violating ``protective
surveillance'' rules. On April 20, he was sentenced to five months
in jail, and he died six days later in prison at Hradec Kralove.
   Rude Pravo said an autopsy showed that Wonka, 35, died of
pulmonary embolism, a blockage of blood vessels.
   The newspaper added that despite the finding, the death was used
by ``Western anti-Communist centers'' as ``a pretext for an
attack'' on the communist state.
   Rude Pravo criticized what it said was an ``anti-Czechoslovak
statement'' by Rep. Steny H. Hoyer, D-Md., who is deputy chairman
of the U.S. delegation to the Helsinki human rights conference in
Vienna.
   Hoyer said Wonka had suffered unjust sentencing and brutal
treatment in prison, and U.S. Ambassador Warren Zimmermann made
similar charges.
   Rude Pravo on Saturday carried an interview with two U.S.
doctors who also examined Wonka's body. One of them, Robert
Lawrence of Harvard University, said he saw no evidence of
``significant torture.''
   Czechoslovak dissidents said earlier that Wonka was beaten in
prison. Petr Uhl, a member of the Charter 77 rights movement, said
Friday that Wonka was illegally convicted the second time because
he was ill and confined to a wheelchair.
   Wonka was buried in his hometown, Vrchlabi, in east Bohemia on
Friday. Dissident sources said police prevented at least two
people, prominent playwright Vaclav Havel and his wife, Olga, from
attending.
   The state news agency CTK, which carried excerpts of the Rude
Pravo article, on Saturday attacked Wonka's activities, charging
that he was ``very active against socialism in the last few
years.'' It said he wrote letters that ``offended Czechoslovak
public officials and the social system, made fabrications about
responsible officials and disseminated them without evidence, (and)
grossly attacked the Czechoslovak state and political bodies.''
   The report also said Wonka physically attacked a district court
judge in Jicin.
</TEXT>
