<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1551EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BuriedHancock     05-07 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Buried Hancock,0606</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Statehouse Construction Work Stumbles on Hancock Foundations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid piles of dirt dug up on the Statehouse lawn
during a renovation project, archaeologists say they may have found
traces of patriot John Hancock's home.
   The foundations of the granite mansion itself may be lost
forever beneath the remains of later buildings. But an
archaeological company hired by the state reports that a
5-foot-high granite garden wall remains intact.
   ``What we do have appears to be the back wall of the terrace
gardens growing up the hill,'' said Michael Roberts, a partner in
the Groton, Mass., firm Time Lines Inc.
   Roberts said he and fellow archaeologists plan to recommend
preserving the excavated site around the wall. The firm is due to
release a study of its findings later this month.
   Officials have halted work around the site while they study
whether a nearby foundation could also be from the Hancock mansion,
which was torn down in 1863. But Roberts said he thinks that the
foundation is part of a later building.
   ``Our analysis seems to indicate that the (Hancock) house
foundation itself was severly destroyed, disturbed and removed when
mansions in the 1860s were put in place on top of that property,''
he said.
   Hancock, the first signer of the Declaration of Independence in
1776, lived in the Beacon Hill mansion most of his life. One of
Boston's wealthiest men and later governor of Massachusetts,
Hancock received many a dignitary at the home, including President
George Washington.
   The mansion, which had been built in 1733 for Hancock's uncle,
was torn down 130 years later after the state failed to appropriate
money to buy and preserve it. The site now lies in front of a later
west wing of the Statehouse.
   The state is spending $32 million on a renovation project in and
around the Statehouse, due to be completed this summer. Excavation
related to improvements in drainage on the grounds led to the
discovery of the Hancock wall, the top of which lay 2 feet below
ground.
   When excavators discovered the wall and a nearby foundation,
city archaeologist Stephen Pendery called for a work stoppage,
arguing that the foundation was likely the Hancock house. Like
Roberts, state officials contended that the foundation was the
remains of later townhouses, but they finally agreed to stop work.
   For the short term, Roberts said, ``the wall will be preserved
in place the way it is. It will be covered over, kept intact and
well documented.''
   Exposing the wall will require an excavation of some seven feet,
he said.
   Judging from descriptions of those who saw them, the house and
garden must have been splendid. One 19th century account at the
State Library tells of ``a vast entrance hall (that) divided the
mansion in the center and extended through to the rear where it
gave upon a group of the loveliest gardens in Boston, laid out on
the hillside against which the house nestled.''
   The wealthy merchant Thomas Hancock, the house's original owner
and John's uncle, insisted on the finest fruit trees, flowers and
shrubbery for the garden.
   When British soldiers occupied Boston during the Revolutionary
War, the home and ancillary buildings were a garrison and hospital
for British soldiers. Surprisingly, despite the hatred of the
Redcoats for John Hancock, the house was spared the destruction
wrought on other Boston homes.
   A letter from a Hancock relative tells of a backgammon table
that was missing and how Hancock insisted that the British replace
it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Locusts     05-07 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Locusts,0372</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabian Peninsula On Guard Against Locusts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Swarms of locusts have been seen in
Saudi Arabia's agriculturally important northern regions but
officials said Saturday they were confident there would be no crop
damage.
   Farther south on the Arabian Peninsula, fears of a locust
invasion were dispelled after agriculture officials took a closer
look and found them to be grasshoppers.
   A. Mjeni, plant protection expert with the Omani government,
said there were no locust sightings in the sultanate so far and he
saw ``a minimal threat'' to the rest of the Arabian Peninsula.
   A path of locusts has been moving recently through parts of
North Africa, consuming large amounts of vegetation.
   Salem Bomofleh, director-general of the Agricultural Research
Center in the Saudi Red Sea port city of Jiddah, said some swarms
sighted in northern regions of the kingdom covered an area of 36
square miles.
   Two swarms were cited in Tabuk, where wheat is grown, but
Bamofleh said those swarms were ``completely controlled before
egg-laying'' by both ground teams and aerial spraying.
   Six swarms in the al-Jouf area, also a wheat-producing region,
have laid eggs that are expected to hatch in mid-May.
   ``Equipped and qualified teams are controlling the locusts
now,'' Bamofleh said by telephone. ``They are also surveying the
area to find out if more swarms have invaded.''
   But he said he did not expect the kingdom to experience any crop
damage from the invasion.
   The sightings have been confined to the country's northern
regions and there have been no reports of locusts in Riyadh, the
capital.
   In Oman, where locusts invaded a 14-mile stretch in the eastern
Sharqiya region two years ago and stripped the area of vegetation,
worried farmers raised the alarm when when they spotted a massive
swarm north of the capital Muscat last month.
   But when the investigating officials tracked it down to the
village of Bahla, the intruders were revealed to be grasshoppers.
   ``It was a case of mistaken identity,'' al-Mjeni said.
``Grasshoppers are attracted to light and, not surprisingly, they
congregated near the governor's office which is well illuminated at
night. People often mistake grasshoppers for locusts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0138 </DOCNO>
