<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     05-07 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extremists Kill Governing Party Official</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ultra-nationalist extremists opposed
to a peace accord assassinated an official of President Junius R.
Jayewardene's governing party, police said Saturday.
   R.B. Henry, a local secretary of the United National Party, was
shot by two guerrillas of the outlawed People's Liberation Front, a
Sinhalese extremist group, on Friday in the northwestern town of
Kurunegala, said police who cannot be identified under briefing
rules.
   The extremists issued no statement to announced their motive,
but they have vowed to kill all backers of a July 29 India-Sri
Lanka peace accord.
   The agreement aims at ending a 4-year-old guerrilla war with
Tamils who want a homeland on part of the island off India's
southern coast.
   The government says the front has killed more than 200 members
and supporters of the United National Party since the accord was
signed.
   The front says the peace accord makes too many concessions to
Tamils, who make up 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Sinhalese are 75 percent of the population.
   Tamil militants say their people suffers discrimination at the
hands of Sinhalese, who control the army and government.
   The main Tamil militant group, Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam,
has also rejected the peace accord.
   India has more than 50,000 soldiers in Sri Lanka to disarm the
Tigers and enforce the accord.
