<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1557EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AgingJets 1stLd-Writethru a0616 05-07 1025</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aging Jets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0616,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aging Jets An Old Problem</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf, According to, to CORRECT year to 1975, sted
1985</NOTE>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic NY21</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The in-flight breakup of a 19-year-old Aloha
Airlines Boeing 737 has heightened concern about the safety of
older jetliners, but the problem has been known for years.
   Nearly a decade ago, the industry and its regulators agreed to
develop new safeguards against potentially catastrophic cracks and
corrosion, with a large portion of the nation's commercial fleet
already approaching old age. A program begun in 1983 covers nearly
1,000 planes now flying.
   But some aviation safety experts remained worried that while the
monitoring program looked good on paper, it might not always be
carried through and that federal regulators weren't able to
backstop all cases.
   According to the National Transportation Safety Board, the
agency has investigated more than 80 incidents and accidents
involving aircraft fatigue, cracks or corrosion since 1975, though
many were isolated to landing gear or engine problems. At least 15
cases involved cracks or corrosion on an aircraft's outer skin or
on control devices.
   On April 28, a 20-foot section of the upper cabin of an Aloha
Boeing 737 ripped away at 24,000 feet, exposing passengers to the
open air and sweeping a flight attendant to her death before the
pilot managed an emergency landing.
   Since then, the Federal Aviation Administration has ordered
renewed inspections of older Boeing 737s, including mandatory
high-frequency electronic testing of those that have more than
50,000 landings. But safety experts note that special visual
inspections of those planes, including the Aloha craft, already
were required at the time of the accident.
   The cause of the Aloha accident is yet to be determined
precisely. But the episode demonstrates a ``need to re-evaluate the
issues surrounding the aging fleet question, especially as it
relates to fatigue and corrosion cracking,'' suggests Joseph Nall,
the NTSB member who headed the initial investigation at Aloha last
week.
   Investigators are certain the accident stemmed from a structural
failure. The unanswered question is why did such a structural
problem on the 19-year-old airplane, which had nearly 90,000
landings, go undetected?
   Where did the system of warnings, inspections and preventative
maintenance go awry?
   ``It's one thing to issue a piece of paper. It's something else
to know with confidence that this stuff is being done the way you
know it can be done,'' says C.O. Miller, a veteran aviation safety
consultant and former government investigator. ``It isn't just a
simple issue of putting out an (FAA directive) or a service
bulletin.''
   Aloha officials have maintained all along that they complied
with all FAA directives in connection with the plane.
   According to the FAA, there are about 1,000 commercial jets _
Boeing 727s, 737s, 747s, McDonnell Douglas DC-9s and DC-8s _ that
are subject to the program designed in 1983 to monitor older
aircraft more closely for structural defects.
   ``The only reason there is the focus on the 737 is because it
had the accident,'' declares Ben Cosgrove, vice president for
engineering at the Boeing Airplane Co.
   The program was established after the airlines made it clear
they plan to keep their jets longer because declining fuel costs
lessened the attraction for investing in new, more fuel-efficient
planes. Whatever new jets are bought are usually flown to expand
service, rather than as replacements.
   As a result, since 1979 the average age of the aircraft fleet
belonging to the major airlines has increased from 10.28 years to
12.53 years, according to Avmark Inc., an Arlington, Va., aircraft
consulting and appraisal firm.
   ``There are probably about 2,300 airplanes now in service that
are fundamentally over 20 years old _ built before 1968,'' says
Boeing's Cosgrove. While these planes are capable of flying years
longer, after the 20-year mark ``you should start expecting to see
some more damage occur ... through fatigue and corrosion,'' he
acknowledges.
   But both Boeing and competitor McDonnell Douglas maintain that
with close inspections and prompt maintenance these jetliners
should have no problem flying well beyond their ``design life.''
   McDonnell Douglas, a few years ago, tested an old DC-9 to an
equivalent of 208,000 landing cycles to see how it would hold up.
As a result of the test ``we're very confident we have a DC-9 life
of at least 104,000 (landing) cycles,'' says J.J. McGrew, the
manufacturer's director of aircraft design.
   Different parts of the plane are affected differently, but the
strength of its fuselage and outer skin is most affected by the
number of takeoff and landings. Each time a plane is pressurized,
the cabin wall expands slightly and then when depressurized, it
retracts. That cycle can take its toll and can lead to a
potentially dangerous failure if critical parts, such as metal
joints, are weakened by corrosion, according to technical experts.
   The Aloha aircraft had nearly 90,000 such cycles in only 33,000
hours of flying, since most flights shuttled among the Hawaiian
islands.
   Ironically, it is such short-haul flights that often are served
by the older jets. Perhaps the most heavily traveled short-haul
system is Eastern Airlines' Washington-New York-Boston shuttle,
where 17 older Boeing 727s are in use.
   Each of the Eastern planes falls under the special FAA
inspection and maintenance program begun for older jets five years
ago, according to Roger Ferguson, Eastern's vice president for
maintenance and engineering, although none approach the number of
landings experienced by the Aloha aircraft.
   While maintenance costs for the older planes are higher _ as
much as 1{ times more for a 20 year-old plane as a 5-year-old craft
_ the older Boeing jets continue to perform economically, Ferguson
said. The planes, including the top of the fuselage, are visually
inspected for cracks every 1,100 landings, said Ferguson.
   John O'Brien, safety and engineering specialist at the Air Line
Pilots Association, says there is an inadequate number of FAA
inspectors, and complains that airlines occasionally ignore
maintenance bulletins from the manufacturers because they are not
mandatory. He says the FAA often is under pressure from the
industry not to issue mandatory directives except as ``a last
resort.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1559EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-IllinoisDelegates     05-07 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Illinois Delegates,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon, Jackson Camps in Accord on Party Delegate Slate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois Democrats divided the last of
their delegates between favorite sons Paul Simon and Jesse Jackson
on Saturday, although a party leader said Simon's delegates might
vote for someone else at the Democratic National Convention.
   Supporters of Jackson, who initially complained about Simon
receiving the delegates, said they were satisfied with the deal
struck Saturday and expected to pick up some those who defect from
the Illinois senator.
   ``If Paul is not there as a choice, I would suspect that many of
the people on the unity slate would vote for Reverand Jackson,''
said Leon Finney Jr., Jackson's Illinois campaign director.
   Simon received 47 delegates and Jackson 13, based on the results
of the state's March 15 primary. The individuals to serve in those
statewide slots were picked Saturday by the state party central
committee.
   Overall, Simon has 148 delegates from Illinois and Jackson has
41, most of whom were elected directly from the primary ballot by
congressional district.
   Simon was eligible for at-large delegates because he suspended
his campaign but did not formally drop out of the race. That tactic
angered supporters of Jackson, who ran second in Illinois and would
have collected all of the state's at-large delegates had Simon
dropped out.
   Some Jackson allies accused Simon of playing an unwitting role
in a stop-Jackson movement, and hinted that Simon might face a
black voter backlash should he seek re-election to the U.S. Senate
in 1990.
   State Democratic Chairman Vince Demuzio said he approached both
camps about a negotiated solution to the delegate disputes in hopes
of avoiding a split in the state party.
   ``It became clear that they were interested as we were in doing
this in a unified manner, and in a manner that was peaceful and
harmonious,'' he said.
   Demuzio said he could not dispute suggestions that Democratic
heavyweights pledged to Simon might feel free to cut their own
deals at the party convention in Atlanta.
   ``They have a moral obligation to vote for the candidate to
which they were pledged, but I think for the most part they will
likely be free agents,'' Demuzio said.
   Simon's operatives also acknowledged that some of their choices
for at-large delegates were dumped from the slate during
negotiations with the Jackson campaign.
   ``We both left a lot of blood on the streets as well as some
good and deserving people,'' said Jerry Sinclair, Simon's Illinois
campaign director.
</TEXT>
