<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlantFire     05-07 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plant Fire,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Mill Blaze Prompts Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROARING SPRING, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents returned to their homes
Saturday after a fiery explosion at a paper mill released toxic
chemical fumes, prompting the evacuation of about 2,600 people,
authorities said.
   Two people who complained of difficulty breathing were
hospitalized.
   The incident began when a seven-story boiler exploded shortly
after 9 p.m. Friday at the Appleton Papers Inc. plant, authorities
said. The fire was brought under control by midnight.
   The cause of the explosion was not immediately determined,
officials said.
   ``My windows shook like a stick of dynamite went off when the
thing blew up,'' said Mary Ann Bathurst, who lives near the plant.
   After the fire was contained, the mill resumed operating around
3 a.m. on two alternate boilers, said mill Manager Jerry E. Wallace.
   The explosion occurred in a supply line containing the chemical
diphenyl oxide, a heat transfer fluid used in the drying process of
paper production, Wallace said. The chemical is highly toxic and
flammable.
   The evacuation order was issued around 10:30 p.m. as a
precautionary measure and lifted around 1 a.m.
   Two plant workers and five residents were treated at Nason
Hospital in Roaring Springs for eye irritations, nausea and
respiratory discomfort, said hospital spokeswoman Barbara Leamer.
   One of the seven was admitted and listed in fair condition
Saturday and a second was transferred to Altoona General Hospital
in good condition, Ms. Leamer said. She declined to release their
names.
</TEXT>
