<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Pollution     05-07 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Pollution,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Measures, Breezes Help Reduce Smog</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Saturday banned half of
the city's taxis and cars from the Athens area in an emergency move
to improve air quality.
   Athens has been covered by a thick brown haze for three days.
   Aided by strong northerly breezes, the measures seemed to be
working.
   ``There has been a significant reduction in atmospheric
pollution because of the measures and improved weather
conditions,'' said Constantine Bourkas, director of the state-run
Program for Pollution Control.
   Bourkas said the wind, coming after two days of calm weather,
blew some of the pollution out of the mountain-ringed Athens basin.
   A brown smog hangs over Athens most of the year. It is formed
when a strip of cold air moves on top of a strip of warm air and
traps it over the city.
   The measures banned half of the city's 730,000 automobiles and
15,000 taxis from a 115-square-mile zone around the city center.
Only vehicles with license plates ending in odd numbers were
allowed in the area.
   They also ordered the city's 120 largest industries to reduce
output by 30 percent.
   The traffic measures lasted only until Saturday afternoon, while
the industrial restriction was ordered to last until 6 a.m. Sunday.
   The city's automobiles, diesel-powered taxis and aging buses are
mainly responsible for the pollution.
</TEXT>
