<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NorthwestCrash     05-07 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northwest Crash,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing For Probable Cause Scheduled For Tuesday In Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Transportation Safety Board is
preparing to issue its findings this week on the probable cause of
the crash last August of Northwest Flight 255, the second-deadliest
air disaster in U.S. history.
   The airplane, an MD-80, or stretch version of the DC-9, crashed
Aug. 16 just outside Detroit Metropolitan Airport while trying to
take off on a flight to Phoenix, Ariz.
   Just one person aboard the plane, a 4-year-old girl, survived
the crash. Her mother, father, brother and 153 other people were
killed.
   The girl, Cecelia Cichan, attracted gifts and letters from
around the nation while she was hospitalized.
   She is living with an aunt and uncle in Birmingham, Ala., and
relatives have pledged to make every effort to let the girl, now 5,
live as normal a life as possible.
   The NTSB scheduled a hearing Tuesday in Washington to issue its
finding of the probable cause of the crash, second only to the May
25, 1979, crash of a DC-10 at Chicago's O'Hare Airport that killed
275 people.
   The Northwest Airlines plane never got more than 50 feet off the
ground before it clipped a light pole in a parking lot, sliced a
chunk from the roof of a building and crashed onto a four-lane
highway.
   The plane broke apart while it skidded down the road, slamming
into a railroad trestle and two overpasses carrying traffic on
Interstate 94.
   The NTSB final report is expected to focus on the setting of the
airplane's flaps and slats, panels on the leading and trailing
edges of the wings that are extended to give aircraft extra lift
during takeoffs.
   Federal investigators have said the flaps on the doomed airplane
were not extended as they should have been for takeoff from the
airport's shortest runway.
   At an NTSB public hearing last November, several theories
emerged about why the flaps weren't set or why the crew wasn't
warned:
   _The pilot and copilot forgot. An NTSB transcript of a cockpit
voice recording during the half-hour before the crash has no
reference to a checklist procedure to check the setting of the
flaps and slats. But Northwest had an independent analysis done on
a copy of the tape and concluded that it contained ``flaps'' and
``flaps set'' command and response.
   _An alarm system designed to signal when flaps were set
improperly failed. There was testimony questioning the reliability
of a key circuit breaker within the system.
   _A crew member disabled the alarm system when the airplane
landed at Metro Airport after a flight from Saginaw. The cockpit
voice recorder's tape is a 30-minute loop which did not go back far
enough to catch the sound of the circuit breaker being pulled.
   More than a dozen court actions have been filed by survivors of
crash victims, and all have been moved to federal court in Detroit.
   The FBI and the Wayne County Sheriff's Department are still
looking for the mysterious Father John Irish, a man who posed as a
Roman Catholic priest and comforted the victims' families while
referring them to a Florida lawyer.
   A federal warrant has been issued for the man, who was charged
last October with fraud in Wayne County for accumulating about
$1,000 worth of hotel, food and telephone expenses paid for by
Northwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
