<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Says Soviets to Leave in Midst of Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party newspaper Pravda said Saturday
that Soviet troops will be withdrawn from Afghanistan under battle
conditions and indicated more may be killed.
   The Soviet news media has provided little coverage of the Soviet
military involvement in Afghanisan, but the Pravda article reported
comments of Red Army soldiers about the withdrawal and their slain
comrades. It apparently was designed to prepare Soviet citizens for
more deaths as the soldiers pull out.
   Under an April 14 agreement between Pakistan and Afghanistan,
the Soviet Union will begin on May 15 to withdraw its estimated
115,000 military personnel in Afghanistan. They entered Afghanistan
in December 1979 to help the Marxist government fight
anti-communist guerrillas.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has called the war a
``bleeding wound'' for the Soviet Union, but Soviet casualties have
never been revealed.
   The Pravda article, headlined ``The Last Summer,'' said Soviet
troops were preparing to come home. It was accompanied by a picture
of three smiling soldiers.
   However, the daily newspaper said: ``The withdrawal of Soviet
units for home is a complicated operation. It will be carried out
in war conditions.''
   Pravda said rebels were continuing to fight Soviet and Afghan
government soldiers ``trying to spoil the process of
reconciliation'' and working to ``pile up weapons inside
Afghanistan, to create there stockpiles and bases.''
   It said the rebels were attacking cities, intimidating citizens
and committing sabotage.
   Pravda quoted one soldier, V. Malashkin, as telling about the
death of a friend who was captain of a helicopter shot down by
rebels on April 18. It said the pilot, Capt. Sergei Gusev, had left
a wife, son and daughter in Minsk. He had served in Afghanistan
eight months and had been decorated twice, according to the report.
   The Soviets have pledged to withdraw all their soldiers from
Afghanistan in nine months.
</TEXT>
