<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-DerbyParties     05-07 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Derby Parties,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`J.R.,' Zsa Zsa, Other Celebrities Flock to Derby Parties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Since the writers' strike in Hollywood has
held up filming fall episodes of ``Dallas,'' Larry Hagman used the
time off to rub elbows with the horsy set on Kentucky Derby weekend.
   Hagman, who plays the villainous J.R. Ewing on the prime-time
series, wore black beaded Reeboks and a watch engraved ``J.R.'' to
the annual party thrown by Preston and Anita Madden on the grounds
of their Hamburg Place.
   Hagman said the strike enabled him to attend the Derby party
Friday as well as the race itself on Saturday. Production of
``Dallas'' was to have resumed April 15, but has been delayed by
the 2-month-old scriptwriters' strike.
   Also among the 1,500 guests crowding in the large tent were Zsa
Zsa Gabor (``I love the horses the best, below my husband,
dahling'') and Annie Potts of ``Designing Women.''
   Potts, a Kentucky native who served as grand marshal of
Thursday's Pegasus Parade in Louisville, was impressed with the
festivities. ``This feels like a premiere tent, but there's no
kiss-kiss, hoochie-coochie. No one's trying to do business here _
at least not with me.''
   The crowd at the lawn party in Lexington, however, paled next to
the record numbers that showed up at the governor's mansion in
Frankfort. Gov. Wallace Wilkinson mailed out 25,000 invitations for
the traditional Governor's Derby Breakfast Saturday morning.
   Wilkinson and first lady Martha Wilkinson arrived by golf cart
at a giant white tent where state Department of Parks employees
served mountains of eggs, grits and country ham.
   At one point during the short trip from the Executive Mansion,
Wilkinson leapt off the car and grabbed a surprised guest for an
impromptu jitterbug.
   Because Wilkinson was using the breakfast to woo businesses to
the region, the guest list was heavy with the names of business
leaders. Wilkinson also entertained two fellow Democratic governors
_ Ned McWherter of Tennessee and Ray Mabus of Mississippi.
   Although no precise crowd figures were available, longtime
observers said the attendance was clearly the largest in the
breakfast's 52-year history.
