<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Kennedy Release,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youngest Child Of Sen. Edward Kennedy Leaves Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wearing a neck brace and leaning on a cane, the
younger son of Sen. Edward Kennedy left the hospital Saturday in
good spirits two weeks after surgery to remove a non-cancerous
tumor pressing against his spine.
   Patrick Kennedy, 20, praised the Massachusetts General Hospital
staff and said he will join his father's re-election effort after
some recuperation.
   ``It's been a long ordeal, but I'm thankful to the doctors and
nurses ...,'' said young Kennedy, who underwent neurosurgery on
April 21. ``It's meant a great deal to my family for so many
thoughtful words and prayers while I've been here. It's meant a
great deal to me. I'm looking forward to getting back.''
   Kennedy, a sophomore at Providence College in Rhode Island, was
admitted to the hospital April 18 after complaining of headaches
and pains in his back and legs for several months, said hospital
spokesman Martin Bander.
   Bander said the operation was completely successful and Kennedy
will return to the hospital in several weeks for a routine
examination.
   The senator, who accompanied his son from the hospital,
expressed relief. ``He's been through a great deal on it, but he's
back on his feet,'' said Kennedy.
   Patrick's older brother, Edward Kennedy Jr., 26, lost a leg to
bone cancer in 1973.
