<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 1713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DolphinDeaths-Study     05-07 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dolphin Deaths-Study,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Financially Strapped Dolphin-Death Study Gets Cash Boost</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERNANDINA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A money-starved project to study
dolphin deaths along the East Coast is receiving a cash infusion
from the Navy and the National Marine Fisheries Service.
   The Office of Naval Research has handed over $50,000 for the
dolphin study, and Tom McIntyre of the fisheries service said his
agency soon will chip in another $50,000.
   ``The animals are still dying. The Navy felt it was appropriate
that the investigation continue. They did a review of his proposal
and it was accepted. We are in the process of moving our money,''
McIntyre said Friday.
   The beneficiary is a task force headed by Canadian researcher
Dr. Joseph Geraci, who has anxiously awaited more money since the
study's funding ran out earlier this year.
   Geraci, professor of veterinary medicine in the pathology
department at the University of Guelph near Toronto, is a member of
the U.S. Marine Mammal Commission. The U.S. goverment asked him to
head the research begun last July when hundreds of dead dolphins
began washing ashore in New Jersey and Virginia. The deaths spread
down the coast, reaching Florida in November.
   Fisheries service statistics put the official East Coast dolphin
death toll at 742, but the actual number is probably much higher
because mammals that didn't wash ashore couldn't be counted.
   The cause of the deaths is unknown, although scientists believe
something is sapping the dolphins' immune systems, leaving them to
languish and die from common infections.
   The fisheries service fears that as much as 40 percent of the
East Coast's dolphin population has been wiped out.
   ``It could take decades to recover,'' said Lesley Scheele, a
dolphin project coordinator for the environmental group Greenpeace.
</TEXT>
