<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SuspiciousFires     05-07 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Suspicious Fires,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson Suspected in Two New Orleans Fires</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NU1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two five-alarm fires broke out within a few
minutes of one another and about one block apart Saturday,
destroying five buildings and injuring three firefighters,
officials said.
   Fire Chief William J. McCrossen said arson is suspected because
of the timing. He said most, and possibly all, of the buildings
were vacant and that firefighters' injuries were minor.
   The first fire broke out in the back of a vacant two-story
wood-frame building, which collapsed during the blaze, and spread
to a two-story brick house and a vacant one-story house, McCrossen
said.
   Firefighters rushing to the blaze saw the other fire a block
away. It started in a two-story apartment building and spread to
the building next door.
   In Reserve, about 20 miles upriver from New Orleans, about 40
people were evacuated briefly Friday after a pilot light from a
clothes dryer apparently touched off fumes from gasoline being
pumped into an underground tank.
   Nobody was hurt in the blaze, which did about $60,000 worth of
damage in 30 minutes, sweeping through a maintenance garage and
trailer house, and exploding at least three tanks of acetylene and
oxygen used for welding, St. John the Baptist Parish Sheriff's
spokesman Edward ``Tootie'' Nowell said.
   Thick black smoke poured from burning tires, fuel and other oily
equipment for more than an hour after the main fire was
extinguished. An emergency truck from the Marathon Petroleum
refinery in Garyville put those fires out with foam.
   Reserve is about 10 miles upriver from Norco, where an explosion
and fire at the Norco refinery last week killed six people, injured
42 and left one missing.
</TEXT>
