<2ND_LINE>AM-Punk Melee,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Punks Hurl Bottles in Melee at Burned-Out Ballroom Dance Club</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Punk rockers hurled bottles and jumped
on cars in a melee that began when 200 youths were ordered out of a
dance club that had been burned earlier in the week, police said
Saturday.
   Eight adults and seven juveniles were arrested in the hourlong
disturbance late Friday at Fenders Ballroom, said Lt. Jim Reed. One
police officer reported a minor injury.
   Police were called at 9:26 p.m. with reports that people were on
the roof of the ballroom and that a crowd had spilled into the
streets. The crowd ignored an order to disperse and police declared
it an unlawful assembly, Reed said.
   Bottles were thrown and groups spread into neighboring streets,
knocking over newspaper racks and jumping atop cars. There was no
estimate of damage.
   About 30 police units were dispatched to quell the disturbance.
   Fenders Ballroom, which had been used as a punk rock dance club
on Friday and Saturday nights, was heavily damaged Monday in a
suspicious fire that also scorched an adjacent residential hotel.
Damage was estimated at $225,000.
   Fenders was formerly known as the International Grand Ballroom
and catered to a different clientele.
