<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Violence     05-07 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill Seven In Attack On Police Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas attacked a police post near
Lake Titicaca with guns and home-made bombs, killing six officers
and a provincial judge, the Interior Ministry said Saturday.
   Elsewhere in the highlands, guerrillas of the Maoist Shining
Path movement also killed a government development official by
shooting him and then detonating a bomb in his car, Ayacucho police
reported.
   The police post attack occurred Thursday night in the Puno state
town of Crucero, located just north of Lake Titicaca near the
Bolivian border and 510 miles southeast of Lima, the ministry said
in a communique.
   Police battled the attackers for an hour before the rebels
destroyed the post by throwing the bombs, said the communique that
was published in the official gazette El Peruano.
   The report said a judge who was visiting the post also was
killed and the attackers fled on foot.
   It did not say how many policemen were at the post or if there
were any guerrilla casualties.
   The assassination in Ayacucho state occurred Friday about 50
miles south of the state capital of Ayacucho, which is 235 miles
southeast of Lima.
   Police said the slain man was a member of the governing Aprista
Party and a regional director of the Ayacucho State Development
Corporation.
   Shining Path rebels have been battling the government for eight
years.
