<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Newspage-Derby     05-07 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage-Derby,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Winning Colors Becomes Third Filly to Win Kentucky Derby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winning Colors led every inch of the way
Saturday to capture the 114th Kentucky Derby by a neck, becoming
only the third filly to win the famed race.
   The barrel-chested roan withstood a desperate stretch run by
Forty Niner after the last turn. Risen Star finished third in the
17-horse field of 3-year-olds.
   Winning Colors' victory was a personal triumph for trainer D.
Wayne Lukas, who had entered 12 previous horses in the 1\-mile race
but had never won it. Jockey Gary Stevens also won his first Derby
in four tries.
   Noting that the filly's victory came the day before Mother's
Day, the 52-year-old Lukas said: ``I would like to salute all of
the women of America _ this one is for you gals.''
   Winning Colors had gone off as the 3-1 favorite along with the
unbeaten Private Terms, who finished eighth. She joins 1915 winner
Regret and 1980's Genuine Risk as the only fillies to win the
Derby. She carried 121 pounds, while her male rivals carried 126.
Her winning time was 2 minutes, 2 1@5 seconds.
   Owned by Eugene V. Klein, the former owner of football's San
Diego Chargers, Winning Colors paid $8.80, $5.20 and $4.60 in
earning $611,200 to boost her bankroll past the $1 million mark on
a career record of six wins and one second in seven starts.
</TEXT>
