<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Spain-Cocaine     05-07 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Spain-Cocaine,0129</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spanish Police Seize 2,200 Pounds Of Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SEBASTIAN, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Saturday made Europe's
biggest drug haul, seizing 2,200 pounds of cocaine in the basement
of a building near the French border, according to San Sebastian
Gov. Jose Ramon Goni.
   He reported arrests were made but did not say how many.
   Goni said the cocaine, found in the border town of Irun on the
Atlantic coast, was ``of a great purity.''
   Spain also had reported the previous European record for a
single seizure of cocaine. Police on April 23 reported finding
1,200 pounds of cocaine aboard a ship off of Spain's northeastern
Mediterranean coast, 28 miles south of Barcelona. A man and a woman
were arrested in connection with that raid.
</TEXT>
