<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope-Poland     05-07 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Poland,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Says Democracy Only Solution To Crisis In His Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Pope, Bjt
^By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Saturday
expressed approval of strikes by Polish workers and declared that
only fundamental political changes leading to democracy can resolve
the crisis in his homeland.
   Speaking with reporters aboard the special Boeing 747 Alitalia
plane at the start of a 12-day tour of four South American
countries, John Paul called a lack of democracy ``the central
problem of Poland.''
   The pope expressed moral support for the strikes that began in
communist Poland last month and said neither ``superficial''
reforms nor resorting to force by the government were the answer to
Poland's problems.
   The statements were his strongest since the labor unrest began.
   ``Certainly strikes are a justified method to defend justice in
the socio-economic and socio-political fields,'' and this is part
of the church's social doctrine, the pope said.
   He stressed the need for a dialogue and said ``here we are
touching the heart of the problem _ the problem of the lack of true
democracy. That I think is the crucial problem, the central problem
of Poland.''
   The Roman Catholic Church, which traditionally has played a
major role in predominantly Catholic Poland, supported Solidarity,
the first free labor union in the Soviet bloc when it was created
in 1980. Solidarity was suspended by the government in December
1981 and subsequently outlawed.
   John Paul said he had no reason to doubt Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's declared intentions for reforms but said ``it is not
easy to democratize a system that is by definition dictatorial and
totalitarian.''
   John Paul also took issue with moves in the U.S. Congress that
would single out Bolivia, Peru and Paraguay _ three of the four
countries on his itinerary _ for economic aid sanctions on grounds
they are failing to cooperate with the United States in the war on
drugs.
   ``Well, are there only these countries?'' he asked, raising his
voice. ``Are only these countries responsible and guilty. ... or
are there others that collaborate, that profit from this and are
not punished? If not whole countries, then groups.''
   The three countries need help, ``not a punishment or a
sanction,'' he added.
   A Vatican official traveling with the pope who briefed reporters
on grounds of anonymity said John Paul was referring to the
responsibility of drug consumers in the United States and other
countries as well as international traffickers.
   Drug trafficking and its international implications is expected
to be one of the pope's major themes as he travels to
cocaine-producing centers in Bolivia after ending his 46-hour visit
to Uruguay on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
