<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Askew 2ndLd-Writethru a0669 05-07 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Askew, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0669,0712</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Askew Surprises Democrats By Dropping From Senate Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 12th graf ``The demands'' to add that Askews have two
children. Picks up 13th graf pvs ``Askew, 59...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Popular former Gov. Reubin Askew gave up
his bid for a U.S. Senate seat on Saturday even though he was
leading the race, saying ``it's just not right'' that candidates
must spend 75 percent of their time raising money.
   Askew said he also was motivated by a desire to spend more time
with his family. He said he would support a fellow Democrat, U.S.
Rep. Buddy MacKay of Ocala, for the Senate.
   ``I found myself increasingly concerned about the extraordinary
cost of running a statewide campaign in Florida today,'' Askew said
in a statement released by his campaign headquarters.
   ``Of course, I knew that before I announced my candidacy in
December. But, frankly, I underestimated the time and effort it
would take _ and how it would limit my ability to have more direct
contact with the voters.''
   The announcement stunned Democrats, who were losing a second
well-known candidate for the seat. Incumbent Sen. Lawton Chiles
announced in December that he would not seek election this fall to
a fourth term.
   ``That is a very devastating thing to have happen, a
front-runner withdraw from the race,'' said State Democratic Party
Chairman Charles Whitehead early Saturday, after published reports
in the Tallahasee Democrat and The Orlando Sentinel broke the story.
   Askew's war chest had reached $1 million, but a 1986 Senate race
in which former Gov. Bob Graham ousted Republican Paula Hawkins
cost both sides a total of $15 million.
   ``As I've said during this campaign, something is seriously
wrong with our system when many candidates for the Senate need to
spend 75 percent of their time raising money,'' Askew said. ``It's
just not right.''
   ``I hope the Senate will start bringing some reason to the
question of raising this much money,'' Askew said later at a news
conference at his Orlando law office.
   He said he originally believed he could get by with a $3.2
million budget, then he thought of limiting contributions but
realized he would still need $4.3 million, ``then it got to be $5.7
million.''
   Askew said the amount of time he would have to spend away from
his family was also ``at the forefront'' of his decision to qut the
race.
   ``The demands of the campaign reminded me forcefully of the
demands on my family,'' said Askew, with his wife, Donna, at his
side. They have two adult children.
   Askew, 59, was governor from 1971 to 1979, then served in the
Carter administration as a trade ambassador. He made a brief run
for the presidency in 1984, dropping out after finishing last in
the New Hampshire Democratic primary.
   He had held a commanding lead in published polls for the
Democratic nomination over his only official Democratic challenger,
U.S. Rep. Dan Mica. The primary is set for September. Polls also
showed Askew with a lead over the likely Republican challenger,
U.S. Rep. Connie Mack.
   ``I came to realize that I'm not prepared to reassume all the
demands of elective office,'' Askew's statement said.
   ``In recent weeks I have found myself treasuring a once-a-week
lunch break with (wife) Donna Lou at an Orlando lakeside restaurant
_ the only respite from the consuming demands of the campaign. And
we both know that those demands don't end on election day,'' Askew
said.
   Askew said he had informed MacKay of his decision early
Saturday. MacKay immediately said he would enter the Senate race,
and Askew said he would support and campaign for him.
   ``Buddy MacKay is running for the U.S. Senate. We will have an
offical announcement Monday,'' said Greg Farmer, MacKay's press
secretary.
   MacKay, 55, ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate in 1980,
losing the primary to another Democrat who then lost the general
election to Hawkins.
   Farmer said Askew's decision was a stunning surprise, especially
following Chiles' withdrawal.
   ``Welcome to the Twilight Zone of politics. If you don't like
Florida's politics, wait five minutes and they'll change,'' said
Farmer.
</TEXT>
