<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope 4thLd-Writethru a0673 05-07 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0673,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Begins Latin Trip in Secularized Uruguay</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 13th: Uruguay legalized divorce... with
pope retiring for the night. Pick up 14th graf: Reports from the
Vatican...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Saturday began a
12-day, four-country mission to South America and told nominally
Roman Catholic Uruguayans to ``pay attention to the Christian
message.''
   ``Set your eyes on Jesus. This country was born Christian,'' the
pope said in this country where church and state are rigorously
divided, even to the point of calling Christmas ``Families Day.''
   Smiling and appearing relaxed after a 13{-hour flight from Rome,
John Paul, his white robes blown by a chilly fall wind, shook hands
with President Julio Maria Sanguinetti, a self-professed agnostic.
   The president, wearing a dark business suit, did not bow or kiss
the pope's ring as Latin American leaders often do. He welcomed the
pontiff in ``a spirit of tolerance, beyond religious beliefs,'' and
emphasized Uruguay's defense of civilian and religious freedom ``in
all its imaginable extensions.''
   Uruguay's 3 million people _ of whom 80 percent say they are
Catholic _ seemed lukewarm at best about the papal visit. The white
and yellow Vatican flags and the huge papal billboards that usually
herald the pontiff's arrival in Latin America were not in evidence.
   The pope did make page 1 of the Saturday edition of the
Montevideo newspaper, La Manana, but the main headline read,
``Measures Approved For Meat Sector,'' a reference to Uruguay's
important beef trade.
   When John Paul visited Uruguay for the first time last year,
there was public enthusiasm. But this time, as taxi driver Arturo
Branco put it, ``Perhaps the novelty is gone.''
   The pontiff received cheers and applause, however, from an
estimated 82,000 young people when he arrived at the Centenary
Soccer Stadium to address the nation's youth.
   The people cheered and shouted ``Viva'' _ long life _ as John
Paul told them to ``meditate on the message of Jesus'' and ``build
a more just and fraternal society.''
   They also applauded when the pope, standing on an outdoor stage,
urged them to be aware of abortion and divorce.
   ``Don't fear children who may come. Don't let civilian authority
put obstacles in the path of fecundity,'' the pontiff said.
Abortion was legal in Uruguay from 1934 to 1938 but now is illegal.
   ``Marital fidelity has not gome out of style,'' the pope said.
   Uruguay legalized divorce in 1907, becoming one of the first
Catholic countries to do so.
   Later Saturday the pope addressed about 500 religious leaders
and students at the Catholic University and told them to ``continue
working together to form a friendlier and more humane world, a
culture more truthful and more beautiful.''
   He then retired to the papal envoy's residence for the night.
   Reports from the Vatican said the pope would try to persuade
Uruguayans to think twice about their independent securalism, on
grounds that this is a country ``that does not reflect on its
destiny.''
   Uruguay, which is the size of Washington state and lies between
South American giants Brazil and Argentina, was a pioneer in
legalizing divorce, ousting Catholic church doctrine from public
schools, and even removing crucifixes from tax-supported hospitals.
   It changed the names of major holidays to take out religious
references and until 1984 resisted establishment of a Catholic
university.
   The church's only significatnt victory came in 1938 when it
successfully pressed for the repeal of a law legalizing abortion.
   President Sanguinetti, a civilian lawyer and journalist, says he
believes in God but not in formal religion.
   In the capital, Montevideo, John Paul planned to say an outdoor
Mass in a 82,000-capacity soccer stadium, meet with the nation's
bishops, and address students and representatives of the local
Protestant and Jewish communities.
   The pope's three-day stay in Uruguay also includes trips to
three interior towns. He plans five days in Bolivia, a major source
of the world's cocaine where government austerity measures to
eliminate 20,000 percent inflation have caused serious labor unrest.
   John Paul then heads for a 1{-day stay in Lima, the capital of
Peru, another major cocaine source and the scene of violence by
anti-government Marxist insurgents.
   The journey _ the pope's 37th foreign mission in his nearly 10
years in the Vatican _ ends with three days in Paraguay, which has
a reputation as an international center of smuggling. The pope
returns to Rome on May 18, his 68th birthday.
</TEXT>
