<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSDemonstrationsRdp     05-07 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Demonstrations Rdp,0700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Activists March for Better AIDS Funding, End to Discrimination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of activists marched for increased AIDS funding in a
downpour in California's capital Saturday, while hundreds more
participated in rallies in Washington, D.C., Albany, N.Y., and
elsewhere.
   In Rosemont, Ill., 10 people were arrested in a protest of what
they said was a 500 percent price increase for a drug to treat AIDS
by a company under federal scrutiny for quality-control measures.
   The demonstrations were part of a nationwide effort by gay
activists to call attention to the AIDS epidemic and discrimination
against homosexuals.
   The Sacramento march was one of the largest ever at the
California capital. State police estimated the crowd at 6,000 to
10,000 marchers, and organizers who had hoped for up to 50,000
people blamed the rain for lowering the turnout.
   Carrying signs that read ``Ignorance is the Real Disease'' and
placards from counties throughout the state, marchers chanted,
cheered and sang their way through the streets of downtown
Sacramento.
   A balloon-carrying delegation from politically conservative
Orange County chanted ``Orange County ain't so straight.'' Other
marchers, some wrapped in plastic trash bags to stay dry, chanted
``Fight AIDS, fight back.''
   Part of a makeshift stage on the capitol steps was set aside for
people with AIDS.
   ``I would've come even if I was very, very sick, because this
means something,'' said Bobby Kennedy, an AIDS patient from San
Francisco who sat bundled in blankets in a wheelchair. ``We're
living proof that what they're doing is not OK.''
   Marchers also rallied at the capitol steps in Albany, handing
out leaflets and displaying a quilt whose patches portrayed the
names of New Yorkers who have died of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   ``We are demanding that Gov. Mario Cuomo and the state
legislature intensify their efforts to develop a comprehensive
range of services for people with AIDS,'' Libby Post of the New
York State Lesbian and Gay Lobby told the crowd of about 400.
   She said a state policy on AIDS should include quality health
care and housing for AIDS victims, an end to discrimination, access
to promising experimental treatment and an AIDS prevention program
for all New Yorkers.
   In the nation's capital, shouting, hand-clapping demonstrators
gathered across Pennsylvania Avenue from the White House, although
President Reagan was away for the weekend at his Camp David retreat.
   The demonstrators chanted, ``Reagan, Reagan, you can't hide; we
charge you with genocide.''
   Across the street, another group held up signs urging Reagan to
move more vigorously against the regime of Panamanian strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega. Together the two groups had about 200
protesters.
   In Ohio, about 100 people gathered in downtown Cincinnati for a
rally, where activists lauded federal plans to distribute pamphlets
on AIDS to every home in the United States. A march in Cleveland
also drew dozens of participants.
   The 10 Illinois protesters were charged with trespassing at the
corporate headquarters of LyphoMed Inc., maker of pentamidine, a
medication used to fight a form of pneumonia that frequently kills
people with AIDS.
   LyphoMed has been under investigation by the federal Food and
Drug Administration, which in a routine check last year found
underfilled vials of drugs and indications of contamination. The
company said it appointed a new director of quality control and
vowed to correct the problems.
   The protesters contend that LyphoMed has raised the price of
pentamidine 500 percent in the past three years. No one answered
the telephone at LyphoMed headquarters Saturday. Pharmaceutical
companies have said that the rapid expansion of knowledge about
AIDS makes research and development of drugs expensive and
speculative.
   ``A single bottle of this drug, about 300 milligrams, costs
$129,'' said Paul Adams, a spokesman for the protesters, members of
a group called Chicago For AIDS Rights, or C-Far, which numbers its
group at about 100.
   Organizers of the other demonstrations said they were affiliated
with various local gay rights groups and with national coalitions
going by the names ACT-NOW, for AIDS Coalition To Network, Organize
and Win, and Act-Up, for AIDS Coalition To Unleash Power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
