<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CandidateWithdraws     05-07 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidate Withdraws,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidate for University President Withdraws Amid Plagiarism
Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Minnesota's interim
president apologized Saturday to the head of the school's Board of
Regents after withdrawing as a candidate for president at another
university amid plagiarism allegations.
   Board of Regents Chairman David Lebedoff said interim President
Richard Sauer called him to apologize for the incident in which
Sauer admitted lifting part of a presentation for the North Dakota
State University job from a magazine article without crediting it.
   Sauer has acknowledged that in a speech he has given several
times in the past six weeks he failed to credit the article.
   ``I got a phone call from Mr. Sauer and he apologized in a very
heartfelt manner for what he described as a `bad mistake' on his
part,'' Lebedoff said.
   Sauer called the lack of attribution ``a dumb thing to do.''
   ``I made a mistake of poor judgment, in retrospect, and I
apologize for that,'' he said. ``I don't think I explicitly said
they were my words, but I used them as an example of points to
consider and I didn't cite (the author's) name.''
   Asked if the incident could possibly lead to a call for Sauer to
step down as interim president, Lebedoff said, ``I don't want to
speculate on that.''
   Regents and lawmakers interviewed by The Associated Press
Saturday said they had heard no calls for Sauer's resignation and
expressed support for him.
   The 48-year-old Sauer was vice president of agriculture,
forestry and home economics at the university before becoming
interim president in March to replace Kenneth Keller. Keller
resigned amid controversy over cost overruns to renovate the
official residence of the university president and over a $200,000
renovation of his office suite.
   Sauer conceded Friday night that he had failed to credit the
article in the speech given at NDSU in Fargo, N.D., on Monday, but
said he had not been trying to claim authorship.
   He called William C. Nelson, chairman of North Dakota State
University's presidential search committee, to say he was
withdrawing from consideration, according to Nelson, who said he
unsuccessfully tried to get Sauer to remain a candidate.
   Sauer's speech was presented to several hundred professors,
faculty and students at a forum for the candidates. History
Professor Larry R. Peterson said he recognized part of the speech
as being nearly identical to points made by Cornell University
President Frank Rhodes in the May 22, 1985, edition of the
Chronicle of Higher Education.
   He said he forwarded the information to the presidential search
committee.
   However, the committee on Thursday recommended Sauer and three
others to the North Dakota Board of Higher Education after
accepting Sauer's explanation that he accidentally omitted the
credit in trying to shorten his speech, Nelson said.
</TEXT>
