<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ColemanTrial     05-07 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coleman Trial,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Georgia Jury Ordered to Deliberate Sunday on Coleman Sentencing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DECATUR, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors spent a fourth day deliberating
whether Wayne Carl Coleman should be executed for killing six
family members, but adjourned Saturday without reaching a decision.
   A rare Sunday session was ordered by Superior Judge Hugh Lawson,
with some participants in the case predicting deliberations could
continue into next week.
   Earlier Saturday, Lawson issued a partial recharge to the
jurors, telling them they should each listen to the views of the
others. ``The jury room is no place for the championship of causes
on either side of the issue. A juror should not be an advocate.''
   The retrial jury, which found Coleman guilty of six counts of
murder on Monday, began deliberating his sentence Wednesday
afternoon.
   Lawson has given no indication when he might halt the
deliberations. If the jury does not decide unanimously for his
execution, Coleman, whose original death sentence for the 1973
slayings was overturned on appeal, will be sentenced to life in
prison.
   Legal experts are divided on whether Coleman, who has served 15
years from his original conviction, would be immediately eligible
for parole consideration.
   Indications that the sequestered jurors were having difficulty
reaching a verdict surfaced Wednesday evening, when they reported
they were not close to completing their task. On Thursday, a female
juror sent Lawson a note telling him she had made up her mind and
wouldn't change it. That juror nodded repeatedly Friday as Lawson
reviewed the law regarding mitigating circumstances that might
justify a decision to spare his life.
   Coleman, Carl Isaacs and George Elder Dungee were convicted of
murder and sentenced to death in 1974 for the May 14, 1973,
killings of Ned Alday, his brother Aubrey, Ned's sons Jimmy, Jerry
and Chester, and Jerry's wife, Mary. The five men were shot one by
one in Jerry Alday's mobile home in rural Seminole County; Mary
Alday was killed in a nearby field after she was repeatedly raped.
   The convictions were overturned by a federal appeals court in
1985 because of excessive pretrial publicity. Isaacs was convicted
a second time and sentenced to death in January. Dungee is to be
retried later in Columbus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
