<DOCNO> AP880507-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 2143EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-FloridaDemocrats     05-07 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida Democrats,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Askew Departure Opens Up Other Races, Too</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Askew, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Reubin Askew's decision to
pull out of the U.S. Senate race Saturday sent several politicians
scrambling because of the likely impact on Senate, gubernatorial
and congressional races.
   ``It's a whole new ballgame,'' state Democratic Chairman Charles
Whitehead said Saturday after Askew made public a decision he had
revealed to other politicians the night before. ``Everybody was
burning up the phones last night.''
   Following the equally surprising December decision of three-term
Democratic Sen. Lawton Chiles not to run for reelection, Askew
again deprived the the party of what it felt was a sure winner.
   ``If there ever was a gimmie, it was there,'' Whitehead said.
``It was his race to lose.''
   The Democratic nominee will likely face U.S. Rep. Connie Mack
III. The Republican from Cape Coral is doing well raising money and
can count on substantial help from the national Republican Party as
it tries to regain a Senate seat from Florida after Republican Sen.
Paula Hawkins lost to then-Gov. Bob Graham in 1986.
   Dan Miller, state president of the AFL-CIO and active among
state Democrats, called Askew's decision ``a real shame.''
   ``But it's still a long season. We have enough time,'' Miller
said.
   Miller suggested that Mack's boost from the Askew withdrawal may
be short-lived.
   ``I think Paula Hawkins and Rep. Bill McCollum (who both had
considered running this year for the Republican nomination) stayed
out because of Reubin Askew. They may change their minds now,''
Miller said.
   U.S. Rep. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay of Ocala was poised to jump
into the Democratic race, which he had stayed out because of
Askew's candidacy. MacKay, who was endorsed by Askew Saturday,
scheduled a news conference for Monday and was expected to pick up
the support of Askew backers. He spent much of Saturday telephoning
Askew supporters.
   Rep. Dan Mica was the only announced Democratic candidate
remaining. He spent Saturday telephoning Florida Democrats from his
Washington office, hoping to take advantage of his headstart in the
Democratic race.
   Mica has a strong southeastern Florida base, but some Democrats
here Saturday speculated that another South Florida congressman,
Larry Smith of Hollywood, or other candidates might consider
joining the race.
   Other speculation as Florida state party officials and activists
met Saturday to name at-large delegates to the national
presidential convention centered on the domino effect.
   MacKay was among leading Democrats lining up for the right to
challenge Republican Gov. Bob Martinez in 1990, so his switch to
the Senate race could prompt others to join state Sen. George
Stuart of Orlando, the only announced candidate for governor.
   The opening of MacKay's seat could make an opportunity for state
House Speaker Jon Mills to go to Washington.
   There also was speculation that the Republicans' improved
chances of winning the Senate seat in November would probably make
national Democrats reluctant to open up another Senate seat by
pushing for Graham as a vice presidential nominee.
</TEXT>
