<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RockefellerFoundation     05-07 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rockefeller Foundation,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foundation Names Times Mirror Executive As New President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter C. Goldmark, senior vice president in
charge of five newspapers for the Times Mirror Co., has been named
president and chief executive officer of the Rockefeller
Foundation, it was announced Saturday.
   Goldmark, 47, will succeed Richard W. Lyman, a historian who
will become the first director of the Institute of International
Studies at Stanford University this fall, the foundation said.
   The appointment is effective July 1. Currently, Goldmark is
responsible for Newsday, The (Baltimore) Sun, The Hartford (Conn.)
Courant, The Advocate in Stamford, Conn., and The Morning Call in
Allentown, Pa., for Times Mirror, which owns the Los Angeles Times.
   Before joining Times Mirror in 1985, Goldmark served eight years
as executive director of the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey.
   He was New York state's budget director from 1975 to 1977 and
for four years prior to that served as Massachusetts secretary of
human services.
   The foundation, which made grants totaling $60.9 million in
1987, is a private philanthropic organization offering financial
support and fellowships for the arts and humanities and promoting
equal opportunity for minorities. It has distributed more than $1.8
billion to institutions and individuals throughout the world in its
75-year history.
</TEXT>
