<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 2210EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AustinCentennial     05-07 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austin Centennial,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austin Throws a Texas-Sized Party to Celebrate Capitol Centennial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governors past and present, cowboys and
Indians and thousands of other Texans gathered Saturday to throw a
100th birthday party for the pink granite Capitol building that
state leaders said symbolizes Texas.
   ``Texas today is as solid as these walls, and our future is as
bright as the gilded Lone Star held aloft by the Goddess of
Liberty,'' Gov. Bill Clements said in a speech moved into the House
chamber because of rain.
   Sporadic drizzle and gloomy skies forced cancellation of a
morning balloon race and thinned crowds for the Capitol Centennial
parade. But Clements and his wife, Rita, proclaimed the day a
success.
   ``The spirits weren't dampened by the wetness,'' Clements said
from the Governor's Mansion reviewing stand, from which he watched
the parade.
   Texas food was dished up alongside historical exhibits on the
Capitol grounds. Tepees were erected near a cavalry campsite. The
building itself remained festooned with Centennial Ball decorations
from the dance Friday night.
   Festivities included a blessing of the grounds by the First
American League, representing Indian tribes in Texas and Oklahoma.
Clements, Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby and House Speaker Gib Lewis received
ceremonial war bonnets and smoked a peace pipe with the Indians.
   The pipe had not been used since 1865 when the United States
signed a treaty with the Kiowa, Comanche and Apache tribes.
   R.C. Ahtone of Oklahoma, chairman of the Indian group, offered a
prayer in his native tongue and instructed the politicians to round
dance ``to make this thing complete.''
   Afterward, the governor and Mrs. Clements cut a giant
Capitol-shaped cake as children sang ``Happy Birthday.''
   Former Govs. Dolph Briscoe, John Connally, Preston Smith and
Price Daniel joined in the parade and House chamber ceremony.
Houston Daniel, a descendant of Sam Houston, read part of the May
16, 1888, Capitol dedication speech given by Temple Houston, a
state senator and son of Sam Houston, the pre-statehood governor.
   Several thousand people lined the parade route, but the rain
held the crowd to far below the 30,000 that organizers had
predicted would take part in at least part of the day's activities.
</TEXT>
