<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Demonstrations     05-07 0141</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Italy-Demonstrations,0146</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Of Thousands Of Workers March In Rome</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of workers marched in the capital Saturday
to demand more jobs and financial help for southern Italy, where
unemployment has topped 20 percent.
   An estimated 200,000 people took part in what Italian news
agencies and state-run television called the largest such
demonstration in a decade.
   Protesters chanting ``work, work'' marched amid a sea of red
banners and blue and white stripped union flags. Many others waved
yellow placards demanding jobs.
   Unemployment last year dropped from 8.2 percent to 7.6 percent
in northern Italy and remained about 10 percent in the central part
of the country. But in the South, unemployement rose from 18.4
percent to 20.6 percent.
   Organizers said about 70,000 people demonstrated separately,
demanding higher salaries for teachers and recognition of their
independent negotiating committees.
</TEXT>
