<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Germany-Demonstration     05-07 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Germany-Demonstration,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Pelt Right-Wing Leader's House With Rocks, Bags of
Paint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOETTINGEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,500 protesters on
Saturday gathered in front of a house owned by a leader of a
right-wing political group, and police said the building was pelted
with rocks and paint-filled bags.
   Officials said the protest took place at a house owned by a
regional leader of the small Free German Workers Party in the
village of Mackenrode, located just east of Goettingen in the
southwest part of the country.
   There were no reports of arrests or injuries. The identity of
the party leader was not released.
   Police said several protesters carried placards that read ``Do
something against the Nazis.''
   Several hundred police had circled the house to prevent
demonstrators from entering the property, officials said.
</TEXT>
