<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BridgeCollapse     05-07 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bridge Collapse,0342</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shipping Will Be Delayed On Route To Lake Michigan</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos HMD1, CX5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ship traffic on the Calumet River, a vital route
for steel and grain, could be suspended up to four weeks while
crews try to untangle a freighter and a bridge that collapsed on
top of it, authorities said Saturday.
   The drawbridge and the 590-foot vessel collided near the
Illinois International Port District Friday night, but officials
still weren't sure if the bridge was lowered onto the ship or if
the freighter struck the span.
   There were no injuries among the 27-member crew.
   ``The Coast Guard is investigating the whole collision,'' said
Ensign Glena Hermes. ``Once they find out the who and the what,
they will be able to tell the how and the why. Until then the cause
is pure speculation.''
   In the worst case, 20 to 30 ships that travel Lake Michigan and
make deliveries via the Calumet River could be barred while the
steel mess is sorted out, said Coast Guard Lt. Chris Boegel.
   The cleanup could take only two days or as long as a month, he
said.
   ``This is discouraging for them,'' Boegel added, referring to
shippers. ``This bridge is blocking the entrance of the harbor from
Lake Michigan. That's where they drop off their steel.''
   The Illinois International Port District, also known as the Port
of Chicago, is near the Illinois-Indiana border in an gritty
industrial area with both shuttered and thriving steel plants.
   The Baltimore & Ohio Railroad bridge is tangled with the
Pondokratis, a ship registered in Cyprus, as the freighter was
heading through the river channel to Lake Michigan. The ship
traveled a few more yards, pulling the massive span with it.
   The ship had just unloaded steel and was bound for Duluth, Minn.
   ``The ship had 25 yards to go before it cleared the bridge,''
said Howard Schillaci, a sales clerk at Calumet Fisheries Inc., who
saw the accident.
</TEXT>
