<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0653,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms Develop In The Central States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 3rd to UPDATE with later storms. SUBS
8th graf ``Snow fell'' with two grafs to UPDATE with wind blamed
for Wisonsin forest fire, later snow totals in Rockies. Picks up
9th graf pvs ``An advisory.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms with hail and a possibility of tornadoes
developed Saturday ahead of a cold front crossing the central part
of the nation, and a new storm spread rain over parched northern
California.
   Thunderstorms developed during the early afternoon over eastern
North Dakota and eastern South Dakota, and eastern Kansas and
northeastern Oklahoma.
   Tornado watches were posted during the late afternoon and early
evening for parts of the eastern Dakotas, western Minnesota,
northwestern Iowa, Kansas, Missouri and Oklahoma.
   Hail the size of tennis balls pounded Shoreview, Minn., 9 miles
north of Minneapolis, and thunderstorm winds gusted to 60 mph at
Faribault, Minn.
   Thunderstorms in Oklahoma produced nickel-size hail south of El
Reno, and one-inch hail fell at Hazel, S.D., and Princeton, Kan.
   Behind the front, high wind continued to plague the central high
Plains.
   In Wyoming, wind gusted to 67 mph at Cheyenne and 80 mph at
Vedauwoo. A gust to 110 mph was reported on Table Mesa in northern
Colorado, and in the Nebraska Panhandle a gust to 71 hit Alliance,
the National Weather Service said.
   On Friday, high wind over Colorado shattered office building
windows, caused power outages and ripped the roofs off at least two
homes. Officials speculated that the wind may have been involved in
the crash of an Army helicopter at Fort Carson in which five
soldiers were injured.
   Brisk winds knocking down electric transmission lines caused
sparks that added to fire problems Saturday in northern Wisconsin
forests, where a shortage of rain has created an emergency, U.S.
Forest Service spokesman David Wester said. The fire damaged 50 to
70 acres of Chequamegon National Forest.
   Two feet of new snow fell at Cooke City, Mont., near Yellowstone
National Park, knocking out power to that area for much of the day.
Up to 20 inches of snow was reported in the Big Horn Mountains of
Wyoming. Lower elevations got heavy rain.
   An advisory for snow and blowing snow was issued for some of the
mountains of south-central Wyoming.
   In the West, a storm out of the Gulf of Alaska spread rain over
the northern half of California, with snow at some higher
elevations, especially in the northern Sierra Nevada and around
Lake Tahoe.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Rawlins, Wyo., to 91 at McAllen, Texas. The low for the
day was 20 degrees at Flagstaff, Ariz.
   For Sunday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the lower Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes region,
the upper Mississippi Valley and the northern Plains. Scattered
showers were forecast from the northern high Plains to the Great
Basin of Nevada and western Utah.
   Highs in the 50s were predicted from northern Arizona and the
Great Basin to the northern high Plains; in the 80s from the Rio
Grande Valley of Texas through the lower and middle Mississippi
Valley to the southern Atlantic Coast, and in the Southwest's
deserts; and in the 60s and 70s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
