<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 2245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FakeArt     05-07 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fake Art,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Bans Art Gallery From Selling Posters As Original Prints</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has frozen the assets of an
Illinois-based group of art galleries accused of selling $50
posters at prices up to $5,000 and calling them hand-signed,
limited-edition prints by well-known artists.
   U.S. District Judge Prentice Marshall has ordered Austin
Galleries not to represent the posters as hand-signed works by
Pablo Picasso, Salvador Dali, Marc Chagall and other painters.
   Marshall issued the order after receiving a complaint from the
Federal Trade Commission. The FTC said Austin Galleries sold the
posters as original lithographs, when in fact the artist was not
involved in the production of the works.
   Donald Austin, president of the galleries, denied the accusation
in a statement, saying his businesses have sold the prints based on
information from suppliers.
   ``We believe that everything we have is authentic until proven
different,'' Stanley J. Adelman, a lawyer for the galleries, said
Saturday. Even art experts differ on how much control an artist
must have of a print before it is considered a limited-edition
issue, he said.
   ``The frames are worth more than the prints,'' said San
Francisco District Attorney Arlo Smith, who is assisting with the
investigation.
   The FTC also asked the court to issue a permanent order against
any misrepresentations in the sale of the artwork and to order the
company to make restitution to customers. The order freezes the
company's assets and allows FTC attorneys to inspect gallery
records.
   Austin Galleries, headquartered in suburban Palatine, has about
eight outlets in Illinois and California, Adelman said.
   The prints were sold at prices ranging from $200 to $5,000.
   ``We rely upon our suppliers to authenticate these works, and
I'm more interested than anyone that what we buy and sell is
authentic,'' said Austin.
   He said that in more than 20 years in the art field neither
Austin Galleries nor he has ``ever been involved in any lawsuit
even remotely suggesting that the works of art sold by us are
anything other than what they are represented to be.''
   It is company policy to give a refund if a customer secures a
written opinion from a ``recognized art expert'' that a print is
not authentic, said Austin.
   Adelman said the business would cooperate fully with the
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
