<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 2319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ZeroTolerance     05-07 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zero Tolerance,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$2.5 Million Yacht Seized For Less Than A Tenth Of An Ounce Of
Marijuana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $2.5 million luxury yacht was seized Saturday
after a U.S. Coast Guard search turned up bits of marijuana on
board.
   Less than one-tenth of an ounce of marijuana was found in a
trash can, dresser and in the state room of the 133-foot Ark Royal
boarded in the Yucatan Channel between Mexico and Cuba, said Coast
Guard spokesman Luis Diaz.
   The seizure was the most extreme example yet of the Reagan
administration's new ``Zero Tolerance'' policy in applying laws
permitting confiscation of ships and vehicles used to transport
illegal drugs.
   ``It's the largest in terms of size and by far the most
expensive and luxurious vessel we've seized under this policy,''
Diaz said, adding that 12 boats have been seized since April 11.
Tractor-trailers have been seized along the Canadian border under a
similar program.
   The Coast Guard cutter Tampa stopped the yacht Saturday morning
to check paperwork and safety equipment, Diaz said.
   ``Just by accident, one of the officers spotted the marijuana in
the trash can and that prompted a thorough search of every corner
of the vessel,'' he said.
   The seized yacht was being brought to Key West Saturday night
along with the six people on board, who will probably not be
charged, Diaz said.
   ``We have been focusing all our efforts in recent years on just
the big smugglers, but drugs are a two-way street,'' Diaz said.
``This is the time we're making the users pay. It really has to
hurt to see a luxury yacht taken away for what basically amounts to
one joint.''
   Under the tougher Reagan administration policy, a seized boat
must be returned to its owners only if allegations of illegal drugs
on board are proved to be false. Otherwise, the boat is turned over
to U.S. Customs, which can sell it at auction.
</TEXT>
