<HEAD>Dan Rather, Jimmy Stewart, Others Stress Old Values in
Commencement Addresses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORMAN, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Evening News anchor Dan Rather told the
University of Oklahoma's graduating seniors Saturday that if
America is to reclaim the ideals that made it great, today's
graduates must acknowledge that ``greed is out'' and ``achievement
is in.''
   ``You must leave here today with a commitment to contribute,''
said Rather, commencement speaker for Oklahoma's 96th graduation
exercise. ``Find a life's work worthy of yourself and your
heritage, commit yourself with all the zeal that you can muster and
throw yourself into it.''
   In Stillwater, the state's new higher education chancellor told
Oklahoma State University's graduating seniors that research funds
will provide the means by which the state will successfully adapt
to the future.
   ``Money, money, money ... that is what is needed. And we should
not be bashful about it,'' said Chancellor Hans Brisch.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Jimmy Stewart urged University of
South Carolina graduates to support traditional values, as several
colleges in the state held commencement exercises Saturday.
   ``You need to stand up for hard work, decent values, love of
country, love of family, love of community and love of God,''
Stewart told the 1,589 undergraduates who received degrees.
   Stewart, star of such films as ``It's A Wonderful Life,'' ``Mr.
Smith Goes to Washington,'' ``The Philadelphia Story'' and ``Rear
Window,'' was awarded an honorary doctor of fine arts degree.
   In Rock Hill, former Secretary of Education Terrel Bell told
graduates of Winthrop College they should become deeply involved in
the education reform movement.
   Bell told the 500 graduates that the nation's top problem is the
number of school dropouts. Nationwide, 30 percent of high school
students drop out of school, he said.
   In Gaffney, Robert E. Coleman, chairman of Textile Hall Corp. of
Greenville, told 360 graduates of Limestone College the ABCs they
need for success _ proper attitudes, strong beliefs and sincere
commitments.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) Veteran newsman and grammarian Edwin Newman
told graduates of North Carolina State University Saturday that
inflated language and poor grammar are dragging down the United
States.
   Speaking at a football stadium where three days earlier the rock
group Pink Floyd sang, ``We don't need no education,'' Newman said
Americans have become addicted to ``mush, to smog, to dull,
pompous, boneless, gassy language.''
   ``It's a grave handicap since there is a direct connection
between the skill and the efficiency with which a nation uses its
language and its ability to compete in the modern world,'' said
Newman.
   Meanwhile, Mary Hatwood Futrell, president of the National
Education Association, gave the Reagan administration an ``F-plus''
for its efforts on behalf of education, children and young people.
   ``And the only reason they get the `plus' is because Congress
... time after time, voted against the administration and said,
`the children of America are too important for us to do what you
want us to do,''' she told the 630 graduates of North Carolina
Central University in Durham.
   At the University of North Carolina at Asheville, the former
director of recruiting for the Peace Corps said the ``Me Decade''
may be giving way to the ``We Decade.''
   Robert L. Gale, who recruited for the Peace Corps from 1962 to
1965 and is now president of the Association of Governing Boards of
Universities and Colleges in Washington, D.C., said Americans may
be growing tired of the excesses of ``Me-ism.''
   ``Having learned that a 60-hour work week, a pile of money, and
all the material goods it buys won't necessarily make one feel
happy and fulfilled, young people in great numbers are again
becoming volunteers,'' Gale told the 306 graduates.
</TEXT>
