<HEAD>Panama Party Official Roughed Up, Expelled to Miami</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of Panama's Christian Democratic Party
arrived Friday, expelled from his homeland after being arrested,
beaten on his feet with a rock and held overnight in prison, an
immigration official said.
   Party Secretary General Ivan Romero was detained Thursday when
he flew to Panama after a weeklong visit to the United States, said
Perry Rivkind, local director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
   ``They apparently interpreted something he said in New York as
unflattering to Gen. (Manuel Antonio) Noriega,'' Rivkind said.
   Noriega is under indictment for alleged drug trafficking in
Florida, and the United States has called for his ouster from power.
   Romero told INS officials here he was taken to a military prison
immediately upon his arrival in Panama. ``He said they held him for
seven hours and beat him on his feet with a rock a little,'' said
Rivkind.
   His captors then drove him to the airport and put him on a plane
to Miami.
