<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MakeMyDay     05-07 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Make My Day,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man in `Make-My-Day' Law Case Gets Life for Murder of Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who successfully used a
``make-my-day'' defense in the killing of a neighbor was sentenced
Friday to life in prison for the murder of his estranged wife.
   David Guenther, 35, who shot to death his wife, Pamela, and
wounded her boyfriend outside a restaurant last year, cannot be
considered for parole for 40 years, District Judge Harlan Bockman
ruled.
   Guenther also was given a consecutive eight-year term for
wounding Stanley Stinson.
   As he left court and got into a police car, Guenther told
reporters, ``I'll have another trial someday, hopefully in about a
year.'' His lawyers have already planned an appeal.
   Stinson, who attended the sentencing, said he was angry that the
parole restriction was not stiffer, saying it should have been for
at least 80 years.
   In April 1986, Guenther fatally shot one neighbor and wounded
two other people in the climax to a neighborhood feud. A judge
ruled he acted lawfully under the state's new ``make my day'' law,
which allows residents to use deadly force in their homes against
intruders.
   The name comes from a Clint Eastwood movie in which he plays a
police officer who urges a criminal to shoot at him so he'll have a
reason to fire back. Eastwood's character says, ``Go ahead, make my
day.''
   However, the Colorado Supreme Court overturned that ruling and
made Guenther stand trial. A jury acquitted him last October,
finding he acted in self-defense.
   But by then, Guenther was charged with killing his 30-year-old
wife and injuring Stinson.
   The Guenthers' children, Christopher, 13, and Jennifer, 11,
witnessed the March 1, 1987, shootings, and were key prosecution
witnesses.
   Disagreement at the trial was not over whether Guenther fired
the shots. However, the prosecution contended Guenther acted with
deliberation, while the defense claimed Guenther fired eights shots
from his pistol in the ``heat of passion'' as he saw his wife
kissing Stinson.
   Prosecutors said the attack followed a sequence of threats and
violence by Guenther against Mrs. Guenther, who had taken the
children and left him a month before she was killed.
</TEXT>
