<HEAD>Cuba Opens Door For Lovebirds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramours pressed for privacy can check into
communist Cuba's new ``date house'' in Havana, a low-budget love
nest that guarantees at least six hours of secrecy.
   The Cuban news agency Prensa Latina said Friday the lovers' inn
is the first built in Havana ``in 30 years of revolution.''
   Couples who lack privacy because of Cuba's housing shortage
might be interested in the inn, the news agency said, as would
``pairs of sweethearts, conquering Don Juans and unhappy wives.''
   It said a small cabin is available for a minimum six hours at a
moderate price. The facility has ``all the comforts and services
that the most demanding users might require.
   ``The modern cabins with air conditioning, indirect music and
food and drink services contrast openly with the old buildings
where all days at all hours couples line up waiting for a chance to
share a room that, the majority of times, is far distant from being
a paradise for love,'' Prensa Latina reported.
