<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites SUB a0722 05-07 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites, SUB, a0722,0174</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs last graf of first item, with MINNEISKA, Minn., dateline
to CORRECT name to Joan, sted John.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MINNEISKA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists encountering the sign of the
turtle along a two-mile stretch of rural highway will be advised to
adopt the ways of the tortoise and creep along the road.
   The signs, featuring a bold profile of a turtle, advise
motorists to slow down and help preserve a threatened species of
turtle that resembles its common wood cousin.
   Female Blanding's turtles, best recognized by a bright yellow
throat and dark, high-domed shell, cross area roadways from mid-May
to mid-June to nesting sites. Then, in the fall, turtle offspring
go back across the road to be with their parents.
   The turtle-crossing signs, posted Thursday in the Weaver area of
Wabasha County in southeastern Minnesota, are as rare as the
turtles themselves. The only other place in the nation known to
have turtle-crossing signs is May County, N.J., according to Joan
Galli of the state Department of Natural Resources.
</TEXT>
