<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Rose-Investigation     05-07 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rose-Investigation,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Into Actor's Auto Death Under Way</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PUERTO PLATA, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police official said
Friday that an investigation was under way at family request into
the single-car death here of British-born actor George Rose.
   Lt. Manuel Raboso, chief of the Homicide Investigation
Department in the Caribbean resort of Puerto Plata, said in a
telephone interview, ``We are carrying out an investigation and it
will be completed as soon as possible. Right now, I can't say what
happened.''
   Police said Thursday that Rose, 68, winner of two Tony awards on
Broadway for his roles in ``Drood'' and ``My Fair Lady,'' was
killed when his car, going at high speed, swerved into a ditch and
turned over several times in the northern Dominican Republic.
   Raboso said Friday that the investigation in part centered on
two head wounds suffered by Rose, ``both ... on the forehead.''
   He said ``the investigation is being carried out at the reguest
of friends and Juan Rose, the actor's adopted son.'' Raboso added
that his department routinely investigates all deaths, including
traffic deaths.
   Rose owned a beach home just outside the town of Sosua, about 15
miles east of Puerto Plata, near where the car wreck occurred.
   Police officer Jose Nunez said the crash occurred about 10:30
p.m. Wednesday less than a mile east of Puerto Plata, but
authorities were not aware of it until early Thursday.
   Raboso said the accident may have occurred ``early Thursday''
rather than Wednesday night. He said he based his conclusion on the
condition of Rose's body.
   Nunez had said that Rose was apparently alone when the car went
into the ditch. He was reported killed immediately. The body was
taken to Ricardo Limardo Hospital in Puerto Plata, 160 miles
northwest of Santo Domingo.
   Rose, a remarkably versatile actor who was as much at home
playing Shakespeare as he was in a comedy or a musical, had lived
in New York City since 1961.
   He preferred the stage, but also appeared in scores of film and
television productions.
</TEXT>
