<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WomenMarineGuards     05-07 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women Marine Guards,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marines Get Only Six Female Embassy Guard Applicants in Initial
Call</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps, under orders to allow women
to work as embassy security guards, has accepted its first group of
women into a training school after failing to generate much
immediate interest.
   According to a spokesman for the corps, only six female Marines
applied by the deadline to enter the next class at the Marine
Security Guard School at Quantico, Va., which begins on May 17.
   ``Of those six applicants, five have been accepted,'' Lt. Col.
John Shotwell, the spokesman, said Friday.
   Shotwell said the five female Marines would join 150 enlisted
men in the next class.
   He declined to say whether the corps was surprised or
disappointed with the low turnout of female applicants, but noted
there had been little advance notice of the change in policy
regarding security guards.
   ``The announcement was made during the first week of April, and
the deadline for applications was May 1,'' Shotwell said.
   The Marine Corps has maintained a strict men-only policy
regarding embassy security guards ever since it ended an experiment
with female guards in 1979. Fifteen women were assigned to foreign
posts during that brief pilot program, which was discontinued after
attacks on embassies in Pakistan and Iran.
   The commandant of the Marines, Gen. Alfred M. Gray, has made it
plain in recent months he would prefer to maintain the male-only
policy because he wants combat-ready Marines serving in the jobs _
and combat jobs aren't open to women.
   Gray's objections were overridden three months ago, however, by
Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci, who heeded the recommendation
of an advisory panel and ordered the positions opened. That move
was part of a campaign by civilian officials at the Pentagon to
counter criticism that the military services are discriminating
against women in job opportunities and doing too little to stop
sexual harassment.
   There are currently about 1,400 Marines serving in the embassy
security force, guarding 140 posts in 127 countries. The guard
force became the object of unwanted publicity a year ago because of
a spy-and-sex scandal involving Marines in Moscow.
   Gray and the Marine Corps leadership so far have refused to say
how many of the embassy guard positions will be opened to women,
citing the need to study everything from available housing to the
threat of terrorism and cultural considerations.
   ``There was no quota for female applicants (in the first
class),'' Shotwell said. ``Each applicant was judged on his or her
own merits. As to whether we'll see more applications in the
future, I won't speculate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
