<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dukakis-NationalGuard     05-07 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-National Guard,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Loses Court Ruling in Effort to Keep National Guard Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge, rejecting a legal challenge by
Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, ruled Friday that Congress and the
president can order National Guard troops to go on training
missions over a governor's objections.
   The ruling, the second by a U.S. District Court answering recent
challenges to federal authority, apparently will force the
front-runner for the Democratic presidential nomination to send a
Massachusetts contingent of 13 public relations officers to
Honduras and Panama later this month.
   Dukakis, a critic of Reagan administration policy in Central
America, had filed suit trying to block the two-week assignment.
   He said in a statement that he would appeal the decision,
contending, ``The Reagan administration is using National Guard
training in Central America as part of its ill-advised and illegal
strategy to overthrow the Nicaraguan government.''
   However, the governor is not seeking a stay of the ruling
pending appeal.
   ``The real issue here is not the sending of public relations
people to Honduras,'' press secretary James Dorsey said. ``The much
larger issue is the overridinig constitutional issue and sending
troops down there as a destabilizing policy. What you need, to
obtain a stay, is to demonstrate that irreparable harm would occur.
No one is going to be foolish enough to say this would cause
irreparable harm.''
   U.S. District Judge Robert Keeton, in the opinion upholding the
federal Department of Defense, said federal authorities have the
power to give orders to National Guard members because the troops
are sworn to federal duty as well as state duty.
   Lawyers for the Justice Department had argued that the ``Army
Clause'' in the Constitution gives Congress the ultimate say over
the nation's entire military apparatus.
   The Massachusetts attorney general's office, representing
Dukakis, had contended the ``Militia Clause'' reserved power to the
governors over training the militia.
   ``Under the Militia Act of 1792,'' Keeton wrote, ``virtually
every able-bodied man between 18 and 45 was enrolled in the militia
and required to arm himself at his own expense. This statute was
the only permanent legislation organizing the militia for over 100
years.''
   But in the 20th century, that status changed, he said, with the
key step being a 1933 law that made the National Guard a permanent
part of the U.S. Army through the device of dual enlistment.
   Citing previous federal court rulings from the Vietnam era,
Keeton said Congress had the power under the Constitution to pass
the 1933 law.
</TEXT>
