<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru a0736 05-07 0561</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Lawsuit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0736,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Report Threats Against Witnesses With Bush Revelations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 8th graf, `The $24 million...' to CORRECT site to
Nicaragua, sted Costa Rica.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key witnesses in a suit accusing Contras and U.S.
officials of running a guns-for-drugs smuggling ring have been
threatened with prosecution to block damaging revelations about
Vice President George Bush, attorneys charged Friday.
   Bush, head of the CIA in 1976, allegedly allowed some of the
suit's defendants, including his covert operations chief, Theodore
Shackley, to set up an underground ``secret team'' to hide their
activities from the incoming Carter administration, said
plaintiffs' attorney Daniel Sheehan.
   ``They were running covert operations for Bush,'' Sheehan told
U.S. District Judge James King. ``Then they set up an off-the-shelf
operation.''
   Sheehan said an effort to intimidate witnesses and cripple the
suit has prevented revelations that could hurt Bush in his
presidential campaign.
   But defense attorney Theodore Klein, who represents three of the
29 defendants, dismissed the Bush-CIA conection as a ploy by
Sheehan, saying Sheehan cannot ``provide a single witness'' to
prove the case.
   ``I don't know where George Bush comes in all of a sudden,''
Klein told the judge. ``I think it bears witness to their political
motivation.''
   The arguments came up during a hearing on the case, which has a
June 29 trial date. The plaintiffs made a number of requests, which
the judge took under advisement and is expected to rule on next
week.
   The $24 million damage and racketeering suit charges that the
defendants _ including indicted Iran-Contra figures Richard Secord
and Albert Hakim _ supplied the Contras with weapons in trade for
cocaine through a secret illegal network. The suit also accuses the
group of planning the May 1984 bombing that injured maverick rebel
leader Eden Pastora in Nicaragua.
   Sheehan works for the liberal Washington-based Christic
Institute, which represents the plaintiffs, journalists Tony
Avirgan and Martha Honey. Avirgan was slightly injured in the 1984
bombing.
   Sheehan's assistant, Lewis Pitts, said that when he tried to
interview mercenary Jack Terrell and others about the smuggling
operation, they told him they had been threatened with indictment
if they gave any statements.
   FBI agents and a Miami grand jury were ``used to silence these
little people, to interfere with the investigation,'' Pitts told
the judge. ``We have concerns about political factors affecting
judicial decisions.''
   Thomas Spencer, attorney for former Maj. Gen. John K. Singlaub,
attacked the plaintiffs for failing to stick to the point of the
suit, damages to Avirgan and Honey.
   ``They are attempting to use this forum to launch their
political arguments,'' said Spencer.
   Pitts argued that the judge could grant immunity to the
plaintiff's witnesses, usually only a prerogative of prosecutors.
But Klein said such an order violated the constitutional separation
of powers.
   Sheehan sought the right to depose witnesses going back for a
10-year period, including the time Bush was head of the CIA,
instead of the four years as King initially granted. The judge
warned that the trial was unlikely to be delayed.
   King denied discussing the suit with U.S. District Judge Gerhard
Gesell, who is handling the Iran-Contra criminal cases in
Washington. Gesell had said in court he would not allow the civil
suit to interfere with the criminal cases against Oliver North and
the other Iran-Contra defendants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
