<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SkyscraperSurvivors     05-07 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Skyscraper Survivors,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`This is It, I'm Going to Die,' Fire Survivor Thought Before
Rescue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Skyscraper Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman rescued from the 37th floor of a
burning skyscraper said her last thought before passing out from
the thick smoke was, ``Sunday's my birthday and I'm not ever going
to be there to turn 29.''
   Melinda Skaar was trapped for more than three hours Wednesday
before losing consciousness as a fire in the First Interstate Bank
tower spread from the 12th to the 16th floors and spewed smoke
throughout its 62 stories.
   ``This is it, I'm going to die,'' Skaar, a financial analyst,
said she told herself as she and Stephen Oskas, an assistant vice
president at the bank, fled from room to room to escape the heavy
smoke.
   One person died and at least 40 people were injured before the
fire was extinguished early Thursday, four hours after it began.
   Roberto Lopez, a janitor, said he was certain he was going to
die in the 50th-floor closet where he sought refuge from the thick
smoke.
   ``I didn't think I had any chance of surviving,'' he recalled.
   Lopez, who has worked at the high-rise for 11 years, said his
final thoughts before passing out were of his family and his
childhood in Mexico.
   Firefighters carried him to the roof, where he was airlifted to
safety. He was listed in fair condition at County-USC Medical
Center Friday.
   Skar and Oskas, who had stayed to work late, were overcome by
smoke by the time firefighters reached them and carried them to
safety.
   Skaar said she thought of her boyfriend of eight years and her
birthday. ``I thought, `Sunday's my birthday and I'm not ever going
to be there to turn 29,''' she said.
   Ms. Skaar was hospitalized at Good Samaritan Hospital to recover
from smoke inhalation. Oskas, who was listed in stable condition at
Queen of Angels Hospital, declined to be interviewed.
   Ms. Skaar said that after the thick smoke kept her and Oskas
from getting down the stairs, they looked for offices with the
least smoke. They tried to break the building's thick windows by
hurling furniture and file cabinets, only to watch the objects
bounce off.
   Rescuers found them shortly after they collapsed.
   ``All I remember is seeing these bodies a few minutes later,''
she said. ``Strong bodies that weren't like ours, bodies that could
walk and breathe and had equipment with them and would rescue us.''
</TEXT>
