<HEAD>Glenn Would Consider Veep Offer, But Doesn't Seek It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John Glenn said Friday he would
consider an offer to run for vice president on the 1988 Democratic
ticket but will not seek it and has not encouraged speculation
about it.
   At a news conference, the Ohio Democrat said the vice presidency
``is not an office you campaign for,'' and that recent plugs for
him by Ohio Gov. Richard Celeste and others have been strictly
their own doing.
   ``All of these things have been occurring without one word from
me or my office,'' Glenn said. But he said that if he is asked by
likely Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis, he would be glad to ``to
sit down and discuss it.''
   Glenn's own presidential bid in 1984 faltered early in the
primary season. Four years later, his debt still stands at about $2
million.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>JFK Most Feared George Romney As Re-Election Opponent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1963, President Kennedy feared then-Michigan
Gov. George Romney more as a potential re-election opponent than
Richard Nixon, Nelson Rockefeller or Barry Goldwater.
   Kennedy's worries about Romney are revealed in a book about the
late president's brother, Robert F. Kennedy, to be published next
month by Bantam Books.
   The book, ``Robert Kennedy: In His Own Words,'' includes the
transcript of a December 1964 interview with Anthony Lewis of the
New York Times, in which Robert Kennedy said his brother thought
Romney would be ``so difficult to soak.''
   Robert Kennedy also told Lewis in the previously unpublished
interview that John Kennedy thought Goldwater would have been the
easiest opponent to beat. Goldwater won the GOP nomination in 1964
and was defeated soundly by Lyndon Johnson.
   Romney's 1968 presidential hopes burst when he said after a
visit to Vietnam, ``When I came back from Vietnam (in 1965) I had
just had the greatest brainwashing that anybody can get when you go
over to Vietnam...not only by the generals but also by the
diplomatic corps over there, and they do a very thorough job.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Campbell Launches Effort to Draft Strauss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Iowa Democrat said Friday he has
launched an effort to draft Bob Strauss, a Texas businessman and
former national head of the party, as a running mate for likely
nominee Michael Dukakis.
   ``Bob Strauss can't be tagged as a liberal, he can't be tagged
as a conservative _ he's a national Democrat,'' said Ed Campbell, a
former chairman of the Iowa Democratic Party who ran unsuccessfully
for the party's nomination for governor.
   Campbell said he has been encouraged in talks with Democratic
leaders in Washington as well as with low-level Dukakis staffers.
   He said Strauss would offer both regional and philosophical
balance to a Dukakis ticket, as well as experience in philosophical
balance to a Dukakis ticket, as well as experience in foriegn
affairs.
   ``I want to win this time, I think every Democrat wants to
win,'' he said. ``I think a Dukakis-Strauss ticket would be
dynamite.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Network Executives To Testify At Poll Closing Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives from all three television networks
are scheduled to testify next week at a Senate committee hearing on
legislation that would set a uniform closing time for polls
nationwide.
   The Senate Rules Committee hearing will come less than a month
after the president of NBC News indicated he was uncomfortable with
an agreement with Congress not to project the winner of the
presidential election until all polls close.
   Washington Democratic Rep. Al Swift, House sponsor of the bill,
and other Western lawmakers have argued that network projections
have discouraged people from voting and even affected outcomes of
close local and state elections in the West.
   Under the proposed bill, polls would close simultaneously across
the country at 9 p.m. EST on Election Day. In the Pacific Time
Zone, daylight savings time would be extended by a maximum of two
weeks during presidential election years, allowing polls to close
at 7 p.m.
   The bill, approved by the House late last year, will not cover
the 1988 presidential election.
</TEXT>
