<2ND_LINE>AM-Disasters-Glance,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sorting Through Wreckage of Explosions and Fires</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Industrial Accidents Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments Friday in the aftermath of
the fiery disasters in three cities that killed at least six people
this week:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   REFINERY BLAST
   In Norco, La., workers searched the ruins of a Shell Oil Co.
refinery, looking for four men still missing since explosions
Thursday killed three and injured 42. The bodies of two workers
were found earlier Friday.
   Small fires fed by oil and gas residue in the tangle of pipes
and equipment still burned in the blast area.
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration and the
Environmental Protection Agency sent investigators to the plant.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   SKYSCRAPER FIRE
   In Los Angeles, a city councilman said he will propose a law
requiring automatic fire sprinklers in all city high-rises
following Thursday's fire in the 62-story First Interstate Bank
tower that killed one person and injured 40.
   First Interstate officials discounted speculation that word of
pending layoffs in the company division on the floor where the fire
broke out could have prompted arson.
   City fire officials had yet to determine the cause of the blaze
that caused $450 million in damage. Federal investigators from the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms were taking part in the
investigation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PLANT BLAST
   In Henderson, Nev., city officials met with executives from
Kerr-McGee Corp., which also makes the rocket fuel manufactured at
the now-leveled Pacific Engineering and Production Co. plant.
Kerr-McGee, located a mile from the blast site, shut down Thursday,
saying they will not reopen until they know more about the accident.
   Damage estimates topped $100 million from the explosions
Wednesday that killed two people. Nearly a third of the city's
16,000 homeowners had already filed damage claims by Friday.
</TEXT>
