<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PoisonDanger 1stLd-Writethru a0665 05-07 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poison Danger, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Warns of Poison Ipecac Danger</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 3rd graf pvs to UPDATE with comments
from general manager of Humco Laboratory Inc.; FIXES spelling of
eucalyptus throughout</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of bottles of Humco
brand syrup of Ipecac, possibly containing a deadly poison, remain
in American homes, the Food and Drug Administration said Friday.
   As many as 400,000 1-ounce bottles labeled Ipecac may actually
contain oil of eucalyptus, which could prove fatal if given to
children, the FDA said.
   Ipecac normally is used to induce vomiting in children who are
suspected of having eaten some dangerous product.
   Larry Copeland, general manager at Humco Laboratory Inc. in
Texarkana, Texas, said Friday evening that the FDA was overstating
the case by indicating that 400,000 bottles are at risk.
   ``We have sold close to 400,000 bottles since February of 1987,
but there was only one lot in which five bottles of eucalyptus oil
were mislabeled as Ipecac syrup,'' Copeland said in a telephone
interview. ``That's all that's been found and that's all that we're
aware of at this time.''
   Copeland, who identified that lot number is 2804, said the
company is recalling all lot numbers of the 1-ounce containers of
Ipecac syrup only ``to make everybody feel safer about it.''
   The FDA initially announced a recall of the Humco brand Ipecac
April 29, after the label mix-up was discovered. However, since
then it has learned that thousands of bottles of the product have
been distributed to consumers across the country as part of poison
prevention week activities.
   Finding and returning those bottles is vital, the FDA says, so
that parents will not forget and accidentally give some of the
eucalyptus oil to a child.
   Eucalyptus oil is used in minute amounts in vaporizers. But if
taken internally it can cause convulsions and coma, officials said.
As little as a teaspoonful could prove fatal, FDA reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
