<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UnitedEngines     05-07 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-United Engines,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>United: 747 Crew Had Alternate Way to Deal With Engine Failures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a jumbo jet that landed Monday in
Japan with only one of four engines operating could have used a
backup system for correcting such failures, United Airlines said
Friday.
   Pending completion of an investigation by the airline and the
National Transportation Safety Board, the plane's cockpit crew has
been grounded in what United described as a routine action in such
cases.
   Flight 97, carrying 258 people from Los Angeles to Japan, landed
safety at Tokyo's Narita airport with three engines empty of fuel,
said United spokesman Rob Doughty.
   The fourth engine had 24,700 pounds of fuel, considerably more
than the federal landing requirement of 18,400 pounds on such
flights, he said.
   The Chicago-based carrier said it had completed tests on the
Boeing 747 and discovered that failure of a valve on one fuel tank
would have prevented the crew from using normal procedures to fuel
the engines, but found no mechanical problem with the backup system.
   ``The alternate method was tested, and there was no problem,''
Doughty said. ``There are always two parts of the investigation of
this type. First, the mechanical part, which we've concluded, and
secondly, the human part, which will now be looked into.''
   Air Line Pilots Association spokesman Hank Krakowski said, ``We
usually don't comment until the investigation is complete.''
   NTSB spokesman Allan Pollock also said he would not comment
while the investigation was under way.
   The pilot had reported losing power in the first engine over the
Pacific about 1 hour, 15 minutes from Tokyo, a second engine 30
minutes later and a third engine just before landing.
</TEXT>
