<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0637EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-Week'sBusiness Adv07-08-2Takes   05-07 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 07-08-2 Takes,0846</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
<HEAD>Program Trading Debate Intensifies, Some Say Legislation
Inevitable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a typical post-crash day on Wall Street,
a slow, nervous market, when suddenly the demand for big-name
stocks jumped and started an apparent rally. Just as abruptly,
prices tumbled and the Dow Jones industrial average ended the
session with a loss.
   At Integrated Resources Asset Management, a firm that manages $5
billion in investment money, executives knew the telephone calls
would be coming in from irate clients demanding to know why the
market had seesawed for no apparent reason. The executives also
knew how they would answer: computerized program trading done by a
few big brokerages.
   ``It's just a horrendous negative for public confidence. The
public has had it with this, bottom line,'' said Harvey Eisen,
president of the firm. ``This stuff is just nonsense. It's like a
casino.''
   Eisen's anger reflects a deepening resentment among many Wall
Street professionals over what they see as the profoundly
destructive effects of program trading, a strategy for selling and
buying massive amounts of stocks instantaneously through the use of
high-speed computer systems.
   It has been widely blamed for injecting volatility into the
stock market, frightening millions of ordinary investors and
contributing to a malaise that has afflicted the securities
business since the crash nearly seven months ago.
   ``My view is that individuals feel it's a big negative for the
market and has driven some people out of the market,'' said John
Markese, vice president and research director for the American
Association of Individual Investors, a Chicago-based group.
   The New York Stock Exchange has attempted to limit the effects
of program trading since the crash by restricting the use of its
computers for the technique when the Dow average swings more than
50 points in one day.
   Nevertheless, program trading still is considered a powerful
influence, partly because it remains profitable in an otherwise
bleak market and because there are ways to sidestep the NYSE
limitations.
   Some brokers say program trading has become an even more potent
force since the crash, because its volatile side-effects are
magnified by an overall decline in trading volume.
   Clearly worried about the long-term implications, NYSE officials
this past week took an additional step to constrict program
trading, by requiring member firms to submit daily logs of all
program trades they have executed.
   The Big Board's move received a mixed reaction. Some critics of
program trading said it might take federal legislation to ban the
technique and restore market confidence.
   ``When you start destroying people's basic wealth because of
some trading scheme or gambling scheme, it obviously causes bitter
resentments,'' said David Johnson, president of Johnson, Lane,
Space, Smith & Co., a regional brokerage in Savannah, Ga. ``If
something isn't done, you'll find a political movement for it. I
think we're going to start seeing that.''
   The most commonly criticized form of program trading is index
arbitrage, a method for selling stocks in New York and buying
stock-index futures contracts in Chicago, or vice versa, to profit
from price disparities.
   Critics contend the strategy is based on mathematics that have
no relation to economic fundamentals. Moreover, they say it
involves little risk because of the relatively low margins, or down
payments, needed to trade index futures.
   Defenders say program trading has been unfairly singled out as a
disruptive force. On the contrary, they contend it helps stabilize
the market by keeping the price of stocks and stock-index futures
from varying too widely.
   ``I think too much blame has been placed on program trading,''
said Daniel Siegel, a business professor who teaches futures and
options at Northwestern University's J.L. Kellogg Graduate School
of Management.
   ``I don't see anyone complaining that interest rates are to
blame. Interest rates have been very volatile,'' Siegel said. ``The
New York Stock Exchange frankly is looking for a scapegoat.''
   Robert Gordon, president of Twenty-First Securities Corp., a New
York firm that utilizes program trading, said he welcomed the
latest NYSE requirement because it will show that the strategy's
influence is extremely limited. ``This will nail it down,'' he said.
   The most significant program traders, however, are highly
sensitive to the criticism and have declined to talk to the press
about it. Executives at Salomon Brothers Inc. and Kidder Peabody &
Co., considered among the biggest users of the technique, did not
return telephone calls for comment.
   Whatever the prognosis for program trading, some securities
professionals say an outright ban would only hurt their business in
the long run by driving customers to less restrictive markets
overseas.
   ``The strength of our capital markets and derivative securities
attract capital to this country, to the point where many countries
are working on mimicking our capability,'' said Kelly Haughton,
senior vice president of Frank Russell & Co., a Tacoma, Wash.-based
investment consulting firm.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0639EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-Week'sBusiness Adv07-08-1stAdd   05-07 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 07-08-1st Add,0776</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: ... consulting firm.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   More likely than an outright ban are stricter regulations on the
use of program trading, imposed either by the securities markets
themselves or the government, traders say.
   Among the possibilities are much higher margin requirements for
trading stock-index futures. Another is a stricter limit on the
sale of a stock when its price is falling, which could prevent the
simultaneous buying and selling of stocks and index futures crucial
to the program trading strategy.
   ``You take the profitability out of it and it won't happen any
more,'' said Johnson.
   In other business and economic news this past week:
   _The Securities and Exchange Commisssion authorized brief
trading halts across domestic markets when important news affecting
a specific stock is pending.
   _The government said the nation's unemployment rate fell to 5.4
percent in April, the lowest it has been since June 1974. The drop
sparked worries that the competition for scarce jobs would heat up
inflation. Other economic reports showed increases in factory
orders, productivity and construction spending.
   _Reports from the nation's largest general retailers showed cool
weather and an early Easter hurt retail sales in April.
   _The Supreme Court, in an antitrust ruling that could make
bargain-hunting more difficult, said manufacturers do not always
act illegally when they agree with retailers to stop supplying
discount stores.
   _An OPEC conference ended with no agreement on a plan to
orchestrate global oil production cuts. But some oil ministers said
they expected prices to stabilize near current levels.
   _A surge in imports caused Japan's merchandise trade surplus to
fall 7.2 percent to $94.3 billion in the 1987 fiscal year,
confirming the continuing strength of Japan's economy in spite of
the strong Japanese yen.
   _As part of its inflation-fighting program, Mexico said it would
hold the peso at its current value against the U.S. dollar until
the end of the year.
   _The United Auto Workers union and Chrysler Corp. reached a
tentative agreement on a two-year national labor contract,
patterned after pacts achieved by the other big automakers.
   _Sales of domestically made cars fell 6.7 percent in late April,
with Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. posting gains and General
Motors Corp. reporting a decline.
   _Eastern Airlines sued its pilots and machinists unions for $1.5
billion, accusing them of trying to destroy the carrier so they can
buy it at a ``bargain-basement price.'' A House panel urged the
government to broaden its probe of Eastern and parent, Texas Air
Corp.
   _Allegis spurned a new proposal from United Airlines pilots to
buy the airline for $4 billion.
   _Staley Continental Inc. rejected a sweetened $1.42 billion
takeover bid from British sugar producer Tate & Lyle PLC and said
it would consider other offers.
   _Gillette Co. said its shareholders narrowly rejected a bid by a
group of New York investors to replace four company directors and
seek a buyer for Gillette's personal care empire.
   _Desert Partners presented USG Corp. with new takeover proposals
valued at about $2.6 billion, seeking to head off a reorganization
plan by the building materials company.
   _A federal jury acquitted an Oklahoma oil contractor on charges
of scheming to defraud Continental Illinois National Bank & Trust
Co., but failed to reach a verdict on two bank executives charged
in the case.
   _Xerox Corp. marked the 50th anniversary of plain-paper copying
with a new line of products that includes its first personal
copier, made for Xerox by Japanese rival Sharp Corp.
   _Coleco Industries announced a wave of layoffs and the
resignation of its chairman as the toy maker sought to shore up its
sagging finances.
   _LTV Corp. unveiled a bankruptcy reorganization plan that keeps
the steel-aerospace giant largely intact but scales back its steel
operations.
   _RJR Nabisco Inc., the nation's largest cigarette manufacturer,
said it would begin test-marketing a nearly-smokeless cigarette in
the final three months of the year.
   _Kraft Inc. agreed to sell its Duracell battery division to a
group led by management and the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co. in a cash deal worth $1.8 billion.
   _Texaco Inc. sued Carl Icahn, its largest shareholder, over
alleged violations of federal securities laws. The suit seeks to
void Icahn's nominees for the Texaco board.
   _The government charged E.F. Hutton & Co. Inc. with conspiracy
and laundering at least $532,000 for organized crime figures and
businessmen who wanted to hide income from the Internal Revenue
Service.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
