<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
<HEAD>Fears of Gold Crash Offset By Market's Trendless Showing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be followed later in cycle with add containing week's
price trends.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   An authoritative forecast for growing supplies and slack demand
has many experts turning bearish on gold. But others say the gold
market's jaded reaction to recent economic indicators casts a cloud
over any long-range predictions.
   A new report _ ``Gold Crash: Risk or Reality?'' _ from the
respected Wefa Group and metals-and-mining consultant Resource
Strategies Inc. lays out the case for sharply lower gold prices.
   The researchers said steadily rising mine production and weak
investor demand will force prices down from current levels of
around $450 a troy ounce to $300 or $350 by the early 1990s and as
low as $250 a troy ounce within five years.
   ``Investors and portfolio managers should not have long
positions in gold at this time,'' the study warns.
   Chicago-based GNP Commodities is also forecasting a sharp drop
in gold prices, beginning next year, to as low as $350 a troy ounce.
   Critics of the Wefa report point out that gold prices have
traditionally responded more to economic factors _ especially
inflation fears _ than to supply factors. But even some of those
analysts foresee sharply lower gold prices.
   Peter Cardillo, commodity trading adviser for New York-based
Josephthal & Co., predicts a rapid decline in gold prices to under
$400 a troy ounce within the next month.
   Cardillo said he disagreed with the Wefa group's reasoning and
based his forecast on gold's high price relative to crude oil.
   He said a troy ounce of gold on New York's Commodity Exchange
traditionally costs about 18 times the price of a barrel of West
Texas Intermediate crude oil on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   He said he expected crude oil prices to average $20 a barrel
over the next two years. Using Cardillo's simple rule of thumb,
that would put gold at $360 a troy ounce.
   At the current price near $450, ``gold is somewhat overpriced,''
Cardillo said.
   He said the inflated gold price stemmed from overdone fears of
inflation.
   ``I think we will have an uptick in inflation but certainly not
anything to worry about,'' he said. ``I don't think we're headed
for a runaway inflation.''
   Inflation is the main engine of the gold market because gold
tends to hold its value during inflationary times.
   The Wefa group took the gold market's reluctance to rally on
recent inflationary indicators as a signal that investor enthusiasm
for gold is not as strong as it used to be.
   That may be true _ many analysts have noted a drop in investor
activity in all the financial markets since the stock market's
plunge in October.
   But gold prices also have refused to fall very far on
deflationary signals, making it difficult to mke any prediction
about future price movement, said David Syphen, vice president of
metals and foreign exchange trading for Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets Inc.
   Gold has traded within a range of $440 to $460 a troy ounce
since February.
   ``We seem to have a high degree of stability to the market right
now,'' Syphen said. ``It's just maintaining equilibrium for the
time being.''
   Reduced investor participation has left the gold market thin and
listless, and it could remain that way for some time, said Bette
Raptopoulos, metals analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``What I see is not a sharp decline nor a sharp move to the
upside, but rather buying at any lows, and some producer selling
when you get to the higher levels,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
