<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Jobless Figures Could Cast Shadow Over Treasury Refunding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No sooner did the edgy bond market get a dose of
good news this past week about the government's borrowing plans
than it got cold water splashed in its face by a new report on U.S.
unemployment.
   And analysts say the jobless data for April, which were widely
interpreted as showing underlying strength in the economy, could
cast a wide shadow over the Treasury's quarterly refunding in the
coming week by keeping bond prices depressed. The government plans
to sell $26 billion in new debt at three days of auctions for the
second quarter, and bond investors are looking ahead anxiously to
the sales.
   ``I don't like the prospects for the refunding following the
release of these (unemployment) data,'' said Robert Brusca, chief
economist and senior vice president of the fixed-income division at
Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.
   The Treasury announced Wednesday its plans for auctioning the
$26 billion in debt, which is down 3.7 percent from the refunding
auction in the first quarter. The reduction in public borrowing
cheered the bond market, since it means less downward pressure on
bond prices.
   Friday's unemployment report, however, was bad news for bond
prices and propelled interest rates higher.
   The Labor Department said the nation's jobless rate fell to 5.4
percent in April, the lowest since June 1974. A separate survey of
business payrolls showed a gain of 175,000 jobs, more than
one-fourth of them on factory assembly lines in industries that
have increased their exports in recent months.
   The economic robustness portrayed by the figures rekindled fears
that inflation could pick up, possibly spurring the Federal Reserve
to tighten interest rates in a bid to rein in growth.
   The price of the Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond tumbled
7-16 point Friday, or $4.38 for every $1,000 in face value. Its
yield, which moves in the opposite direction from its price, jumped
to 9.13 percent from 9.09 percent late Thursday.
   The unemployment report ``does nothing to allay the market's
concerns about a buildup in inflationary pressures,'' said William
Sullivan, director of money-market research for Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. ``It all points toward higher yields.''
   The bond market is fearful that investors _ especially the
Japanese _ could shy away from the Treasury auctions if they smell
a trend toward higher interest rates in the air. Japanese investors
are traditionally big buyers of U.S. government securities.
   A poor showing at the auctions of new government securities
would tend to depress prices of existing bonds. That is why some
analysts are viewing the sales as ``acid tests'' of bond supply
that could be difficult to digest.
   The Treasury plans to sell $8.75 billion in new three-year notes
on Tuesday, another $8.75 billion in 10-year notes on Wednesday and
$8.50 billion in 30-year bonds on Thursday.
   The $26 billion to be raised includes $9.5 billion in new cash
and $16.5 billion to pay off maturing debt.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
