<1ST_LINE>d f PM-BankBid     05-07 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid,0751</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Irving, Bank Of NY Both Optimistic About Proxy Battle Results</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seven-month cliffhanger for control of
Irving Bank Corp. has reached a climax, with both Irving and its
hostile suitor, Bank of New York Co., hinting at victory.
   But the final results of the shareholder vote completed at
Irving's annual meeting Friday won't be known until later this
month.
   Irving stockowners had to choose between a slate of 16 incumbent
directors that back a restructuring and friendly merger with Banca
Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy's second-largest bank, and nominees
from rival Bank of New York.
   Irving Chairman Joseph A. Rice, wearing a ``V for Victory'' pin
on his lapel, said Friday that he was optimistic about the vote.
``Why shouldn't I say we have this wrapped?'' he told a news
conference.
   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady also said, ``We are very
optimistic.''
   Although the results are not expected to be released before a
reconvened meeting May 24, both sides said they were confident
based on preliminary proxy counts and conversations with
institutional investors, which hold about two-thirds of Irving's
18.5 million common shares outstanding.
   Irving spokesman David Santos said early counts showed about
half of the 20 million voting shares, which included preferred
stock, were in favor of Irving's board. But he cautioned that it
was possible a number of those shares also were sent in duplicate
to Bank of New York.
   Banking analysts generally have given Bank of New York an edge
in the proxy battle, mostly because it already has secured the
necessary regulatory approvals from the Federal Reserve and New
York State Banking boards. Banca Commerciale, which is controlled
by the government agency Instituto per la Recostruzione
Industriale, has just begun the lengthy regulatory review process.
   Bank of New York, which owns a nearly 5 percent stake in Irving,
is offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its stock for each of
Irving's common shares. The offer is valued at about $63 a share or
$1.08 billion.
   Earlier this week, the company said that it held about 59
percent of Irving's common shares, including its own stake and
shares tendered to it. The bid expired on Friday, but Brady said
the company may decide to extend it on Monday.
   Banca Commerciale is offering $75 a share for 9.5 million Irving
shares, or about 51 percent, valued at $707 million. In addition,
it said it would pay shareholders interest on the purchase price
from May 31 until the deal closes.
   The Banca Commerciale bid is part of a complex restructuring
plan that includes asset sales such as Irving's 50-story Wall
Street headquarters, cost-cutting measures and a $10-a-share
special cash dividend. Irving said the offer has a blended value of
between $65.20 and $72.55 a share.
   Irving shares fell 37.5 cents to $60, while Bank of New York
rose 12.5 cents to $30.25 in New York Stock Exchange trading Friday.
   Some of the approximately 1,200 shareholders that packed the
annual meeting Friday expressed mixed feelings about either offer,
and many said they were angered that Irving had not obtained a
better deal.
   ``There's no question in my mind that the Bank of New York is
trying to steal your bank,'' said Robert Strougo, a New York
attorney representing 1,600 voting shares. ``There's no reason why
this bank couldn't be sold for in excess of $100 a share.''
   Bank of New York offered Irving a cash-and-stock deal valued at
around $1.4 billion when it first made its rare hostile bid seven
months ago, but it lowered its offer twice following the Oct. 19
stock market crash.
   Irving has staunchly resisted Bank of New York's advances. Among
its many defenses was to activate its ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
defense, which is intended to make any hostile buyout prohibitively
expensive.
   Rice said representatives from his bank and the Bank of New York
met as recently as two weeks ago but had no plans to resume talks.
In the meantime, he said, the company would continue to welcome
offers from other potential suitors.
   ``We are in discussion with anyone who will talk with us,'' he
told reporters. ``We're willing to consider the best proposition
from anybody ... (because) we are dealing with a situation that was
thrust upon us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
