<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     05-07 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Rise, Crude Up 35 Cents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices have risen in reaction to an expected
rise in demand and fears of a U.S. supply squeeze caused by a major
refinery fire.
   The rise on Friday was magnified by short-covering, a
price-boosting occurrence caused by traders who repurchase borrowed
oil they had sold earlier on the hunch that prices would fall.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate crude oil rose 35 cents per 42-gallon barrel to
close at $17.74.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale
unleaded gasoline rose .91 cent a gallon to 51.52 cents, and
wholesale heating oil rose .85 cent a gallon to 47.42 cents.
   Traders said predictions of a rising demand for petroleum,
caused partly by the impending summer driving season and a growing
domestic economy, was one reason for the rise in prices.
   They also said an explosion at a Shell Oil Co. refinery in
Norco, La., which helped boost prices Thursday, continued to buoy
the market Friday. Although the facility produces a miniscule
fraction of total consumption, some traders said the explosion
could disrupt the flow of supplies from the Gulf Coast.
   As with most one-day price moves, no trend emerged for the oil
market, which has been volatile largely because of failed efforts
by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to restrict
output and stabilize prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880507-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-07-88 0613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     05-07 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unemployment Slips, Consumer Debt Rises, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lost ground for the week, ending with its third
consecutive daily loss as traders worried that the strength evident
in the April unemployment report could lead to higher interest
rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 12.77 points on
Friday to close at 2,007.46, bringing its loss for the week to
24.87 points.
   Before trading opened, the government said the unemployment rate
fell to 5.4 percent in April. Later in the day, it reported
consumer installment debt grew by $4.46 billion in March.
   The drop in the unemployment rate, down from 5.6 percent in
March, left it at the lowest level since June 1974.
   The number of Americans at work rose by 606,000 last month while
those listed as unemployed fell by 191,000 to 6.6 million, the
Labor Department said.
   It said the average hourly wage nationwide in April rose a
nickel to $9.22 for an average annual increase of 5.6 percent.
   Some private analysts said the tighter labor market is bound to
push wages up soon and exert inflationary pressures on prices as
well.
   Donald Ratajczak, head of the Georgia State University Economic
Forecasting Project, said ``606,000 new jobs is far above what
anyone expected.''
   ``At other times, we would be happy about that kind of decrease
in unemployment, but at this stage in the cycles, we are nervous.
It may be too strong for the economy,'' Ratajczak said at a meeting
in Atlanta.
   But other economists said the wage gains are still not big
enough to trigger a tightening of credit by the Federal Reserve
Board through higher interest rates in an effort to cool off the
economy.
   ``The fears of an inflationary boom are overstated,'' said
Lawrence Chimerine, president of the Wefa Group of Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., an economic consulting firm.
   In the report on consumer credit, the Federal Reserve Board said
consumer installment debt grew by $4.46 billion in March, a strong
annual rate of growth of 8.6 percent.
   The Fed said consumer debt grew a 10.3 percent annual rate for
the first three months of the year, compared with 7.2 percent for
all of 1987.
   Seprately, a business information group reportyed that
businesses placed slightly more help-wanted advertisements in March
than they did in February.
   The Conference Board said its seasonally adjusted Help Wanted
Advertising Index rose 3 points in March to 159. The index measures
the volume of classified advertising in 51 major newspapers around
the nation.
</TEXT>
