<HEAD>Allied Stores Corp. President Resigns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allied Stores Corp. President Robert H. Morosky,
who was expected to become chairman of Federated Department Stores
Inc. after its merger with Campeau Corp., has agreed to resign,
Campeau said in a surprise announcement.
   Campeau said late Friday its chairman, Robert Campeau, would
serve as chairman of both Allied and Federated for the foreseeable
future.
   The statement said Robert Campeau would hold both positions ``in
light of the size and importance to Campeau Corp. of its
acquisition of Federated.''
   However, the suddenness of the announcement raised the question
of a dispute between the two men.
   Morosky was not at home when a reporter called for comment late
Friday.
   It has been widely assumed the Morosky would be named chairman
of Federated and Allied. At a news conference last month, several
days after Robert Campeau won a two-month-long takeover battle for
Federated, he introduced Morosky as the ``president and chief
executive of Federated.''
   Both men talked then about their plans for Federated, and
Morosky has visited Federated's headquarters and divisions.
   The statement from the Toronto-based Campeau said Robert Campeau
and Morosky were discussing the possibility of Morosky's remaining
a consultant on distribution, expansion and overseas office.
   Those areas have been Morosky's strong suit. Before being hired
by Campeau last November, he had spent 15 years at Limited Inc.,
the apparel retailer. As Limited's vice chairman, Morosky, 46,
developed the distribution and inventory system that helped that
company's rapid expansion.
   He left Limited in the summer of 1987, reportedly because of a
dispute with company chairman, Leslie Wexner.
   During Campeau's battle with R.H. Macy & Co. Inc. for Federated,
many Wall Street analysts, looking back at Morosky's tenure at
Limited, said they feared he would transform Federated's diverse
divisions into a group of look-alike stores.
   The Campeau Corp. statement said Robert Campeau expected to name
a new chief executive officer for Federated and Allied within 30
days.
   Control of Federated passed to Campeau earlier this week when
the Canadian developer announced it had accepted more than 87
million shares tendered by the retailer's stockholders.
   The merger between Federated and Campeau is expected to be
completed in about a month.
   Several Federated divisions have been sold to finance the
Campeau acquisition, and others are expected to go on the block.
Campeau is retaining the Bloomingdale's, Lazarus, Burdine's,
Abraham & Straus, Rich's and Goldsmith's department store divisions
and Ralphs supermarkets.
   Allied Stores, which Campeau took over in 1986, now comprises
Stern's, Ann Taylor, Maas Brothers and Jordan Marsh and Bon stores.
Most of Allied's store divisions also have been sold.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
